<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0637,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with attack. No pickup.</HEAD>
<UNK>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked the
1st Army Brigade headquarters Thursday evening with
rocket-propelled grenades and rifle fire, and combat raged through
the capital for more than an hour.
   Col. Orlando Zepeda, commander of the brigade, told journalists
six rebels were killed in the fighting, which panicked thousands of
residents of the city's northern sector. He said five militarized
National Police, one army soldier and three civilians were wounded.
   The fighting was the heaviest in the capital in at least a year.
   Zepeda said four men aboard a jeep fired U.S.-made M-69 grenades
and Soviet-made RPG-18 rocket-propelled grenades into the brigade
headquarters at dusk.
   He said six or seven projectiles landed inside the base
perimeter, causing property damage but no casualties.
   The brigade commander said combat in the neighborhoods of
Zacamil, Mejicanos and around the headquarters of Transit Police
broke out after police and soldiers clashed with retreating
guerrillas. He estimated about 30 insurgents took part in the
attack.
   Rebel spokespersons called several local radio stations to say
the strike comprised coordinated attacks on four military and
police posts. The rebels said the actions was part of an offensive
called ``All against Arena. We're Going to Win.''
   President-elect Alfredo Cristiani of the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, is to take office from outgoing
Christian Democrat Jose Napoleon Duarte on June 1.
   Earlier Thursday, the rebels declared a natiowide transport ban
for the inauguration.
   ``We call on all our units to enforce the ban and the people to
observe it in repudiation of this government from the moment of its
inception,'' said a communique issued by the high command of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN.
   The indefinite ban is to begin at 12:01 a.m. May 31. Previous
transport bans have lasted an average of three days.
   An estimated 7,000 Marxist-led guerrillas are waging a
9-year-old revolution against the U.S.-backed government. The war
has killed about 70,000 people, most of them civilians.
   The rebels periodically call transport bans and enforce them
with threats and sabotage. The previous ban, during the March 19
presidential election, virtually paralyzed interprovincial
transport.
</TEXT>
