<FIRST>r a PM-CoincidingLives     05-25 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coinciding Lives,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Born And Died Hours Apart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORESVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people born hours apart died
within 4{ hours of each other in traffic accidents 270 miles apart.
   Jacqueline Johns Wiatrek and Billy Wayne Mutz were born Oct. 7,
1966, in a San Antonio hospital. Their mothers shared a room and
the same doctor handled the deliveries.
   Nineteen years later, they graduated together from Floresville
High School.
   Last weekend, they died.
   Mrs. Wiatrek, 22, and her 29-year-old husband, Richard, were
killed instantly in a head-on collision Saturday evening in the
Dallas suburb of Mesquite.
   Mutz died in a crash 4{ hours later when he lost control of his
pickup on a curving farm road near Floresville, southeast of San
Antonio.
   ``I was taking it so hard, but when I found out that Jacqueline
had died too, it struck me as a sign from God,'' Elizabeth Mutz
said Tuesday after her son was laid to rest in St. Ann's Cemetery
in Kosciusko.
   Funeral services for the Wiatreks were held Wednesday in
Elmendorf.
   Mrs. Wiatrek's mother, Rosie Johns, said she didn't hear about
Mutz's death until Monday.
   ``We went to the funeral home to make arrangements and saw some
of the Mutz family there,'' she said.
   ``I asked ``Who did you lose?' and they said it was Billy
Wayne,'' said Mrs. Johns. ``I said, ``Oh my gosh' and went to hug
his mother. We talked about what happiness we'd both had at the
same time 22 years ago.''
   Mrs. Mutz said the two women had been friends as had their
mothers, but that they'd lost touch with each other until they
arrived in the hospital to deliver their babies.
   ``We hadn't seen each other in a while, and then there we were
having the same doctor deliver our babies on the same day.''
</TEXT>
