<FIRST>u a AM-PanPacific-Fire 2ndLd-Writethru a0401 05-25 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Pacific-Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0401,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auditorium Burns in Spectacular Blaze Visible Across City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with arson suspected, details; no pickup.
ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIC LEYVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire destroyed the vacant Pan Pacific
Auditorium on Wednesday night in a spectacular sunset blaze that
sent a column of black smoke more than 1,000 feet into the air that
was visible at least 35 miles away.
   ``The entire structure is engulfed,'' said Fire Department
spokesman Jim Williamson.
   Fire officials said the fire might have been sparked by
transients at the huge, art deco-style sports arena and exhibition
hall five miles west of downtown.
   Flames burned through the roof of the building, which was built
during the Depression by the Works Project Administration and
provided a stage for such performers as Sonja Henie and Elvis
Presley.
   ``There's not gonna be much left, if they ever put it out,''
said Elsie Cutler, who watched as 150 firefighters battled the
blaze.
   Flames shot more than 100 feet into the air, and the smoke was
visible in Malibu 35 miles west of downtown, witnesses said.
   The fire was reported shortly after 7 p.m., Williamson said.
   Firefighters dumped water on the blaze from three-story-high
elevated cranes.
   ``The roof is pretty much gone,'' said Deputy Fire Chief Greg
Drummond.
   Drummond said the fire appeared to have broken out in the
southwest corner of the 150-foot-by-300-foot building and quickly
spread through the structure.
   Assistant Fire Chief Tony Ennis said he doubted the building
could be salvaged.
   ``I think it could be arson,'' Ennis said. ``But it will be
several days before we determine that.''
</TEXT>
