<FIRST>u i AM-Japan 2ndLd-Writethru a0792 05-25 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0792,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister to Testify in Scandal Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with Nakasone beginning testimony.
Picks up 4th pvs, `According to ...' EDITS thereafter to conform. ^By ERIC
TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone said in
long-awaited testimony to Parliament Thursday that he is ``totally
innocent'' of opposition charges that he was linked to the Recruit
influence-peddling scandal.
   Nakasone spoke under oath in the Budget Committee of the House
of Representatives, and his words were broadcast live nationwide
though with only a still photo. By law live television broadcasts
are banned from testimony of special witnesses in Parliament.
   ``I am totally innocent,'' the former prime minster said in his
opening statement. ``I refused to testify earlier because I have
never done anything wrong.''
   After his statement, he faced questioning by opposition parties
that was to continue for over two hours.
   Meanwhile, support for the governing Liberal Democratic Party
appeared at an all-time low.
   According to a survey of 2,280 eligible voters conducted May
20-21 by the mass-circulation Yomiuri Shimbum, support for the
Liberal Democrats stands at just 26.5 percent, the lowest since its
founding in 1955, while combined support for five opposition
parties stands at 26.7 percent. The survey said 44.1 percent of
those polled supported no party.
   ``We hope that this testimony before Parliament will not be the
end of the matter,'' and that Nakasone ``will resign from
Parliament and maybe take some others with him,'' said Seiji
Masamori of the Communist Party.
   Masamori and four other opposition lawmakers questioned Nakasone
in a session scheduled to last 2 hours, 20 minutes, with the time
given each determined by his party's number of seats. The committee
chairman, of the governing Liberal Democrats, also was to be
allowed time for questions.
   For months, the opposition has demanded testimony in Parliament
from Nakasone, who was prime minister at the time of dubious stock
deals and large contributions to politicians by the Recruit Co., an
information and publishing conglomerate.
   The Liberal Democrats refused until last week, calling the
demands ``improper'' because of Nakasone's status as a former prime
minister.
   A long opposition boycott of debate on the budget finally
changed that.
   Liberal Democrats forced the budget through the House of
Representatives last month, but widespread criticism resulted and a
deal was made: The opposition would not boycott the budget in the
upper house if Nakasone testified before the budget committee.
   Prosecutors have arrested 14 bureaucrats and businessmen so far
on charges involving bribery and violations of securities laws, and
have filed charges aginst two members of Parliament.
   Recruit sold unlisted shares in a subsidiary to scores of people
prominent in government and business, including at least 17
politicians or their aides. The buyers made large profits when the
shares went on public sale.
   Eleven of the 17 were members of Nakasone's Cabinet, and
opposition leaders claim he was a central figure in the scandal.
Nakasone, prime minister in 1983-87, has acknowledged his aides
bought 29,000 shares and said the profits were used for political
activities.
   One of the lawmakers against whom bribery charges were filed
Monday was Takao Fujinami, a Nakasone lieutenant and former chief
Cabinet secretary.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, Nakasone's finance minister and
successor, has said he will resign to take responsibility for the
Recruit scandal.
   National newspapers reported last weekend that Nakasone would
resign from Parliament, but an official of his party faction said
privately: ``There is no truth to the reports. Mr. Nakasone said he
inends to continue as a legislator, although in the face of
adversity.''
   Tsuruo Yamaguchi, secretary-general of the Socialist Party, the
largest opposition group, has accused Nakasone of doing Recruit a
special favor that involved ordering Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Co. and the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications to buy
multimillion-dollar U.S. supercomputers.
   Two of the supercomputers made by Cray Research Inc. were resold
to Recruit and helped establish it in leasing computer time and
related telecommunications services.
   Hisashi Shinto, former chairman of Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone, which was a government monopoly until 1985, was arrested
and accused of taking bribes from Recruit in the form of the
bargain stock shares.
   The opposition also wants to know whether Nakasone recommended
Hiromasa Ezoe, founder and former chairman of Recruit, for
membership on several government advisory committees.
</TEXT>
