<FIRST>r i PM-China-Trek     05-25 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Trek,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Student's Long March to Tiananmen Square</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To get to Tiananmen Square, Ji Xiujie took three
trains, blocked railroad tracks for hours with his classmates,
bounced along in a bus and threatened a police officer with a
beating.
   But the student from Chongqing, an industrial city about 1,100
miles from Beijing, finally made it to the heart of China's
month-long student movement for freedom.
   ``I will tell my children about this with pride,'' said the
20-year-old junior from Chongqing University surrounded by his
classmates under a makeshift styrofoam tent. ``I have come to
Beijing to take part in a great revolution.''
   Ji is one of tens of thousands of students from outside Beijing
who made the long march to the capital to demonstrate for a more
democratic China and the resignation of Premier Li Peng and senior
leader Deng Xiaoping.
   The students' presence in Beijing has given the movement a boost
now that thousands of others in the capital have retuned to their
schools, exhausted after sleeping for 10 days on concrete.
   Indeed, the out-of-towners now make up more than half of the
students on the square, student leaders say.
   Many traveled across the country for free because train clerks
and ticket sellers also support the movement. Now they live on the
good graces of Beijing residents who bring them noodles and steamed
bread, and man the blockades keeping army troops out of the city.
   Their travels have echoes in China's recent past. During the
ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution, hundreds of thousands of
students took to the road to visit the revolutionary sites. For
many, the experiences on the road as Red Guards were formative ones.
   For Ji, his travels to Beijing play the same role.
   Ji and about 30 classmates started their trek to Beijing on
Friday night, a day before Premier Li Peng ordered a martial law
crackdown in Beijing to suppress the movement.
   ``By the time we left there was a news blackout on the movement
throughout all of China,'' Ji said. ``We just had to know what was
going on.''
   On Sunday, they arrived in Loyang in Henan province, but police
on orders to keep protesters from coming to Beijing forced them
onto a train returning to Chongqing.
   They got off a few stops later and rented a mini-bus to head
back to Loyang to get a train to Beijing.
   ``A police officer came to the bus station and said we couldn't
go,'' Ji said. ``We pleaded with him but he refused to give in.''
   Finally, the Sichuan students threatened him with a thrashing
and he let them go. ``That was very satisfying,'' Shi Zhifen, a
Sichuan classmate, said with a smile.
   In Loyang, they boarded another train, but it was stopped in
Anyang, another Henan city.
   ``Police threw all the students off,'' said Ji.
   Thousands of students then began a demonstration in the station,
lying on the railroad tracks for seven hours until just before dawn
Sunday. The railroad office relented.
   ``We had shut down the whole railyard. There was nothing they
could do,'' Ji said.
   The band arrived victoriously in Beijing on Monday.
   ``I haven't taken off my clothes in five days,'' Ji said as he
batted at a fly under the styrofoam roof. ``But my spirit is
strong. We will stay here until the government falls.''
   Qian Jin and her classmates from Yunnan University didn't have
any problems traveling from Kunming, capital of faraway Yunnan
province, until they neared Beijing.
   ``We heard rumors that police were throwing students off trains
at the next station,'' said the 21-year-old senior, her face burned
by the sun. ``So we got off and started to walk.''
   A day later, on Tuesday, they arrived in the city.
   ``My feet are still blistered,'' the English major said as she
sat under a 3-foot-high tent. ``But I am proud to be here.''
   Bao Shu from Qingdao, on the Pacific coast, remembered the tales
his father told of his days as traveling Red Guard during the
1966-76 Cultural Revolution.
   ``He covered the whole country,'' said the 18-year-old student
from Ocean University. ``He met my mother on the road, too.''
   Although Bao's ideals are different from those of his parents,
who at the time sought a radically communist society, he said he
understands the excitement they felt.
   ``Coming here I felt for the first time that China has hope,''
he said. ``I know what my parents felt then.''
</TEXT>
