<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-25 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down in Tokyo, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was moderately lower against the
Japanese yen Thursday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
35.21 points the previous day, added another 153.57 points, or 0.45
percent, to end at 34,005.39 points.
   The dollar finished trading at 142.35 yen, down 0.65 yen from
Wednesday's close of 143 yen. Opening at 142.60 yen, the currency
ranged between 141.45 yen and 142.60 yen.
   ``Japanese investors, including trading houses and securities
firms, sold the dollar for profit taking all at once,'' said an
analyst with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``After such a sharp rise of the dollar, everybody's selling it
now to collect profits,'' he said.
   The trader said the dollar's downswing followed its trend in New
York Wednesday, where market players sold the currency after
President Bush's comment that the dollar's recent sharp rise was
not favorable. It closed at 142.90 yen on Wall Street.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the Nikkei rose as the yen
started to recover against the dollar.
   Uncertainties over the foreign exchange market and over a
possible discount rate hike remain in the stock market, making
trading less active, the dealer said.
   Market sources and media reports have been speculating the Bank
of Japan will soon raise official discount rate by at least 0.5
percent from the current 2.5 percent. So far, the monetary
authorities have not made official comments on the rate hike.
</TEXT>
