<DOCNO> AP890525-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HouseEthics     05-25 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House Ethics,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel is Told Congress Can Ban Honoraria, Raise Pay, and Survive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a House ethics task force have been
told that members of Congress can ban honoraria, raise their pay
and still survive politically to serve another term.
   ``Why don't you just do it? You're not going to lose your
seats,'' Lloyd N. Cutler, the chairman of a now-defunct
presidential pay commission, testified Wednesday before the
eight-member panel studying changes in House ethics rules.
   Cutler, White House counsel in the Carter administration, even
suggested how lawmakers could accomplish the politically risky
task: Vote this year for a package to abolish honoraria and
increase pay by an equal amount, make the change effective in
January 1991, and take the case to the voters next year.
   ``It's a risk, but it's a principled stand. If the public
decides that it prefers the finest Congress that other people's
money can buy, I should think you would not wish to be a member of
that kind of a Congress,'' Cutler said.
   Cutler testified only days after House and Senate members
disclosed they earned more than $8.7 million in honoraria last
year, mostly from speeches to special interest groups.
   The chairman of the former Commission on Executive, Legislative
and Judicial Salaries, Cutler referred to special interest payments
of speaking fees as ``dishonoraria'' and ``a totally indefensible
practice.''
   The system ``comes very close to government for sale, at least
legislation for sale,'' Cutler said.
   Cutler's commission recommended, and former President Reagan
proposed, that Congress this year raise its pay 51 percent while
abolishing honoraria.
   After a public outcry that included a campaign against the raise
by radio talk show hosts across the nation, the House voted 380-48
and the Senate 94-6 last February to defeat the pay plan. Cutler
recalled receiving a letter during the debate that said, ``The only
thing worse than a public official is a child molester.''
   Before the plan collapsed, a bipartisan group of House leaders
had worked out broad outlines for a proposal that would have
abolished honoraria in return for more pay and instituted other
ethics reforms.
   After the whole package was dropped, Speaker Jim Wright
appointed the eight-member task force to conduct a long-term ethics
review, and divided the panel's membership equally between the two
parties, with Reps. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., and Lynn Martin, R-Ill.,
as co-chairs.
   Cutler also suggested that Congress end the current restrictions
on amounts of outside earned income that members can receive, and
move instead to establish categories of outside earnings that would
be permitted or prohibited.
   Examples of ``harmless'' outside earnings that should be
allowed, he said, could include income from writing books.
   Currently, rank-and-file House members can retain 30 percent of
their $89,500 salaries, or $26,850 in earned outside income.
Senators can keep 40 percent, or $35,800. There is no restriction
on unearned income such as investment earnings.
   Edward S.G. Dennis, chief of the Justice Department's criminal
division, and former Sen. Charles McC. Mathias Jr., R-Md., told the
task force that the same ethics rules should be applied to all
three branches of government unless there are valid reasons for
exceptions. Ethics provisions currently are far more stringent in
some areas for top executive branch officials than for members of
Congress.
   President Bush has proposed legislation that would revise ethics
laws and would extend many provisions to lawmakers for the first
time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
