<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RavenKill     05-25 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Raven Kill,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bureau To Kill Tortoise-eating Ravens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALIFORNIA CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 1,500 ravens are
targeted for execution to protect Mojave Desert tortoises, which
are too slow to escape the birds' hunting prowess.
   Hundreds of tortoise shells stacked next to some raven nests
help the U.S. Bureau of Land Management to identify 200 to 300
ravens that habitually feast on young tortoises.
   In a pilot program to protect the tortoises, the agency began
killing the birds last week at one site, and two more sites are
being prepared for the four-month kill.
   The agency said up to 1,500 ravens could be killed if it saves
enough tortoises. In recent years, ravens have been killing a
disproportionate number of tortoises.
   In spots, ravens are responsible for 85 percent of young
tortoise deaths, said agency wildlife biologist Ted Rado.
   Once rare in the desert 125 miles northeast of Los Angeles, the
ravens now number between 10,000 and 12,000 _ 15 times their 1968
population.
   Officials have prepared for the raven kill by getting the birds
accustomed to a diet of hard-boiled eggs. At the appointed hour,
the eggs are laced with Starlicide, a poison originally used to
kill European starlings.
   ``We've gone to great pains to absolutely minimize the
poisoning'' of non-target animals, Rado said.
   The eggs are wired to a platform and removed at night. Officials
said Starlicide breaks down into non-toxic compounds so the dead
ravens will pose no threat to wildlife higher in the food chain.
   Other ravens will be shot with rifles, which Rado suspects will
prove a less successful method. He said the birds will likely learn
quickly to steer clear of humans.
</TEXT>
