<FIRST>r i PM-China-Rumors     05-25 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Rumors,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Struggle Heats Up, Rumors Take Over</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters in Shanghai and the northwestern
cities of Xian and Lanzhou staged funerals last week for students
who died in Beijing during a hunger strike for freedom and
democracy.
   The somber Shanghai procession featured huge wreaths of flowers
to remember comrades in Beijing that an epitath said were
``sacrificed for democracy.''
   The only problem: nobody died.
   Without a free press at a time of great social and political
turmoil, China has been taken over by rumors.
   From student loudspeakers, official government sources,
journalists and the man on the street, the flow of hints and
innuendoes is unceasing.
   Sometimes the rumors are created to sully an enemy or aid a
friend. Sometimes it seems all of Beijing is playing a gigantic
game of ``telephone,'' with no goal other than the passing of
strange information.
   Chinese with a political ax to grind are putting out false or
distorted information to benefit whichever faction they support.
Others, reveling in their life on the inside track, are relaying
the stories with all the glee of small-town gossips.
   The situation is so bad the government outlawed rumor-mongering
in Beijing when it declared martial law on Saturday.
   Widespread student rumors included an imminent attack on
Tiananmen Square, which student protesters have occupied, by
paratroopers and the electrification of subway grates by
authorities.
   But the rumors are not confined to the student movement.
   Within one week, various sources reported that Communist Party
chief Zhao Ziyang had resigned, returned to power and then was
forced out again.
   Other rumors said Premier Li Peng and three other conservatives
had seized power. Then there was the story that Li and senior
leader Deng Xiaoping had stepped down and that President Yang
Shangkun, a former general, was poised to stage a coup.
   A government source said someone he know in the State Council,
China's Cabinet, told him Li had resigned and that the resignation
would be broadcast on state-run television that night.
   ``I called the TV station and a friend there started laughing.
It just wasn't true but this thing came from the State Council,''
he said.
   Zhang Weiguo, a reporter on the World Economic Herald, a
relatively liberal newspaper based in Shanghai, said the rumor mill
shows how badly China needs a freer press.
   ``People are learning about major government changes and about
the biggest student movement in China's history from popsicle
sellers and newspaper dealers,'' he said. ``This is not a way to
inform the people.''
   Indeed, after several days in early May when the official media
gave lively objective reports about the student movement, the press
has returned to somber reporting, pockmarked with an occasional
shrill editorial calling for stability.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     05-25 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Legislation Clears Another Hurdle, Thanks to Liberal Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush once again is relying on
liberal Democrats to protect his savings and loan bill from attacks
by members of his own party.
   The legislation cleared another hurdle Wednesday on its way to
the House floor for a vote next month. But a GOP amendment that
critics said would have ``crippled'' Bush's proposal to make S&amp;L
owners put up more of their own money narrowly escaped passage by a
17-17 tie, promising future challenges.
   ``We have no illusions that we'll have to fight the capital
issue again, again and again,'' said Assistant Treasury Secretary
David Mullins, the administration's point man for keeping Bush's
package intact. ``It's like one of those cheap movies; the monster
keeps coming back.''
   Bush and other critics have blamed thrift operators' risky and
often fraudulent lending, using federally guaranteed deposits
without exposing much of their own money to possible losses, for
the $90 billion hole in the government S&amp;L insurance fund that
necessitated the bailout.
   ``In the past, this industry has repeatedly won capital fights
in the Congress,'' Mullins said. ``That's one of the reasons we're
here today.''
   The legislation, as approved by the House Banking Committee and
the Senate and endorsed by Bush, would require S&amp;L owners to put
$1.50 of their own money at risk for every $100 of federally
insured deposits they lend.
   Under the House banking panel's version, that hard-cash capital
requirement would rise to $3 for every $100 in outstanding loans by
June 1990.
   The latest assault on the proposal came from an amendment by
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., during the House Judiciary Committee's
consideration of the bill.
   The measure would make federal regulators go through a lengthy
series of hearings before imposing the proposed new standards on
about 450 S&amp;Ls that enjoy so-called ``supervisory good will''
exemptions from the current capital requirements.
   Federal regulators granted the exemptions in the early 1980s to
then-healthy institutions that agreed to take over and absorb the
losses of unhealthy S&amp;Ls to minimize payouts from the federal
insurance fund.
   Hyde argued that it's unfair to ``change the rules in the middle
of the game.'' He warned that 152 institutions will have to be
considered insolvent unless they are permitted to continue counting
good will as capital.
   ``You're taking institutions that are treading water and headed
toward shore and you're drowning them,'' he said. ``My amendment
says ... you get a chance at due process before we hold the
funeral. I'm trying to make an honest lady out of my government.''
   However, defenders of Bush's proposal argued that capital has no
more value than air in insulating the insurance fund and taxpayers
from poor lending practices.
   ``The capital standards the president proposed and are in this
bill are our insurance policy,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
``This amendment would cripple the bill and make it a
laughingstock.''
   Eleven of the committee's 14 Republicans and six Democrats
supported Hyde's amendment _ one vote shy of the simple majority
needed for approval. Three Republicans and 14 Democrats voted no,
while the committee's chairman, Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas,
abstained.
   ``Strong capital survived,'' Mullins rejoiced afterwards.
   But Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, who as chairman of the
House Banking Committee has been the administration's main
legislative spear carrier on the capital issue, was worried about
the closeness of the call.
   ``The vote ... points to the need for more work to let members
know the seriousness of the problem before the legislation reaches
the floor,'' said Gonzalez.
   In other action, the judiciary committee adopted an amendment
offered by Rep. William J. Hughes, D-N.J., that he said was
designed to avoid a court challenge of civil penalties for bank and
S&amp;L fraud.
   The Bush administration had proposed maximum civil fines for
fraud by individuals and institutions of $1 million a day for any
one violation, up to a total of $5 million.
   Hughes' measure cutting in half the maximum for individuals
passed by a 17-14 vote. But the committee later adopted his
subsequent proposal throwing out the caps for both individuals and
institutions, but limited the penalty to double any loss and
expense to the government.
   The committee defeated by voice vote an attempt by Hughes to
halve the maximum proposed jail term for financial institution
fraud from 20 years to 10 years.
</TEXT>
