<FIRST>r i PM-China-Corruption     05-25 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Corruption,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anger Over Corruption Has Brought Many Into Streets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The struggle to rid China of official corruption
has been a galvanizing force behind the phenomenal outpouring of
support for the pro-democracy student movement.
   Bespectacled office workers and elderly women in baggy trousers
say they are all for democratic reform, but what really angers them
is nepotism and ``guandao,'' the official corruption they must deal
with every day.
   ``Mao sent his son to Korea, Deng sends his children to
America,'' goes one popular slogan, which by the contrast accuses
today's Communist Party leaders of furthering their own interests
instead of serving the public.
   One of Mao Tse-tung's sons died in the Korean War, while several
of senior leader Deng Xiaoping's children have had extended stays
in the United States.
   Ordinary Chinese view with helplessness and rage the power of
high officials to send their sons and daughters abroad, obtain good
housing and cars and buy amenities.
   Common people often cannot buy a train ticket or a good
television unless they know the right people. The ``back door'' is
the most common entrance for getting many goods and services, and
everything comes with a price, ranging from ``gifts'' of cigarettes
and free meals to cash bribes.
   Officials' access to sought-after goods has made them
susceptible to bribery. Many consider receiving money, lavish
banquets, color television sets or stereos all part of the job.
   Newspapers regularly report how officials stockpile scarce goods
such as fertilizer and steel, buying them up at artificially low
state-set prices and selling them for huge profits on the free
market.
   Despite a government crackdown last year, many officials still
use their positions to set up companies that distribute _ for a
healthy profit _ hard-to-get raw materials and resources.
   One of the first posters to go up at Beijing University during
the student upheaval listed several dozen senior officials who it
alleged got their jobs because of family connections.
   Premier Li Peng, it noted, was the adopted son of the late Chou
En-lai. People's Liberation Army Chief of Staff Chi Haotian is
President Yang Shangkun's son-in-law.
   A recent survey of 10,000 workers found that 46 percent listed
corruption as China's most serious social problem and 63 percent
said improper deeds by party members was a major political problem.
   Chinese courts handled 37,000 cases of official profiteering
last year, up 50 percent from 1987, and 101 embezzlers and
bribe-takers were sentenced to death or life imprisonment.
   Local governments have set up neighborhood centers where
ordinary people can report official abuses of power without fear of
recrimination.
   But most agree that corruption is here to stay until China
alleviates imbalances in supply and demand and closes the wide gap
between subsidized state-set and free market prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
