<FIRST>r a PM-Fulton-Okla     05-25 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fulton-Okla,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Official's Nomination for Federal Job Threatened</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Loyd in 15th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state official whose nomination for a top
federal post has run into trouble with anti-abortion forces spent a
rocky 4{ years as head of the Oklahoma's largest agency before
switching jobs.
   Robert Fulton took over as director of the state's Department of
Human Services amid controversy and left as criticism of his
administration grew in the Legislature.
   His critics questioned his administrative capabilities and
accused him of replacing a legislative patronage system with a one
of his own.
   Fulton's supporters say he is a hard worker gifted in putting
together programs and obtaining federal dollars. But one backer
said he is an eternal optimist prone to promise more than he can
deliver.
   For the past two years, he has been social services secretary, a
member of Gov. Henry Bellmon's cabinet serving as liaison with
Human Services.
   Fulton, 57, had a long federal career before coming to Oklahoma,
working for five agencies over 21 years, including the U.S. Senate
Budget Committee.
   Now, U.S. Health and Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan
wants him to return to Washington to head the Family Services
Administration, which manages major welfare programs.
   But his nomination has come under attack by some conservative
Republican senators because of a old policy at an Oklahoma state
hospital regarding the treatment of infants with crippling spina
bifada.
   Fulton was named as a defendant in a 1985 lawsuit alleging that
from 1977 to 1983 several babies born with the severe spinal defect
were denied live-saving surgery at the state hospital.
   Fulton said the deaths occurred before he became Human Services
director in 1983 and he took steps to improve treatment for spina
bifida babies. He was recently dropped as a defendant.
   In a recent interview, he said anti-abortion forces ``have their
axes out for Louis Sullivan and I've become their symbol.'' He said
he couldn't change their minds if ``I laid down in front of 15
abortion clinics across the country.''
   Sullivan's own nomination ran afoul of anti-abortion advocates
when he indicated in an interview earlier this year that he
personally opposed abortion but favored women's right to choose.
   Fulton had a difficult task ahead of him when he came to
Oklahoma to succeed the late L.E. Rader, who ruled the Department
of Human Services with an iron fist from its infancy and was
considered one of the state's most powerful figures.
   ``He was an institution,'' said Fulton. ``I didn't go in and
purge Rader people because that is not my style. I thought my job
was to be something of a healer and I tried to do that.
   ``But I was obviously not a Loyd Rader. I could not play those
games with the Legislature like he could and I ran into some flak.''
   His 4{ years as Human Services director covered a time of severe
budget restraints caused by a collapse in the oil industry in 1983.
   State Sen. Bernest Cain, chairman of the Senate Human Services
Committee, said Fulton is ``is brilliant in understanding the
interaction of state and federal programs and dollars.''
   ``He also was an extreme optimist,'' Cain said.
   He said Fulton's optimism may have led him to tell legislators
that he could get by on less funding than the agency really needed
``and that caused some problems.''
   A few months after Fulton took over the post, a huge revenue
shortfall hit state government, forcing cutbacks at Human Services.
   In the next two years, the work force was slashed from about
14,500 to about 12,500.
</TEXT>
