<FIRST>r w PM-US-Israel     05-25 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Israel,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Issues Reserved Statement on Israel Plans for Palestinian Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's cautious response to Israel's
plan for Palestinian elections in the occupied territories fell
short of the State Department's wholehearted approval.
   The election proposal ``constitutes an important contribution to
a process that has the potential to bring about negotiations''
leading to limited Palestinian self-rule, Bush told Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin in a meeting Wednesday.
   The proposal ``gives us something to work with, and we are now
looking for a constructive Arab response to it,'' said the White
House statement released following the meeting.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler, who spoke
shortly before Bush and Rabin met, was more enthusiastic. Referring
to the plan put forward by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir,
she said, ``We are wholeheartedly supportive of his election
proposals. We want to work with the Israelis and the Palestinians
to move the peace process forward.''
   Tutwiler's comments marked the first time the Bush
administration has expressed unreserved backing for the election
proposal set forth seven weeks ago. The State Department reserved
judgment on other aspects of the Israeli plan.
   A State Department official said he had not seen the White House
statement and could not comment on the difference in tone between
the two statements.
   Bush also ``voiced his deep concern over the escalating violence
in the occupied territories and expressed the strong hope that all
parties would exercise maximum restraint,'' according to the
statement.
   Rabin appealed to Bush to help Israel enlist support among Arabs
and Palestinians for the Israeli election plan.
   ``My impression is the United States would like to assist Israel
in finding the partner among the Palestinians in the territories to
move ahead along the outlines of the peace process,'' Rabin told
reporters outside the White House. He did not say what steps Bush
urged Israel to take.
</TEXT>
