<DOCNO> AP890525-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0429EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WrightProbe-Thumbnails     05-25 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Probe-Thumbnails,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Look at Key Democrats Involved in Negotations Over Wright's Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at key congressional
Democrats who are involved in negotiations over House Speaker James
Wright's political future, or who will be affected by them.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>The Speaker</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   First elected to Congress in 1954, Wright is a New Deal Democrat
who represents the district around Fort Worth, Texas. Wright was
elected House majority leader in 1976, which put him in line for
the speakership after Thomas P. O'Neill stepped down in 1986.
Potential opponents for the speaker's post stepped aside,
recognizing Wright already had the votes among his Democratic House
colleagues.
   But Wright drew criticism from those colleagues once in the job.
Some accused him of a tyrannical leadership style. Others said his
old-fashioned, pompous rhetorical style wasn't in step with the
times, didn't represent the Democrats well on television, and
provided the opposition with an easy target.
   Wright took the lead in forging a Central American peace plan.
But he drew fire from House members on the touchy issue of a
congressional pay raise, giving in to public pressure and forcing
members to go on record with a vote _ a move that killed the big
pay raise proposal.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>The Majority Leader</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Thomas Foley of Washington state has served in Congress
since his election in 1964, and emerged as a leader in 1974 when he
leaped through the seniority system to the chairmanship of the
agriculture committee. In 1980 he was appointed to the post of
majority whip by O'Neill and Wright, and when Wright moved up in
1986 Foley drew no opposition to become majority leader.
   Foley is a former practicing lawyer and prosecutor from Spokane
who has built a liberal voting record in Congress. He is widely
respected by his colleagues for his calm judgment, although he is
hardly exciting or dynamic as a speaker.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>The Majority Whip</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tony L. Coelho of California has served in Congress since
he was first elected in 1978, after working as an aide to his
predecessor for 15 years. He represents California's Central Valley
farmland.
   Already wise in the ins-and-outs of Congress when he was
elected, Coelho quickly moved up the leadership ladder. He
succeeded in generating political IOUs from many Democratic members
as chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee _
where his job was raising millions of dollars and handing it out to
Democratic campaigns.
   He was rewarded in 1986 with the majority whip's post. He has
been admired for his fund-raising success, his political savvy and
his ability to overcome epilepsy. But Coelho's reputation, and
perhaps his future on the leadership ladder, may have been hurt by
recent reports of questionable financial dealings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Richard Gephardt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Although he no longer holds a leadership position, Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri is one of the leaders House Democrats look to.
He ran an unsuccessful but credible campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 1988 and is widely expected to try again.
   He formerly held the job of chairman of the Democratic Caucus,
and is considered a possible candidate for House speaker if Wright
gives up the post, or, if Foley moves up, a potential candidate for
the majority leader's post.
   Gephardt has a moderate voting record and has made tough trade
legislation his big issue. His presidential campaign attracted wide
support from his House colleagues, evidence of his political
spadework as well as the respect of his peers. But it also caused
him some discomfort, as his record as a congressional insider did
not mesh well with the populist image he built his campaign on.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>William Gray</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rep. William H. Gray III of Pennsylvania is chairman of the
House Democratic Caucus and chairman of the Budget Committee, where
he has been a visible leader of Democrats on the budget, deficit
and tax issues.
   Gray was elected to Congress in 1978 and quickly moved into the
ranks of the party's leaders. He continues to preach at the Baptist
church in Philadelphia whose pulpit propelled him into politics.
Gray has advanced quickly in Congress by being able to forge
effective compromises.
</TEXT>
