<FIRST>r a PM-Water-Disease     05-25 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water-Disease,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Microbe in Public Water Blamed for Large Diarrhea Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty percent of residents of a Georgia county
got sick two years ago from drinking the public water supply,
demonstrating that germs can get through the standard purification
process, a study concludes.
   Investigators from the U.S. Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta tracked the cause of the outbreak of intestinal illness in
Carrollton County in the first two months of 1987. The culprit was
a microscopic parasite called cryptosporidium.
   They estimated that 13,000 of the 64,900 residents of the county
got sick from drinking the public water supply.
   The researchers found that the microbe got through the county's
filtering and purification system even though it met standards set
by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.
   A report on the investigation, directed by Dr. Edward B. Hayes,
was published in today's New England Journal of Medicine.
   The county gets its water from a small river that runs through
pastureland. The researchers speculated that low-level
cryptosporidium infection in cattle and an overflowing sewer pipe
may have allowed the microbe to get into the river.
   The parasite is highly resistant to chlorine, which kills other
germs.
   The CDC investigators said their results ``demonstrate that
cryptosporidium can contaminate filtered public water systems _
even when the water quality is within regulatory limits for
coliform bacteria, chlorine, and turbidity.''
   In an editorial, Dr. Betty Olson of the University of
California, Irvine, said the report ``is a dramatic and important
reminder of the country's need to keep a vigilant eye on its water
supplies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
