<SECOND>PM-Wright-Texas,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texans Rally to Defend Wright's Honor; Blame Problems on Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of House Speaker Jim Wright's
hometown supporters say the 34-year veteran's political troubles
are Republicans' way of getting even for John Tower's rejection as
defense secretary.
   ``Jim is a dedicated person. He is honest,'' said Maybelle
Gregory, a longtime Democratic activist. ``It's pure and simple
politics.''
   ``It's get-even-for-Tower time,'' added Bob Collins, a patron at
the White Elephant Saloon in the Fort Worth Stockyards.
   The House ethics committee is investigating 69 charges that the
Democratic congressman violated the congressional ethics code.
   His attorneys reportedly proposed an arrangement Wednesday under
which Wright would step down from the speakership if the most
serious ethics charges were dropped.
   But Wright, 66, denied that he's considering resigning and vowed
to ``press ahead.''
   ``All of these people who are out there accusing him of things
have done the same ... things he did,'' said Diane Emling of nearby
Euless. ``I just wish people would leave him alone.''
   Ms. Emling and several other regulars at Angelos barbecue
restaurant in Fort Worth were pondering Wright's political fate as
they drank beer Wednesday night.
   ``They jump on a whipping dog and they get with it,'' said
mechanic Jack Russell, referring to Wright's political enemies.
   Estil Vance, former chairman of the Tarrant County Democratic
Party and former Fort Worth city councilman, lauded Wright's
congressional career, citing Wright's push for military contracts
that benefit Fort Worth manufacturers and his efforts to keep
Carswell Air Force Base in the city. Vance also said Wright was a
key player in the decision to locate the super collider in Texas.
   Like others, Vance blamed much of Wright's predicament on
partisan politics, which he said was enhanced by the Tower
rejection.
   ``I think it almost feeds on itself,'' Vance said. ``It, to a
certain extent, is partisan, just as the John Tower thing is
partisan.''
   Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox said it would be ``a tragedy''
for Texas if Wright stepped down as speaker.
   And Republican Gov. Bill Clements said: ``I think that it would
be a great loss to the state of Texas. He is a most, most powerful
person in Washington and it has to be good for Texas. There's no
question about that.''
</TEXT>
