<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-25 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Rise, Dollar Falls In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose
moderately today, while the dollar declined against the Japanese
yen after gaining 8.56 yen since May 11.
   The dollar closed at 142.35 yen, down 0.65 yen from Wednesday's
143.00-yen close. The currency opened at 142.60 yen and fluctuated
in a wide range of 141.45 yen to 142.60 yen.
   ``The basic tone of today's trading was speculative investors'
dollar-selling,'' said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a trader with Daiwa Bank.
   He said a rumor that the Bank of Japan might raise its official
discount rate by 0.75 percentage points also encouraged yen-buying.
   Japanese market sources and news media have speculated that the
central bank would raise the key rate by at least 0.5 percentage
points from the present 2.5 percent, but monetary authorities have
made no official announcement. Higher interest rates in Japan would
tend to make the yen more attractive to investors.
   ``But the release of the wholesale price index, which showed
only a modest increase in May, made investors think Japanese
economic growth was slowing down and buy back the dollar,''
Kinugasa added.
   The Bank of Japan reported that the nation's wholesale price
index rose by 0.2 percent in the first 10 days of May from the
previous 10-day period and 3.1 percent from a year earlier.
   ``Basically, the market has a strong demand for the dollar even
though some speculative players occasionally sell it like they did
today,'' Kinugasa said.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed
at 34,005.39, up 153.57 points, or 0.45 percent. The index had
climbed 35.21 points the previous day.
   Dealers said the yen's recovery reassured stock investors and
prompted buying.
   Kenji Ishizuka, a dealer with Daiwa Securities, said the
wholesale price index report also encouraged buy orders.
   ``It's mainly because the figure was within their
expectations,'' he said.
   Ishizuka said the Nikkei's rise also was helped by substantial
profit increases shown in corporate financial reports for fiscal
1988 that came out today.
</TEXT>
