<FIRST>u a PM-HandicappedRuling     05-25 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Handicapped Ruling,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Boosts Handicapped Schooling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public schools must provide education for all
handicapped children, no matter how severe the disability or how
little they might benefit, a federal appeals panel has ruled in
reversing a lower court.
   The ruling Wednesday by the three-judge panel of the 1st U.S.
Circuit of Appeals was in a New Hampshire case, but it could affect
public schools and handicapped children throughout the country.
   Judge Hugh Bownes wrote the decision that reversed a ruling last
year in U.S. District Court in New Hampshire.
   The appeals court said the 1975 Education for All Handicapped
Children Act ``mandates an appropriate public education for all
handicapped children, regardless of the level of achievement that
such children might attain.''
   The judges also said, ``A school district has a duty to provide
an educational program for every handicapped child in the district,
regardless of the severity of the handicap.''
   The case began in 1974 with a complaint filed in the federal
court in New Hampshire on behalf of a boy identified as Timothy W.
   The complaint alleged his rights under federal and New Hampshire
law were violated by the Rochester, N.H., school district when it
said the boy was not eligible for special education.
   At later hearings, the boy's mother and therapists testified
that Timothy could hear, see bright light and respond to music,
touching and talking.
   But a developmental pediatrician testified Timothy ``did not
have educational needs and could not benefit from an education.''
   The district court ruled last July that federal law mandates
that before a child receives a special education, a determination
must be made whether the child will benefit from it.
   The court concluded that Timothy could not be educated.
   The appeals court remanded its ruling to the district court
until the school district develops a ``suitable individualized
program'' for Timothy.
   Rochester School Superintendent Raymond Yeagley said the appeals
court decision will force the school district to shift resources
from students who could benefit from education and focus them on
less capable students.
   ``School districts are getting to the point they are asked to do
everything and spend more on education services than education,''
said Gwendolyn Gregory, deputy general counsel of the National
School Boards Association in Washington.
   The association had filed a brief in support of the Rochester
school district.
   Ms. Gregory said the appeals court decision could make a school
liable for such medical services as physical therapy that could be
considered education.
   But Lorraine Greiff, spokeswoman for the Massachusetts Office of
Handicapped Affairs, hailed the decision.
   ``I think it's terrific. How can you prove who is going to
thrive and who isn't?'' she said.
   Ronald K. Lospennato, the New Hampshire lawyer who represented
Timothy and the Disability Rights Center, said, ``It simply
reinforces what the Education Act said all along: that all
handicapped children are entitled to an education.
   ``They shouldn't have to fight to get in the schoolhouse door.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-VoteCount     05-25 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Vote Count,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Congress Counts Votes the Old Way</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Soviet-Politics, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Congress Of People's Deputies is new, but the
method of counting votes is as old as Communist rule.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, presiding over the initial
debate and several procedural votes at today's inaugural session of
the 2,250-member body, promised to speed up the process _ but not
in time for this session.
   Since the Communists came to power in 1917, balloting has been
by show of hands. At party meetings, delegates traditionally raise
their party cards. Members of the legislature, the Supreme Soviet,
vote with ``a forest of hands.''
   By custom, such votes simply endorse the decisions of the
leadership, making precise counts unnecessary.
   The tradition started to falter only within the last year.
   But as wrangling broke out today at the start of the
long-awaited session of the country's first competitively elected
congress, it became apparent the old way would be quite
time-consuming.
   Opposition to the leadership emerged, even on procedural
questions.
   ``Who is for this agenda?'' Gorbachev asked as the body
considered the plan adopted by a closed caucus Wednesday night.
Most of the 2,155 deputies present raised their delegate cards.
   ``Who is against?'' he asked. When only a smattering of cards
appeared in the cavernous auditorium, Gorbachev began counting
aloud. He gave up when he reached 31 and asked for an official
count.
   A 10-minute pause ensued as representatives of each sector in
the hall counted votes by hand. The tally was 379 against with nine
abstentions.
   Gorbachev declared the agenda adopted, but there was grumbling
among the deputies and he called for another show of hands of those
opposed.
   ``Do not get excited,'' he said. ``I know what to do. I can see
that this is the minority. I think we are not going to count this
time. There is an absolute majority. The agenda is adopted.''
   After several more vote counts, the president told the delegates
that an electronic counting system would be installed.
   ``Soon,'' he said. ``Very soon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
