<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies
except the Canadian dollar in thin European trading early today.
Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said the dollar edged lower before today's scheduled
release of revised U.S. gross national product figures for the
first quarter.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 142.35 Japanese yen, down 0.65 from
the 19-month high posted Wednesday. Later, in London, the dollar
eased further to 142.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _2.0002 West German marks, down from 2.0115
   _1.7670 Swiss francs, down from 1.7887
   _6.7780 French francs, down from 6.8250
   _2.2660 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2670
   _1,449.50 Italian lire, down from 1,455.75
   _1.2075 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1985
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5767 from $1.5695 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $363.75 a troy ounce, up
from $362.75 late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $363.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $364.40, up from $362.60 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.31 to a closing bid of
$364.31. Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.23 a
troy ounce, up from $5.18 dollars bid late Tuesday.
