<FIRST>r a PM-RetardedGirl-Assault     05-25 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retarded Girl-Assault,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Students Arrested in Sexual Assault on Mentally Retarded Girl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More arrests are possible in the sexual
attack of a mentally retarded teen-ager who was assaulted with a
baseball bat and broomstick by five boys as eight others watched,
authorities said.
   Five high school students from the affluent suburb of Glen
Ridge, including the co-captains of the football team, were
arrested Wednesday. The eight who apparently watched the attack
also were Glen Ridge High School students between 16 and 18 years
old, authorities said.
   ``We are satisfied that this was a non-consensual sexual assault
by these five males against this young woman,'' Essex County
prosecutor Herbert Tate said at a news conference. ``She didn't
understand the nature and quality of her actions.''
   Police said the other eight students are being investigated
although none has been charged. The group includes the son of the
Glen Ridge police lieutenant who initially handled the
investigation, according to WNBC-TV and the New York Daily News.
   When the detective discovered that his son was one of the eight
teens who allegedly was present and did not intervene, he took his
son in for questioning and notified his superiors, according to the
published reports. He then reportedly was removed from the case and
it was turned over to Essex County authorities.
   The hourlong assault took place March 1 after the students and
the girl met in a Glen Ridge park and went to the nearby home of
the football players charged in the case, 18-year-old twins Kevin
and Kyle Scherzer, authorities said. The Scherzers' parents were
not at home, authorities said.
   The girl, who has since turned 18, was assaulted in a basement
room with a small baseball bat and a broomstick, Tate said. There
was no sexual intercourse, police said.
   Rumors of a gang rape had circulated throughout the small town
for weeks, and some parents said they were angry at the long delay
in making the arrests.
   ``Why weren't parents told?'' asked Marcia Mann, whose daughter
is a sophomore. ``Apparently a lot of kids knew all the sordid
details. There was bragging going on in the halls.''
   The arrests were made a day after WNBC-TV reported that no
arrests had been made despite the time that had passed.
   ``I think there was a coverup,'' said Josh Golin, a 17-year-old
senior. ``Until the media got called, this was going to be kept
quiet until it blew over.''
   Tate said the NBC report was not a fact, just that the
investigation took time.
   Kevin Scherzer is charged with one count of conpiracy to commit
sexual assault, and two counts each of aggravated criminal sexual
contact and aggravated sexual assault, said Assistant Prosecutor
Robert D. Laurino.
   Kyle Scherzer and Peter Quigley, 18, each were charged with
conspiracy and two counts of aggravated sexual assault, Laurino
said.
   Quigley was accused of cheering on the assault, although Tate
would not give details.
   The three were released on bonds. A 17-year-old male and another
student who has since turned 18 were charged as juveniles in all
three counts, Tate said.
   Two juveniles appeared in Family Court, said Ray Weiss, a
spokesman for Tate. Details of that appearance were unavailable
since those proceedings are closed to the public, Weiss said.
   The girl attends a special education program at West Orange High
School, and participates in extracurricular activites in Glen
Ridge, a community of about 8,000 located about five miles
northwest of Newark.
   School officials declined comment but issued a statement that
said school administrators had become aware of the attack through
``informal reports.''
</TEXT>
