<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Hockey     05-25 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Hockey,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Leading Soviet Hockey Players Free To Play In NHL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of the Soviet Union's finest ice hockey
players are now free to play with the National Hockey League, the
official Tass news agency reported today.
   The announcement that Vyacheslav Fetisov, Igor Larionov and
Sergei Makarov were discharged Wednesday from the Red Army _ whose
hockey team they represent in the Soviet league _ capped months of
unprecedented public squabbling within the world champion hockey
team.
   Tass said the three were discharged ``owing to reduction of
staff'' in the Red Army and ``are now free to sign contracts with
NHL or any other foreign clubs.''
   The agency did not mention the squabbles in its brief dispatch
and it was unclear how much of their hard-currency earnings the
players would be permitted to keep if they sign NHL contracts, as
expected.
   Other Soviet athletes competing internationally have been
required to turn over a share of their earnings or winnings to
Soviet sports organizations.
   Larionov last year publicly criticized the methods of national
team coach Viktor Tikhonov. In a long article in the weekly
Ogonyok, Larionov complained of rigorous training, inadequate
compensation and a lack of debate and discussion in the team.
   Fetisov quit the national team after a public row with the coach
over the treatment of his players. The two reconciled before the
World Championships in Stockholm in late April.
   The Soviets won the title but lost one of their best young
players, Alexander Mogilny, who defected to the United States.
   The defection of Mogilny, who has been contracted to play with
the Buffalo Sabres, prompted speculation in Moscow that the Soviets
would block freedom for other players to play for foreign teams.
   Today's announcement did not specify whether Fetisov, Larionov
and Makarov would continue to play for the Soviet national team.
   Fetisov is a standout defenseman, and Makarov and Larionov are
star forwards on the Soviet team.
   The New Jersey Devils have contract rights on Fetisov, the
Vancouver Canucks on Larionov and the Calgary Flames on Makarov.
   There was no immediate reaction from the three players.
</TEXT>
