<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseNewspaper     05-25 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Newspaper,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Quit NY Chinese Newspaper in Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half the editorial staff of a New York-based
Chinese newspaper quit after the publisher demanded they print his
commentary urging the use troops to restore order in Beijing, The
New York Times reported today.
   Four reporters, two editors and the editor in chief walked out
of The Center Daily on Wednesday, two hours before the paper's 10
a.m. presstime, the Times said.
   The Center Daily's publisher, Chaochu Fu, called on typists and
graphic editors to compose the front page to include his article,
which the editor in chief and others had objected to as reactionary.
   The chaos created by the walkout at The Center Daily led to the
paper's Wednesday editions being printed in two sections instead of
the usual four, the Times said.
   Fu had wanted to run the article calling for the government
crackdown on Tuesday, but editors refused. He then demanded the
article go in Wednesday's paper, precipitating the resignations.
   Powin Lin, the editor in chief, said he did not want the article
to appear ``because it is against the students, and the whole world
supports the students.''
   On Monday, Fu demanded publication of another commentary, which
he signed with a pseudonym that praised China's senior leader, Deng
Xiaoping, for his contributions, the Times said.
   Deng's resignation has been among the demands of Beijing
protesters.
   The pseudonymous commentary brought a storm of protest from
readers of The Center Daily and 100 threatening phone calls, Lin
said.
   Fu could not be reached for comment, the Times said.
   The Center Daily is published Monday through Saturday with a
circulation of 60,000 and is the second-largest Chinese newspaper
published in the United States.
   The paper was founded by Fu in 1981.
</TEXT>
