<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-25 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornadoes, Thunderstorms Push Across Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell today from the Great Lakes to the middle Mississippi
Valley as a line of thunderstorms pushed across the Midwest. A
tornado hit a campground in Springfield, Ill., early today
following several twisters in other states.
   Strong winds overturned a trailer near Appleton, Wis., killing a
32-year-old woman and injuring two relatives, officials said.
   A cold front moved into moist and unstable air, producing severe
thunderstorms Wednesday evening across the upper Mississippi
Valley. Tornadoes and high winds were reported in Iowa, Minnesota,
Missouri, Kansas, Wisconsin and Illinois.
   A twister that swept through the Abe Lincoln campground in
Springfield injured five people. Seven trailers were damaged and
two were overturned.
   A tornado also touched down at Riverton, Ill., downing power
lines that caused fires. Thunderstorm wind blew down two barns and
large trees and blew windows out of homes west of Elgin.
   Marshall County, Iowa, was one of the hardest hit areas in the
state, with severe damage reported. Three people suffered broken
bones and bruises when they were caught by tornado winds as they
tried to reach a storm cellar.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included 2 inches at Green Bay, Wis., and 1\ inches at Wausau, Wis.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
Great Lakes across the Ohio Valley and southeast Missouri to much
of Arkansas and Oklahoma; scattered showers and thunderstorms
across Mississippi, Alabama and southern Florida; showers from the
Pacific Northwest to North Dakota with some snow in Montana and
gusty winds from Wyoming across the Dakotas to the upper
Mississippi Valley.
   Predicted high temperatures: 50s and 60s from the central and
northern Pacific Coast across the northern and central Rockies and
much of the northern Plains to northern Minnesota; the lower 90s
over portions of West Virginia, Kentucky and Tennessee; 90s from
Georgia and Florida across the Gulf Coast states, most of Texas and
southern New Mexico to the desert Southwest. A few readings between
100 and 105 degrees were expected in southwest Texas and the desert
Southwest. Elsewhere, highs were to be in the 70s and 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 29 at
McCall, Idaho, to 86 degrees at Laughlin Air Force Base in Del Rio,
Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 fair; Boston 56 cloudy; Buffalo 56 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 64 fair; Cincinnati 70 partly cloudy; Cleveland 66
fair; Detroit 67 partly cloudy; Miami 73 fair; New York 62 cloudy;
Philadelphia 54 fair; Pittsburgh 58 fair; Portland, Maine 54 rain;
Washington 59 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 43 fair; Chicago 65 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 76 windy; Denver 56 cloudy; Des Moines 57 fair;
Indianapolis 70 cloudy; Kansas City 70 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul
55 fair; Nashville 74 partly cloudy; New Orleans 79 foggy; St.
Louis 77 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 64 fair; Anchorage 48 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 69 fair; Los Angeles 59 fair; Phoenix 77 fair; Salt Lake City
46 partly cloudy; San Diego 61 fair; San Francisco 54 windy;
Seattle 47 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 52 foggy; Toronto 55 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
