<FIRST>u i PM-HongKong-China 1stLd-Writethru   05-25 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0475,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Plunge on Hong Kong Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with stocks showing slight rebound
in afternoon. Picks up 10th pvs, `On Sunday...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In nervous reaction to political developments
in China, share prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange suffered
their worst loss this morning since the worldwide market collapse
of 1987.
   Stocks rebounded in the afternoon but still ended the session
sharply lower.
   Brokers said investors reacted primarily to reports that
hardliners in the Chinese leadership, led by Premier Li Peng, had
won a power struggle against moderates, headed by Communist Party
Secretary General Zhao Ziyang.
   The market rebounded after China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs
announced that both Li and Zhao were still holding their posts.
   Investors in British-run Hong Kong, which reverts to Chinese
rule in 1997 when a territorial lease expires, remain skittish over
political shifts in China even though the Chinese government has
promised to preserve the territory's social and economic lifestyle
for 50 years.
   The Hang Seng Index of blue chips lost 256.22 points to 2752.51,
down 58.92 points from Wednesday. It ended the morning session at
2,668.70 points, down 340.03 points from Wednesday's close,
suffering from the worst loss since the worldwide market collapse
of 1987.
   On Monday, the Hang Seng Index plunged 339.06 points, its worst
single-day loss since the worldwide market collapse in October
1987. It recovered 261.08 points on Tuesday, but fell 58.92 points
on Wednesday.
   Li imposed martial law in Beijing on Saturday in an attempt
suppress a student-led democracy movement that has swept China, but
the students have refused to quit their protest and citizens have
come to their aid.
   Zhao, who has been sympathetic toward the students, is regarded
by many as the only Chinese leader able to resolve the impasse
without violence.
   On Sunday, a crowd of Hong Kong Chinese estimated at between
400,000 and 1 million rallied in support of the pro-democracy
demonstrators in China in what was described as the largest protest
march in the British colony's history.
   There have been daily rallies since Li imposed martial law, and
on Wednesday an estimated 100,000 students, teachers, housewives
and workers demonstrated through streets, demanding the resignation
of the Chinese premier.
</TEXT>
