<FIRST>r a PM-SkiCharges     05-25 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ski Charges,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads No Contest In Fatal Ski Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with manslaughter
for a skiing collision that killed an 11-year-old girl Feb. 17 has
pleaded no contest to a reduced charge and is expected to receive a
month in jail.
   The case was one of the first in Colorado in which a skier was
prosecuted for an accident on the slopes.
   Howard Hidle, 31, of North Richland Hills, Texas, entered the
plea to criminally negligent homicide Wednesday in the death of
Kari Meylor, 11, of Sioux City, Iowa. She was struck by Hidle's
skis at the Winter Park ski area.
   Hidle was skiing out of control when he hit Meylor, according to
a witness.
   Under a proposed plea bargain, Hidle would get a month a jail,
two months under house arrest and four years' probation, and would
be required to do 400 hours of community service, working with the
handicapped and critically injured.
   He also would be required to pay $15,000 to the child's family
and pay for a plaque to be erected in her memory at Winter Park.
   Judge Richard Doucette tentatively accepted the plea and set
sentencing for July 21.
   ``Every spare penny and every spare hour of the next four years
of his life will be spent on restitution and helping others,'' said
District Attorney Greg Long. ``We see this as a more positive
consequence (than jail).''
</TEXT>
