<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PanPacific-Fire     05-25 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Pacific-Fire,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auditorium Where Elvis Made Coast Debut Burns</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA3, LA12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIC LEYVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspicious fire destroyed the landmark Pan
Pacific Auditorium, the streamlined, art deco arena where Elvis
Presley made his West Coast debut and Sonja Henie skated during the
1930s, officials said today.
   The auditorium, vacant since 1972, once boasted the world's
largest indoor ice rink and was host to the Ice Capades.
   The fierce, fast-moving fire broke out shortly after 7 p.m.
Wednesday and burned for about two hours.
   Fire officials said the blaze may have been started by
transients.
   ``The building has been abandoned for several years and sealed
up. As far was we know the power is cut, too, and there is and no
reason to assume natural causes,'' said Assistant Fire Chief Tony
Ennis.
   The building, which boasted a dramatic, multi-pillared facade,
was listed on the National Registry of Historic Buildings. It also
featured prominently in the recent film ``Miracle Mile,'' an action
thriller about nuclear apocalypse.
   ``Virtually everyone performed there,'' said Mike Venema, a
public relations man who noted that Presley gave his first West
Coast performance there in 1956.
   The building was created by the Works Progress Administration
during the Depression and ``is considered, was considered, one of
the finest examples of Art Moderne in existence. It's considered a
landmark piece,'' said Venema, who was working on behalf of a
preservationist seeking to save the building.
   A man who sought treatment for burns was questioned by fire
investigators.
   ``Right now, we just want to talk to him in regards to what he
observed at the time of the fire,'' Arson Capt. Gary Seidel said.
   Fire authorities had no immediate dollar estimate on the damage.
</TEXT>
