<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PlasticsBan     05-25 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plastics Ban,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Stays Suffolk Ban on Some Plastic Packaging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEER PARK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ruled Suffolk County cannot
enforce its ban on plastic packaging until it studies the potential
effect on the environment.
   Supreme Court Justice Jack Cannavo on Wednesday stayed the law,
which would ban stores from packaging food in polystyrene or
polyvinyl. The law, which was to go into effect July 1, is opposed
by plastics manufacturers and food merchants.
   Wednesday's ruling requires the county Legislature to file a
complete environmental impact statement, which takes about three
months.
   The judge ruled that Suffolk County legislators failed to comply
with state environmental law when they approved the measure last
year after saying it would have do no significant harm to the
environment.
   The law would ban grocery bags, coffee cups, eating utensils and
fast-food containers made from either of the two plastics. Similar
bans have been adopted in St. Paul, Minn.; Minneapolis; Berkeley,
Calif., and Portland, Ore.
   Advocates of such bans say the non-degradable, non-recyclable
plastics take up too much space in landfills and might release
harmful emissions if incinerated.
   In a lawsuit filed last year, however, the Society of the
Plastics Industry and manufacturers of plastic food packaging said
paper products are a greater environmental threat than the plastic
items they would replace.
   They said that paper products dumped in landfills could pollute
ground water as the paper products decomposed.
   Suffolk County attorney Paul Sabatino said the county may appeal.
</TEXT>
