<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-ArabSummit 1stLd-Writethru a0438 05-25 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arab Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Summit Leaders Try to Agree on Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with foreign ministers drafting final
text, meeting still split over Lebanon. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LaserPhoto NY12 ^By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab leaders extended their summit an
extra day as they sought agreement on a strategy to resolve the
conflict in Lebanon and on whether to support PLO chief Yasser
Arafat's peace moves.
   Traditional foes Iraq and Syria remained at loggerheads over the
presence of Syrian troops in Beirut as foreign ministers attending
the summit began drafting a final summit communique today. They
were to consider three separate resolutions drafted by Egypt, Saudi
Arabia and Jordan.
   Syria's President Hafez Assad told a marathon session Wednesday
night that he is willing to withdraw the 15,000 Syrian soldiers in
the Lebanese capital if an Arab force replaces them. But some of
the Arab leaders reportedly do not want to send troops to Syria's
war-plagued neighbor.
   The extraordinary summit, called mainly for the ceremonial
return of Egypt following a 10-year ostracism for making peace with
Israel, has turned largely into a quarrel over Lebanon.
   Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah, has
indicated his country wants to stop presiding over the six-nation
league committee designated to find an Arab compromise in Lebanon,
conference sources said.
   Heads of state met for 5{ hours Wednesday night but made no
headway in resolving the bitter dispute between Syria and Iraq.
   Syria supports Lebanon's Moslem acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss
against his Christian rival, Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Iraq is the only outspoken Arab supporter of Aoun.
   The Syrian soldiers are among 40,000 Syria deployed in Lebanon
under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate. Christian Lebanese and
their backers say Damascus broke that mandate by siding with
Moslems in recent sectarian fighting that has killed at least 359
people.
   At Wednesday night's meeting, Assad chided his fellow Arabs for
their inability to act on promises to dispatch a multinational Arab
peacekeeping force to Beirut. The Syrian leader threatened to leave
Beirut with only a Lebanese garrison _ or no garrison at all.
   Conference sources said Assad argued bitterly with Iraq's Saddam
Hussein through most of the session. ``Basically, Assad accused
Hussein of backing the anti-Moslem Christians, while Hussein
accused Assad of introducing Iranians into Lebanon,'' one source
said.
   Most Arab countries, including powerful Saudi Arabia, Egypt and
Jordan, reportedly are leaning toward the Iraqi position. This
leaves Syria in need of a compromise or facing isolation in the
Arab world.
   Despite the arguments, the 22-nation league summit has brought
some spectacular reconciliations, particularly between Libya's
leader, Moammar Gadhafi, and Egypt's leader, Hosni Mubarak.
   The Egyptian president told a Moroccan television interviewer
the readmission of the Arab world's most populous state ``will
undoubtedly help to bring the Arabs together.''
   Syria also challenged on Wednesday night the Palestine
Liberation Organization's recognition of Israel and the PLO's offer
to negotiate peace with the Jewish state. All the other Arab
leaders seem to accept PLO leader Yasser Arafat's move as
unpleasant but inevitable, sources said.
   President Bush has sent a message expressing hope the summit
will support peace initiatives from Israel and Arafat.
   The summit, originally scheduled to end Wednesday, was to end
with a public session late today.
   Tunisia's President Zine Abidine Ben Ali and Djibouti's Hassan
Gouled Aptidon quietly slipped out of town Wednesday to attend the
summit of French-speaking countries in Dakar, Senegal.
</TEXT>
