<FIRST>r a PM-DolphinUlcers     05-25 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dolphin Ulcers,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Privacy Seeking Dolphins Get Ulcers From Crowds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dolphins, like Greta Garbo, want to be alone
sometimes, scientitsts have learned.
   A study by the former chief of medicine at Baltimore's National
Aquarium says three dolphins developed ulcers shortly after
arriving at the newly-opened aquarium eight years ago because of
the big crowds that came to see them.
   ``We looked at everything we thought could be stressful to them,
such as the configuration of the tank, temperature, being watched
by the public, light levels and noise from the pumps,'' said
Michael K. Stoskopf, professor of comparative medicine at Johns
Hopkins University School of Medicine.
   ``The real problem with the exhibit was the people,'' said
Stoskopf, chief of medicine at the aquarium from 1981 to 1988.
   Kibby, Mimi and Aphrodite developed gastro-intestinal ulcers in
1981 within 50 days of arrival in Baltimore but recovered within
six months of their being flown to the Dolphin Research Center in
Grassy Key, Fla., in 1982, Stoskopf said.
   The Baltimore aquarium's multimillion-dollar dolphin tank was
never used for dolphins again.
   The animals didn't have enough room to get away from the crowds,
Stoskopf said. Researchers found later that by fleeing from the
crowds, the mammals congregated in a spot where noise from the
tank's pumps was loudest.
   Aquarium officials spent $250,000 on modications that reduced 98
percent of the noise, limited visitors to a maximum of 850 people
an hour and set firm closing hours to assure the animals at least
eight hours of rest every night.
   The lessons learned led aquarium officials to select beluga
whales as replacements and allow them more time to adjust to their
new home.
   The first two belugas spent a year in a quiet tank at the New
York Aquarium and were introduced slowly to larger numbers of
people.
   The belugas, Anore and Illamar, ``seem to be very happy,'' said
Robert L. Jenkins, aquarium director of operations and husbandry.
They were joined last summer by a third whale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
