<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-25 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Hezbollah Shootout, Druse Fire at Israeli Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops exchanged gunfire with
pro-Iranian militiamen in south Beirut today, while Syrian and
Christian gunners skirmished on the city's dividing Green Line,
police said.
   One person was killed and 11 people were wounded in the clashes,
police said. The casualties brought the toll to 359 killed and
1,399 wounded since the latest round of fighting in Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war broke out March 8.
   Also today, low-flying Israeli jets on reconnaissance sorties
drew anti-aircraft fire from Druse positions in mountains above the
Lebanese capital, a police spokesman said on condition of
anonymity. None of the planes was hit, police said.
   Militiamen of Hezbollah, or Party of God, Iran's main Shiite
Moslem ally in Lebanon, opened fire on a Syrian army jeep in Ouzai,
on Beirut's southern edge. ``Other Syrian troops in the area fired
back. The gunbattle sent panicky residents at a nearby cooking gas
distribution center fleeing,'' said the police spokesman. He said
one Hezbollah militiaman was killed in the 10-minute shootout. Five
militiamen were injured, the spokesman said.
   The Hezbollah is believed the umbrella group for underground
factions holding most of the 15 foreign hostages in Lebanon. The
longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   In another incident, six civilians were wounded in a sudden
half-hour flare-up with 106mm recoilless guns and rocket-propelled
grenades between Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly Christian troops and
Syrian forces. The clash occurred on the mid-city Museum crossing
that divides Beirut into Moslem and Christian sectors.
   Each side accused the other of starting the fight, which
violated a fragile cease-fire called by the Arab League May 11 to
halt the fighting between Christian forces and Syrian troops allied
with Druse militiamen.
   The fighting broke out weeks ago after Aoun ordered a blockade
of three illegal harbors run by Moslem militias.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party
retaliated by shelling the Christian enclave. The Syrians are in
Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   Also today, Aoun reiterated that Syria should pull its troops
out of Lebanon to facilitate Israel's withdrawal from the
6-to-10-mile border enclave under its control for almost seven
years. Israel refers to the region in Lebanon as its security zone.
   Syria says it will pull out only after the Israeli army also
withdraws. Aoun criticized the United States for not pressuring
Syrian troops to leave.
</TEXT>
