<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Trial 1stLd-Writethru   05-25 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0514,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Acquits Four Soldiers of Manslaughter in Palestinian's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD that doctor acquitted of negligence, ages
of soldiers, ADDS comment from defendant's sister. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASTINA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military judge today acquitted four
soldiers of manslaughter in the death of a Palestinian man they
beat with a broomstick and rifle butts but found them guilty of
mistreating the detainee.
   Col. Emanuel Gross said the four, members of the elite Givati
Brigade, should have refused orders by their superiors to punish
detainees with beatings. He said they went further than those
instructions allowed.
   The case was seen as a test of the army's willingness to
discipline soldiers accused of brutality in the Palestinian
uprising.
   Maltreatment is a misdemeanor punishable by up to three years in
prison. Sentencing was set for June 15.
   The soldiers, none older than 21, were accused of beating to
death 42-year-old Hani el-Shami on Aug. 22 while conducting an
arrest in the Jabaliya refugee camp in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   Gross found that they inflicted blows ``indiscriminately'' for
about 15 minutes, hitting the man all over his body with rifle
butts and a broomstick. One soldier jumped from a bed onto
el-Shami's stomach, he said.
   But he said the cause of el-Shami's death was not that beating
but a second beating administered by unknown soldiers at a military
base.
   The judge said the investigation was so poorly conducted it was
doubtful the soldiers who actually administered the fatal beating
could be identified.
   Had the defendants _ Pvts. Yitzhak Kibbudi, Aryeh Luchato and
Ron Hakhel and 1st Sgt. Yitzhak Adler _ been convicted of
manslaughter they could have received up to 20 years in prison.
   The judge also acquitted an army doctor, David Nussam, of
negligence related to his treatment of el-Shami after the beating.
   The verdict did not make any judgment on the policy of beating,
and the army withheld comment on whether charges would be brought
against the defendants' superiors.
   Beatings became widespread after Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
in January 1988 authorized soldiers to beat Palestinian rioters to
prevent violent demonstrations.
   Commanders said many soldiers initially felt they were required
to break bones to punish rioters, but this was later clarified and
the number of beating cases fell significantly.
   The often brutal use of clubs has brought widespread criticism
of Israel, especially after pictures of soldiers beating
Palestinians were shown on foreign television news programs.
   The State Department has criticized Israel as failing to bring
soldiers who mistreat detainees to trial or being too lenient in
punishing them.
   In testimony at the trial in March, the army chief of staff, Lt.
Gen. Dan Shomron, acknowledged the army's policy was unclear and
left many ``gray areas'' open to soldiers' discretion.
   ``Deterrence is not the goal, overcoming violence is,'' Shomron
testified. ``But when someone stops resisting, that's a matter of
opinion.''
   Gross, in his 100-page verdict, reviewed the policy, which
allows soldiers to beat Palestinians to disperse demonstrators or
in pursuit of troublemakers. He said beating is to stop when a
Palestinian is in custody.
   Defense lawyers contended the troops had been following orders
given by a field commander, whom they said should bear
responsibility for any wrongdoing.
   Gross said the soldiers' commander had told them they could beat
Palestinians after arrest as punishment.
   ``The order given to them was manifestly illegal,'' the judge
said. ``The beating of someone who disturbs order for the purpose
of deterrence is not a military need. It is punishment.''
   The soldiers sat quietly through the two-hour reading of the
verdict and hugged their families afterward.
   Hakhel's sister Shira, 19, said she thought the trial was often
unfair. ``I think the trial was very hard,'' she told reporters.
``I think they just took them to set an example. These soldiers are
just kids.''
   The soldiers were among 67 officers and soldiers charged with
crimes ranging from assault and battery to manslaughter since the
start of the 17-month-old Palestinian uprising.
   Excluding the Givati soldiers, 36 of the troops have been found
guilty and received a maximum punishment of 21 months in jail.
Three others were acquitted. Cases of the others are still in
progress.
</TEXT>
