<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-US     05-25 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-US,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Minister Predicts U.S. Ties May Be Normalized in 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach today
predicted that Vietnam-U.S. relations will be normalized by 1990,
after Vietnam has ended its military occupation of Cambodia.
   ``The United States has repeatedly stated that relations with
Vietnam would be normalized after complete withdrawal of Vietnamese
troops from Cambodia,'' he said.
   ``I am of the opinion that the United States will keep the words
of a big country. The sooner it is normalized, the better, and it
is better late than never,'' Thach said in an interview with The
Associated Press.
   Asked to predict when relations would be normalized, he said a
reasonable guess would be next year. ``It is the end of the tunnel.
Now we can get out of the tunnel,'' he said of the Cambodian
conflict.
   The key player in any peace agreement is guerrilla leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, who has failed to fashion a deal in several
rounds of negotiations with the Vietnam-installed government in
Cambodia.
   Thach said Sihanouk often has changed his behavior and tactics
but always had the same objective _ to be head of state in
Cambodia. Since the pro-Vietnamese government has now offered him
that post, Thach said, ``I don't think he will miss the
opportunity.''
   The United States has not recognized the communist government
that has ruled since defeating the U.S.-backed South Vietnam
government in April 1975. The Carter administration came close to
normalizing ties in the 1970s, but that fell apart after Vietnam
invaded Cambodia in late 1978.
   The United States, which supports the resistance guerrillas, has
said it would not consider ending its trade and aid embargo or
normalizing ties until the last Vietnamese troops leave. Vietnam
has pledged to withdraw its remaining 60,000 to 70,000 troops by
Sept. 30.
   U.S. ties are crucial to Vietnam's top priority of drawing the
aid and investment to develop its economy, one of the world's
poorest.
   The United States and Vietnam in recent years have made rapid
progress on humanitarian issues, including the resettlement of
refugees and migrants to the United States and resolving the fates
of U.S. soldiers missing in action in Vietnam.
   Private U.S. citizens also have substantially increased contacts.
   Arnold Schecter, a leading American researcher, said on
Wednesday that Vietnam is allowing him to open an office in a Hanoi
medical school to study the health effects of Agent Orange, the
herbicide U.S. forces sprayed on Vietnam during the war.
   ``It is something of a breakthrough. Vietnam now is very
different and relatively easygoing compared to the extreme rigidity
that used to be there,'' said Schecter.
   Schecter, of the State University of New York at Binghampton,
just ended a visit to Vietnam.
</TEXT>
