<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-YorkshireRipper     05-25 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yorkshire Ripper,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Private Eye' Appeals For Help to Fight Record Libel Judgment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The satirical magazine ``Private Eye'' appealed
today for help in fighting a record $942,000 libel judgment.
   A jury on Wednesday ordered that sum paid to Sonia Sutcliffe,
wife of a mass murderer known as ``the Yorkshire Ripper,'' because
of Private Eye's false report that she sold her story to a tabloid
newspaper for $392,000 after carousing with its reporters at a
hotel.
   The award is the highest given by a jury in a British libel suit.
   Ian Hislop, the magazine's editor, admitted the report was
incorrect but said the magazine would go bankrupt if it had to make
the payment.
   ``By launching an appeal in this way we are making it clear that
we are fighting this absurd award which we want overturned,''
Hislop told a news conference. He was accompanied by actor-comedian
Peter Cook, a major owner of the 200,000-circulation magazine.
   Peter Sutcliffe was jailed for life in 1981 for killing 13 women
and attempting to kill five more. Mrs. Sutcliffe, 38, was not
implicated and since has separated from her husband.
   ``We shall apply for a speedy hearing,'' Hislop said. ``As we
understand it, this will mean a retrial. If the damages are not
substantially reduced then it looks as though we will have to
bankrupt the company.''
   He said he believed a fair settlement would have been about
$24,000.
   The amount awarded by the jury, Hislop said, was 100 times the
average compensation paid to three of Sutcliffe's victims.
   Private Eye first alleged in 1981 that Mrs. Sutcliffe had made a
deal with London's Daily Mail newspaper. In 1983, it repeated the
allegation. This year, after she sued, it published two more
articles that Mrs. Sutcliffe said implied she knew about her
husband's crimes.
   During the trial, Private Eye conceded there was no deal with
the Daily Mail but argued that Mrs. Sutcliffe had negotiated with
newspapers and was prepared to capitalize on her husband's crimes.
   The previous British libel award record was $831,000 awarded to
novelist Jeffrey Archer in 1987 against The Daily Star, a London
tabloid newspaper that alleged he gave money to a prostitute. He
said he never met her.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
