<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Netherlands-Environment     05-25 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Netherlands-Environment,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Government Proposes Plan to Fight Pollution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today unveiled an
ambitious plan to clean up the Dutch environment by the year 2010,
but it said 80 percent of the nation's forests may die even if the
measures are put into effect.
   The 250 pages of pollution-fighting measures are likely to be a
major issue in September elections. Controversy surrounding them
brought down the government headed by Premier Ruud Lubbers.
   The proposals will be taken up by the new government after the
elections.
   If passed, the government would spend about $2.9 billion yearly
by 1994 on the program, which aims to clean up the heavily polluted
Dutch environment by 2010. That expenditure would come on top of
the $3.5 billion already spent annually on environmental programs,
said Environment Minister Ed Nijpels.
   The package is expected to cost the average Dutch household $13
a month, he said.
   But even if the government meets the targets set by the plan,
only 20 percent of Dutch forests will be saved, the document warned.
   Environmental groups criticized the plan as ``mopping up water
from a running faucet,'' and said it was inadequate.
   The plan cited acid rain caused by car exhaust emissions,
coal-burning power stations and the farming industry's fertilizer
production as major causes of pollution in the Netherlands.
   Its recommendations include removing 7,000 toxic waste dumps
scattered around the Netherlands, cutting pesticide and fertilizer
use by 50 percent, and slashing industrial discharges by 75 percent.
   It said the emission of acidity-causing chemicals must be cut by
at least 70 percent.
   For the second successive day, Dutch Television broadcast an
official appeal for drivers to leave their cars at home as
pollution reached a dangerous high. Authorities were considering a
complete driving ban, according to the network.
   Lubers' Christian Democrats had hoped to include among the
measures the elimination of breaks for long-distance commuters. But
the ruling coalition's junior partner, the Liberal Party objected
to the measures and the subsequent battle split the government.
</TEXT>
