<FIRST>r a PM-DixieBeer     05-25 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dixie Beer,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deep South Brewery Dunned for Taxes, Files for Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dixie Brewing Co., the Deep South's last
major independent beer maker, has filed for bankruptcy protection
to keep city tax officials from closing the 82-year-old brewery.
   The Chapter 11 petition, filed late Wednesday, apparently will
allow the company to continue operating while it reorganizes its
finances. Workers were seen entering the brewery this morning.
   Dixie received a letter Tuesday from the city giving it 24 hours
to come up with $375,000 in overdue sales and property taxes or
shut down.
   Stewart Walker, the city's chief administrative officer, said
the city had no way to arrange a compromise on the unpaid property
taxes.
   City spokeswoman Jinx Broussard on Wednesday said New Orleans
cannot grant an alcohol permit if a company has outstanding
obligations.
   ``Basically the city right now is just doing what it has to do
under the law. If they don't have an Alcohol Beverage Permit they
can't operate,'' she said.
   Earlier this month, the city gave Dixie's husband-and-wife
owners, Joseph Bruno and Kendra Elliott, an extension to pay water
bills of $215,000.
   New Orleans once had 13 breweries providing an estimated 3,000
jobs.
   Dixie survived Prohibition by dabbling in ice cream, sodas and a
near-beer named Dixco. When Prohibition ended, Dixie established
itself as the frontrunner among New Orleans beers.
   But in 1975, phenol fumes given off by a new flooring material
in the brewery's cellar seeped into the brewing water and gave the
beer a bad taste. Beer drinkers switched to other brands and Dixie
sales plummeted, never to recover.
   Dixie's share of the local beer market, which once topped 20
percent, has dropped to less than 1 percent. The brewery employs
about 100 workers
</TEXT>
