<SECOND>PM-Hoffman Lawsuit,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Beginning in Suit Against Actor in Drowning Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection has begun in a lawsuit
over from a woman's accidental death 2{ years ago in a hot tub on
Dustin Hoffman's estate.
   Five of the eight jurors needed were chosen Wednesday.
   Sheila Cruse Fionda, 43, was found floating face down in the hot
tub at Hoffman's Roxbury estate in 1986. The actor was not there at
the time. The woman had gone out to dinner with the estate's
caretaker the previous evening.
   State Police concluded that Ms. Fionda drowned accidentally; her
blood-alcohol level was three times the legal limit for driving in
Connecticut.
   Her former husband, A. Joseph Fionda, sued Hoffman, the
property's former caretaker, the tub installer and the manufacturer
of its heater.
   The suit does not specify amount of damages sought, but Fionda's
attorney, Robert Guendelsberger, said last year that the family
would settle for $200,000.
   The suit accuses Hoffman of failing to have the area of the hot
tub fenced, failing to ensure that the water did not get too hot
and failing to instruct the caretaker about the safe use of the tub.
   Hoffman is in a play in London, and his attorney, Jon Berk, said
he would not return to the United States until September.
