<FIRST>r w PM-AirControllers     05-25 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Controllers,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Study Sees Serious Problems In Air Traffic Control System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's air traffic controllers complain
they are handling too many planes, working too many hours and
suffering from low morale in a system that has changed little since
the same problems were cited four years ago, a congressional report
said today.
   ``In short, the (Federal Aviation Administration,) simply
ignored recommendations for change,'' said Rep. Guy V. Molinari,
R-N.Y., referring to the General Accounting Office study that
showed 43 percent of controllers characterize their morale as low.
   FAA officials said their own surveys painted a brighter picture.
   The GAO study said that while most controllers were concerned
about working conditions, the increasing traffic they have to
handle and ``other aspects of air traffic control that affect
system safety and operating efficiency,'' their supervisors were
far less concerned.
   The survey, released at a House subcommittee hearing, was based
on 5,098 questionnnaires filled out by controllers and supervisors
at the FAA's largest facilities late last year.
   Molinari, ranking minority member of the Public Works and
Transportation subcommittee on investigations and oversight, said
the results were ``nearly a replica'' of a similar 1985 GAO survey
and show that many of the problems that contributed to a 1981 air
traffic controllers strike still exist.
   More than 11,000 controllers were fired for the illegal walkout,
and Molinari said the system still has 3,600 fewer fully qualified
controllers than it did before the strike. The FAA says the work
force totals 16,464, with 9,689 classified as ``full performance
controllers.''
   Molinari said the number of full performance controllers has
dropped by 150 in the last six months.
   ``The FAA has failed in these eight years to rebuild the air
traffic control system adequately and they have failed to heed the
views of controllers and supervisors,'' he said.
   GAO official Kenneth M. Mead said the Flight Safety Foundation
concluded from the survey that the system ``is not unsafe but that
the margin of safety _ that undefined limit beyond which the system
would no longer be safe _ remains less than desirable.''
   The private foundation acts as a consultant to the GAO, which is
the investigative arm of Congress.
   The FAA's acting administrator, Robert E. Whittington, told the
subcommittee that the agency's own surveys of controllers show some
encouraging results. He gave figures showing that most controllers
believe their supervisors communicate honestly with them, believe
their training is adequate and believe they are treated fairly
regardless of age, sex or race.
   Whittington said safety records also indicate that the system
works well.
   He quoted statistics showing that runway incursions, reported
near-collision and operations errors all decreased between 1986 and
1988.
   Meanwhile, the National Transportation Safety Board said the FAA
should act immediately to improve air traffic procedures in the
crowded skies over southern California.
   The NTSB, in a letter to the FAA, its investigation of air
traffic in that region cited a variety of problems, including
excessive overtime, poor training and understaffing of controllers.
</TEXT>
