<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan     05-25 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto Removes Powerful Army General</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto has
removed the powerful army intelligence chief who handed out
millions of dollars in American military assistance to Afghan
rebels, officials said today.
   Lt. Gen. Hamid Gul, director general of Inter Services
Intelligence, was transferred to army headquarters in neighboring
Rawalpindi, a Defense Ministry spokesman said on condition of
anonymity. He reportedly has been replaced by retired army general
Shamsur Rahman Kallu, said the spokesman.
   Gul gave the military assistance to the Afghan anti-communist
resistance, headquartered in Pakistan. Both Pakistan and the United
States have helped finance guerrillas fighting the Soviet-supported
Afghan government.
   But Gul came under fire from moderate Afghan guerrilla groups
for giving most aid to hard-line Islamic fundamentalists, the
Hezb-e-Islami, led by Gulbadin Hekmatyar.
   He was also apparently behind the guerrilla's much-criticized
attack on the eastern Afghan city of Jalalabad after Soviet troops
ended their nine-year intervention in Afghanistan on Feb. 15.
Although some guerrilla leaders predicted Jalalabad would fall
quickly, the fighting has reached a stalemate.
   Gul was appointed by Pakistan's late president and military
leader Mohammed Zia Ul-Haq, who was killed last year in a plane
crash that investigators said was sabotage.
   Zia retired Kallu, the reported new army intellegence head,
after Kallu suggested Zia should forfeit the post of army chief of
staff while ruling the country as president.
   Analysts, who requested anonymity, said Gul's removal appears to
indicate Ms. Bhutto's growing strength in Pakistan, the first
Moslem nation in modern times to be governed by a woman.
</TEXT>
