<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Perks,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Most Deputies, No Limos &amp; $24 a Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the deputies who have come to Moscow for
the new Soviet parliament are traveling by bus, eating ordinary
hotel food and must survive on about $24 a day.
   In an article reflecting sensitivity to the issue of privileges
for the powerful, the Communist Party daily Pravda said
rank-and-file representatives in the 2,250-member Congress of
People's Deputies aren't getting special treatment, despite rumors
to the contrary.
   Citizens are concerned whether their representatives are
``getting special food parcels, black Volga sedans, presents and
special passes for the GUM central department store,'' the
newspaper said Thursday.
   The newspaper made no mention of existing privileges for top
party and government officials, many of whom are members of the new
Congress. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other members of the
ruling Politburo are entitled to chauffeured Zil limousines,
country houses, access to special food packets, stores, medical
care and other services not available to ordinary Soviets.
   Lesser officials may get smaller cars and somewhat limited
special treatment.
   Many successful candidates for the congress, notably political
maverick Boris N. Yeltsin, campaigned against special privileges
for top officials.
   ``Each deputy is paid a per diem of 15 rubles,'' Pravda said.
``The offered transportation is mainly by bus, but a lot of
deputies prefer to walk because hotels are located near the
Kremlin. In special cases, a car may be provided.''
   As for food, Pravda said, ``it is the same as it always was at
restaurants and buffets of the Moskva and Rossiya hotels.''
   The only ``perks'' for the deputies are free telephone calls to
their constituencies and well-stocked book stalls, the newspaper
said.
   ``Although some deputies were violently against even such a
small privilege,'' Pravda said, ``others believed that it might be
good for deputies from far places to bring a few good books to
their small villages and towns where such books are in short supply.
</TEXT>
