<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SovietGas     05-25 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Gas,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Physicians Say Soviet Troops Used World War I Gas on Civilians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American doctors returning from a week in Soviet
Georgia said today they believe the Soviet army used a World War
I-era toxic gas against demonstrators in the Georgian capital of
Tbilisi last month.
   Soviet officials have acknowledged that two forms of tear gas
were used to disperse a crowd of 8,000 to 10,000 holding an
all-night demonstration in Tbilisi's Lenin Square on April 9. At
least 20 people died during and after the protest.
   The American delegation from Physicians for Human Rights, a
1,300-member group based in Somerville, said it concluded on the
basis of interviews, medical records and videotapes that a third,
more potent gas was probably used.
   The group identified the gas as chloropicrin, first used during
World War I in 1916. Also known as nitrochloroform, it was once
used for crowd control in the United States but is now banned
because of its toxicity, the group said.
   The chemical, which causes potentially lethal chest irritation,
can be used in the United States only by licensed applicators as a
fumigant against insects, the group said.
   According to Georgian health officials, about 4,000 people
sought hospital treatment after the demonstration.
   Dr. Jonathan Fine, executive director of Physicians for Human
Rights, said the delegation concluded that ``the majority of those
hospitalized were probably suffering from the lingering effects of
toxic gas exposure.''
   But, he said, there is no conclusive evidence that chloropicrin
caused any of the deaths.
   Physicians For Human Rights was invited by Andrei Sakharov, the
Soviet physicist and human rights activist, and top Georgian health
officials to send a delegation to investigate the alleged use of
toxic chemicals in Georgia.
   The delegation, which spent May 17-22 in Soviet Georgia,
consisted of a leading toxicologist, Dr. Barry H. Rumack, director
of the Rocky Mountain Poison Center in Denver, Colo; Dr. Jennifer
Leaning, chief of emergency services for the Harvard Community
Health Plan in Cambridge, and Dr. Ruth A. Barron, a psychiatrist at
McLean Hospital in Belmont.
   The delegation met with officials of the Georgian Ministry of
Health and a large number of doctors who treated people injured in
the demonstration. The group also examined pathology reports of 20
known deaths, examined photographs and videotapes of the
demonstration and inspected canisters of gas allegedly used by
troops.
</TEXT>
