<HEAD>Japan to Replace its Ambassador to the United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry has selected Ryohei Murata as
the new ambassador to the United States, replacing Nobuo Matsunaga,
officials said Thursday.
   Murata, administrative vice foreign minister, is expected to
replace Matsunaga in September, said a ministry official, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Matsunaga became ambassador to the United States in January
1985, after serving as deputy foreign minister.
   The Asahi Shimbun newspaper reported the decision came because
the ministry thinks it is a good time for the personnel change now
that the Bush administration has settled in.
   The ministry has also decided to promote Takakazu Kuriyama,
deputy vice minister for political affairs, to administrative vice
minister in July, according to the Foreign Ministry.
   Hisashi Owada, ambassador to the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development will take Kuriyama's place, the
official said.
