<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Soviet-Threat     05-25 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-Threat,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Scare Forces Emergency Landing of Soviet Jetliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous bomb threat forced a Soviet jetliner
with 160 people aboard to make an emergency landing shortly after
takeoff from an airport in remote Central Asia, Tass said Thursday.
   The call was traced and the caller, who made the threat as a
joke, was arrested, the official news agency said.
   The Tupolev-154 had taken off Wednesday from Dzhambul, in the
Kazakstan republic 1,500 miles southeast of Moscow, when the
airport's information service received a telephone call warning of
a bomb on board, Tass said.
   ``By the time the aircraft returned to the airport, the security
forces were on full alert, ready to check the plane and trying to
trace the caller,'' said the city's militia chief, Maj. Gen. M.T.
Bersenev.
   A search of the aircraft found no bomb, and after a five-hour
delay, the passengers took another flight, he said.
   Airport security traced the call to V.V. Fan, 21, who was seeing
relatives off at the airport, Tass said.
   ``He made the call for fun and had no idea of the
consequences.'' It said Fan will have to pay all costs incurred by
the hoax.
