<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     05-25 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Clash with Hezbollah, Christian Troops; 1 Killed, 11 wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arab Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops battled pro-Iranian
militiamen and Christian army units Thursday in separate clashes
that left one person dead and 11 wounded in Beirut.
   Low-flying Israeli warplanes cracked the sound barrier over
Druse-held mountains southeast of the capital, but avoided
anti-aircraft fire, police said.
   Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun said Syria should pull
its troops out of Lebanon to ease Israel's withdrawal from a border
strip it has controlled for almost seven years.
   Police said militiamen of the Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem
Hezbollah, or Party of God, opened fire on a Syrian army jeep near
the Iranian Embassy in the seaside Ouzai district on Beirut's
southern edge.
   ``Other Syrian troops in the area fired back. The gunbattle sent
panicky residents crowding a nearby cooking gas distribution center
fleeing,'' said a police spokesman, who cannot be identified under
standing rules.
   He said one Hezbollah militiaman was killed in the 10-minute
shootout. One woman, a Hezbollah fighter and three Syrian soldiers
also were wounded, he said.
   Witnesses said the firefight began when the factions quarreled
about who had priority for butane gas refills. The cooking gas has
been in short supply since artillery duels began devastating Beirut
11 weeks ago in battles between Aoun's mainly Christian troops and
an alliance of Syrian troops and Druse militiamen.
   Six civilians were wounded in another clash, police said,
describing a 30-minute firefight with 106mm recoilless guns and
rocket-propelled grenades between Aoun's units and Syrian troops at
a crossing on the Green Line that divides the segregated capital.
   Shells also triggered fires in four cars near the western edge
of the crossing and halted traffic across the divide for two hours,
the police spokesman said.
   Each side accused the other of provoking the clash, which
violates the latest cease-fire called by the Arab League on May 11.
   Thursday's casualties raised the toll to 359 killed and 1,399
wounded since the fighting broke out March 8, two days after Aoun
imposed a blockade of militia-run ports south of Beirut to recoup
lost taxes of $10 million a year.
   Syrian gunners joined militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt
in shelling the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of the
capital.
   None of five cease-fires called by the Arab League has held
because the Syrians continued to shell the enclave's coastline to
prevent Aoun receiving supplies by sea.
   Aoun on Thursday reiterated a call for Syria to withdraw its
troops from Lebanon to strip Israel of any pretext for maintaining
control of a six- to 10-mile border strip.
   The Christian leader criticized the United States for not
pressuring Syrian troops to leave.
   Syria first intervened militarily in Lebanon in June 1976 and
now has 40,000 troops there under an Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   Aoun has declared a ``war of liberation'' to drive Syria out of
Lebanon. Syria says it will pull out only after the Israeli army
withdraws from its self-designated security zone.
</TEXT>
