<FIRST>r w PM-Soviets-Threat 1stLd-Writethru a0560 05-25 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviets-Threat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0560,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Retract Threat To Retain Missiles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Desk: Inserts new penultimate graf with State Dept. comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has retracted a threat to
retain some nuclear missiles banned under a 1987 treaty, U.S.
officials said today.
   The SS-23 missiles, which have a range of about 315 miles, or
just above the treaty threshold, were outlawed along with all U.S.
and Soviet missiles with a range of 312 to 3,125 miles.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said May 13 while
on a trip to West Germany that destruction of the SS-23s might be
stopped if the North Atlantic Treaty Organization deployed new
Lance missiles.
   The U.S.-built Lances have a range of about 75 miles, but after
the treaty was signed the United States and Britain launched a
campaign within NATO to more than triple the missile's range to
just below 300 miles.
   West Germany and several smaller countries in the Western
alliance registered objections to the modernization program and
called for U.S.-Soviet negotiations over the Lances and other
short-range nuclear arms.
   The issue will be aired in Brussels next Monday and Tuesday when
President Bush and the leaders of the 15 other NATO countries hold
a summit meeting in the Belgian capital.
   Shevardnadze's statement was interpreted as an attempt to
pressure the allies to postpone plans for making the Lance missiles
more potent. The United States and Britain also are resisting West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's call for negotiations as
potentially harmful to NATO's strategy.
   The State Department on May 15 denounced Shevardnadze's
statement as ``outlandish'' and Bush last Sunday said the threat
made ``clear that Soviet `new thinking' has not yet totally
overcome the old.''
   However, the day before Bush spoke Pravda, the Soviet Communist
party newspaper, had published an interview with Shevardnadze in
which he said ``no one in the U.S.S.R. intends to upset the INF
(Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces) treaty.''
   On Monday, the Soviet foreign ministry spokesman, Gennady
Gerasimov, gave similar assurances in Moscow.
   The Soviets ``called our attention'' to the retractions, a U.S.
official said today. The official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said it had been considered unlikely in any event that
the Soviets would not fulfill their obligation under the treaty to
destroy the missiles.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler today welcomed
Shevardnadze's statement and said Gerasimov's remarks had also been
noted.
   During negotiations that preceded the 1987 treaty the Soviets
resisted including the SS-23s, but relented. They have 200 missiles
in the category as well as trainers. All are supposed to be
destroyed by Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
