<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SovietUranium     05-25 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Uranium,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Official Says Soviets Selling More Nuclear Fuel To U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is increasing its sales of
enriched uranium to U.S. nuclear power plants and is ``not playing
fairly'' in the global market for this product, a senior Energy
Department official said Thursday.
   Henson Moore, the deputy energy secretary, said the Soviets now
have 8 percent of the U.S. market for enriched uranium, which is
used as a fuel for civilian nuclear power plants.
   ``There are plans for them to move even more aggressively to
take even more of our market right out from under our noses,''
Moore told a Capitol news conference at which House members
unveiled a bill aimed at revitalizing U.S. sales of enriched
uranium.
   Moore did not elaborate on his assertion that the Soviets were
``unfairly'' marketing their uranium enrichment services, except to
say it was difficult to determine their production costs because of
the closed nature of that society.
   Moore said the Bush administration had helped draft the House
bill, which would tranform the Energy Department's enriched uranium
operations into a government corporation. The United States has no
privately run uranium enrichment business.
   Rep. Marilyn Lloyd, D-Tenn., a lead sponsor of the bill, said
the U.S. share of the world market for sales of enriched uranium
has plunged from 100 percent 15 years ago to less than 50 percent
today. She said the decline would continue unless the operation
were made a government corporation.
   Rep. Bob McEwen, R-Ohio, a co-sponsor of the legislation, said
taking the Energy Department out of the business would give it more
flexibility, since its executives would not have to get
congressional approval before making key moves.
   The department runs its enrichment operations at plants in
Portsmouth, Ohio, and Paducah, Ky. These plants increase, or
``enrich,'' uranium-235 atoms beyond their natural concentration
for use in nuclear reactors, including those used to power Navy
ships and submarines.
</TEXT>
