<FIRST>r w AM-VietnamTrips     05-25 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam Trips,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vets to Defy Government Ban on Vietnam Trips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Vietnam veterans from Akron, Ohio, said
Thursday they will continue to organize group tours of Vietnam for
fellow veterans, in defiance of a Treasury Department order.
   The American Civil Liberties Union said it will defend the two
men if they are prosecuted.
   The Treasury Department sent a letter in February to Donald
Mills and John Myers, of the Akron chapter of Vietnam Veterans of
America, them to ``immediately terminate performing any activities
involving travel tours to Vietnam.''
   The department's letter said such activities are prohibited
under foreign assets control regulations and are punishable by a
fine of up to $50,000, imprisonment for up to 10 years, or both.
   The regulations were issued in March, 1988, in accordance with
economic embargo laws affecting Vietnam, Cambodia and North Korea
under the Trading with the Enemy act. They do not prevent a veteran
from traveling on his or her own.
   Mills and Myers have conducted the trips twice yearly since
1984. The seventh and most recent one was in February.
   The next trip is scheduled for November and will involve 21 or
22 veterans, paying $2,700 for three weeks in Vietnam including
travel, accomodations and meals, Mills said.
   He said it would be too difficult and costly for most veterans
to make the trip individually.
   Mills said he began the trips after going to Vietnam on a
permitted mission for the veterans' organization in 1984, and
finding that many veterans wanted to return to the scene of the war.
   ``I feel that going back to Vietnam is very beneficial to
them,'' he said. ``Every other veteran in history has been able to
return back to the battlefield that they served in. There is no
reason why we as veterans can't do the same thing.''
   Susan R. Brenda, legislative analyst with the Washington office
of the ACLU, joined Mills and Myers at a news conference and said,
``The Treasury Department is simply without authority to reach
directly into the First Amendment-protected activities of Americans
in the United States and prevent them from organizating towards the
perfectly legal end of travel to Vietnam.''
   In 1977, the Treasury Department issued regulations exempting
travel transactions from the embargo, and authorizing individuals
to spend funds incident to travel. The March, 1988, regulation
amended this by prohibiting Americans in the United States from
arranging or promoting such travel.
   ``We believe that an attempt to prosecute Vietnam veterans for
traveling back to Vietnam in an effort to learn about present day
Vietnam and heal old, deep wounds would be a grave mistake,'' Ms.
Brenda said. ``Should the government proceed along that course,
however, we will assist these veterans in their legal defense.''
   A telephone call was placed to Roger Bolton, assistant secretary
of the treasury for public affairs, for comment, but he was not
immediately available.
   Ms. Brenda said the ACLU is supporting a bill sponsored by Rep.
Howard Berman, D-Calif., that would prohibit the embargo laws from
being used to limit the travel of Americans abroad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Wages     05-25 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Wages,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wages of Major Japanese Firms Rise 5.11 Percent in 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average wage at 317 major Japanese companies
rose by 5.11 percent this year, compared with last year's 4.39
percent raise, the Japan Federation of Employees' Association said
Thursday.
   An association official attributed the bigger raises to a
domestic business boom.
   In April, labor unions demanded shorter working hours as well as
higher wages, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   He said 28.6 percent of the 317 companies agreed to shorten
working hours.
   According to Labor Ministry figures, Japanese workers took only
7.6 days of the 15.1 days of vacation to which they were entitled
in 1987. The government seeks to reduce average annual working
hours from 2,111 in 1988 to 1,800 by 1993.
   Workers are seeking to live more comfortably by working less and
gaining higher purchasing power with price stabilization, since
their monthly pay is nearly the highest in the world, the official
said.
   Management tries to hold down monthly wages while paying higher
bonuses _ twice a year _ if a company earns high profits, the
official said.
   Before the wage increase in April, the average monthly wage at
the 317 companies was $1,715, not including bonuses and overtime,
the official said.
   Those companies employ 2.43 million workers, or 5.4 percent of
Japan's 45 million-member labor force, the official said.
   The Institution of Labor Administration, a private research
center, said workers at 263 major firms will receive bonuses
averaging $4,400 this summer, up 7.7 percent from a year ago and
the highest in nine years.
</TEXT>
