<FIRST>r i AM-NATOSummit     05-25 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO Summit,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Chief Says Missile Dispute May Not Be Resolved Before Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-NATO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute over short-range nuclear
weapons policy may not be resolved before President Bush and the
other NATO leaders begin a summit next week, the alliance's chief
executive said Thursday.
   ``I've still some hope, but I'm not sure,'' Secretary-General
Manfred Woerner said in an interview at North Atlantic Treaty
Organization headquarters.
   Failure to settle the disagreement, which is primarily between
the United States and Germany, would be ``a rather unfortunate
situation, but it would not be a crisis or a catastrophe,'' he said.
   ``This alliance has lived with differences of opinion all
through its very successful lifetime, and if this question is not
solved today it will be solved tomorrow,'' the former West German
defense minister declared.
   Woerner added, however, that he would like the allies to
overcome their divisions ``and avoid the impression of being split
in an important matter.''
   Bush and leaders of the 15 other members will meet on Monday and
Tuesday for a 40th anniversary summit. It will be the first NATO
meeting for the president since his inauguration in January.
   NATO officials had hoped the meeting would be an example of
unity at a time when Mikhail S. Gorbachev's promises of reductions
in the Soviet military personel, arms and defense spending have
captured public imagination in Western Europe.
   The argument over short-range, or battlefield, nuclear weapons
has dominated preparations for the meeting, at which the leaders
are expected to plot NATO strategy.
   At issue is a West German demand for early negotiations with the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact on reducing such arms in Europe. Most of
NATO's short-range nuclear missiles are based in West Germany and
would be used there in case of war.
   The United States and Britain arguing that attention should
center on new talks in Vienna on reducing conventional weapons.
They also feel negotiations on tactical nuclear arms would lead
inevitably to removal of all such weapons from Europe.
   Woerner said any solution to the dispute must connect the
beginning of short-range nuclear negotiations to a specific stage
of the conventional arms discussions.
   As examples, he mentioned the end of the first phase, during
which bargaining positions are introduced, and when results of the
talks are implemented.
   Alliance officials have been seeking acceptable language on the
future role of short-range nuclear weapons for the Comprehensive
Concept, a blueprint for NATO planning on arms control and force
structures. The document is virtually complete except for a
paragraph on the contentious issue.
   Some diplomats have said they would like the document released,
probably Monday, even if teh dispute is not settled. Woerner would
not speculate on whether that would be done.
   He also said the summit's main task will be to map the future
NATO agenda, including a ``political message'' on relations with
the changing Soviet bloc.
   Bush and the others will consider ``how we want to cooperate
with the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe (and) make use of the
existing opportunities,'' Woerner said. ``Let me make it very clear
that this summit is not a missile summit.''
</TEXT>
