<HEAD>Prestigious Theater Producer Dies at 75</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgy Tovstonogov, one of the Soviet Union's
best-known producers who created ``a golden age of theater'' on the
Leningrad stage where he worked for more than 30 years, has died at
the age of 75.
   ``Many believe that Soviet culture has suffered an irretrievable
loss,'' Tass said Thursday in announcing the death of the chief
producer at the Leningrad Gorky Academic Bolshoi Drama Theater.
   It did not give the cause of death, but Leningrad TV news said
he died in a car accident.
   Tovstonogov, a native of Tbilisi, the capital of Soviet Georgia,
was named chief producer at the theater in 1956.
   ``At the Leningrad Academic Theater, Tovstonogov staged
productions which created a golden age of theater,'' Tass said.
   Among his most famed productions was a stage adaptation of
Fyodor Dostoyevsky's novel ``The Idiot.'' He also wrote books on
stage technique and theory.
   Tovstonogov's official death notice was signed by President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other Communist Party and government
leaders, a tribute to Tovstonogov's prominence.
   He also served for many years as a member of the Supreme Soviet
legislature and as secretary of the governing board of the
theaterworkers union, Tass said.
