<FIRST>u a PM-LATeachers 5thLd-Writethru a0561 05-25 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Teachers, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0561,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tentative Settlement in 11-Day Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with preparations for ratification vote,
more background on walkout. No pickup. Ratification vote set for 3 p.m.
EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE FITZPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers today tentatively agreed to end a
strike that has crippled the nation's second-largest school
district for 11 days.
   A 10-hour bargaining session ended about 1 a.m. with an
agreement on a three-year package that would give teachers an 8
percent raise per year and more say in shaping the curriculum in
the 594,000-student district.
   Teachers could be back in class by Friday if they approve the
pact, said union president Wayne Johnson. A ratification vote was
set for this afternoon.
   The union board of directors met to consider the agreement this
afternoon as ballots and copies of the offer were printed up for
the ratification vote.
   The union representing 22,000 of the district's 32,000 teachers
walked out May 15 in the city's first such strike in 19 years.
   About half the students stayed away from school, opting for the
beach, shopping malls or home. Many who did attend school were
treated to games, cartoons and filmstrips because there weren't
enough substitute teachers.
   Teachers had been earning between $23,440 and $43,319 a year,
depending on experience and education. The new pact would raise
those salaries in the first year of the contract to $25,316 and
$46,594.
   At the start of the walkout, the district was offering a 21.5
percent raise over three years; the union had sought a two-year, 21
percent increase.
   The contract would also give teachers a bigger hand in deciding
what goes on in their classrooms, with the district no longer
enjoying veto power on curriculum decisions.
   ``I hope this signals a new era of working together, of
cooperation, rather than confrontation,'' said school board
President Roberta Weintraub.
   But Johnson said the union made compromises that could become
stumbling blocks, including an agreement that teachers would work
extra hours to recover pay docked during the dispute. He would not
say whether he would recommend ratification.
   Johnson said the strike probably would leave no hard feelings
between the union and district but that it would take a
``considerable amount of time to heal those wounds'' between
striking teachers and those who crossed picket lines.
   On Wednesday, a striking teacher was booked on assault charges
for allegedly throwing a rock at a substitute. Sheriff's deputies
said the rock missed the teacher's car and struck a 12-year-old
girl outside a junior high school.
   Negotiations had collapsed Sunday with both sides accusing each
other of lying and bargaining in bad faith.
   But Johnson said the impasse was broken following meetings
Tuesday in Sacramento in which officials from both sides spoke to
Los Angeles-area lawmakers. The meetings laid groundwork for
Wednesday's negotiating session.
   Most classes wind up June 23, but some schools operate
year-round.
</TEXT>
