<FIRST>r a AM-SnakePayment     05-25 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Snake Payment,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cass County Man Ordered To Pay For Attorney With 18 Snakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOGANSPORT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of being represented in court
by a public defender in Cass County is, for one defendant, 18
snakes.
   Robert Haggerty, who breeds snakes for a living, told Cass
Circuit Court Judge Donald Leicht that he could not afford an
attorney to defend him against drug charges.
   So Leicht reviewed Haggerty's assets this week and ordered his
stock of snakes sold at auction to pay legal costs.
   Haggerty, 36, estimated the value of his pets at $3,800, said
court reporter Debbie Frey.
   The snakes were taken from Haggerty's apartment April 18 after
police arrested him on charges of possession of cocaine and
marijuana.
   Authorities had been called to the apartment by a neighbor
complaining of a burning smell. The odor turned out to be caused by
a makeshift electrical system through which Haggerty allegedly was
using the neighbor's electricity, investigators said.
   When authorities entered the apartment, they saw a sign on a
bedroom door that read: ``Don't enter this room. A rattlesnake is
out of the cage.''
   The officers called in animal control officer Dan Baker.
   ``There was no power in the house,'' said Baker, ``and I'm
walking around with a flashlight trying to find a snake.''
   They found 18 reptiles, all in aquariums. One other aquarium
housed 23 live mice _ the snakes' intended meals.
   The snakes included three poisonous rattlesnakes, an Arizona
mountain king, an albino black rattler and three boa constrictors.
One of the boas is pregnant and could give birth to about 50
offspring, each worth $80 to $100, Baker said.
   Authorities have been calling zoos around the Midwest but have
yet to receive an offer for the snakes.
</TEXT>
