<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navajo Police Clear Tribal Administration Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navajo police in riot gear and gas
masks removed dozens of supporters of suspended tribal Chairman
Peter MacDonald from an administration building they had occupied
for three days.
   Six people, including MacDonald's sister and three Tribal
Council members, were arrested when about 40 officers stormed the
building held by some 60 MacDonald supporters. The six were
released on their own recognizance this morning.
   MacDonald called Wednesday's arrests ``a disgrace to the Navajo
Nation.''
   ``This whole thing is a silly game. It's an embarrassment to the
chairman and the Navajo Nation,'' said Duane Beyal, a spokesman for
interim Chairman Leonard Haskie.
   Two people were treated at the scene for minor injuries, Beyal
said. One person was hit by a passing car and was held for
observation at a hospital.
   Those arrested were booked on various counts, including
resisting arrest, obstructing an officer and disorderly conduct,
according to police.
   Haskie was named interim chairman by the Tribal Council after it
placed MacDonald on leave in February. That followed allegations
before a U.S. Senate committee that MacDonald had taken kickbacks
from contractors.
   MacDonald had denied any wrongdoing and contests the legality of
the council's actions, but tribal courts have upheld his suspension.
