<FIRST>r a AM-SalaryFlap     05-25 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salary Flap,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Constable Wants Raise From $40 Per Month to $30,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAXAHACHIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Constable Gary Witherspoon wants Ellis
County to pay him $30,000 per year to do what he now does for $40
per month.
   County officials claim Witherspoon and Constable Bruce
Hollabaugh have virtually no duties.
   Witherspoon and Hollabaugh have sued, accusing county
commissioners of acting arbitrarily and unjustly by paying them
only $25 a month plus a $15 monthly car allowance. They want to be
paid what constables in comparable counties earn, as much as
$30,000.
   County Judge Penelope Redington says the county does not give
the constables so much as a pencil or a desk, let alone a car, a
staff and the other usual trappings that would indicate they carry
out official county business.
   State law requires each county with more than 30,000 people to
have at least four justice of the peace precincts, each with a
constable and a justice. Ellis County's population is estimated at
75,000.
   A constable, like a sheriff, is an elected official and a
certified peace officer authorized to carry a gun, make arrests and
serve court-related documents.
   In urban counties, constables usually serve notices of lawsuits
and other papers associated with the civil court system. They also
serve as bailiffs in the justice of the peace courts while the
sheriff runs the jail and carries out law enforcement functions.
   Each of Dallas County's eight constables is paid $49,152
annually plus a monthly car allowance of $350.
   But in rural counties, the sheriff is responsible for all jail
and court-related activities, and the constable's office is largely
symbolic.
   Ellis County Sheriff John Gage, who took office in January and
is paid $34,140 annually, said his deputies serve virtually all
warrants and civil court papers.
   Witherspoon said he also serves civil court papers, mostly those
coming from other counties. He declined to say how many papers he
serves monthly.
   A hearing is set for June 5 on Hollabaugh's suit; no date has
been set for Witherspoon's suit.
</TEXT>
