<FIRST>r a AM-Flight103-Movie     05-25 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103-Movie,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims' Relatives Agree to Television Movie on Flight 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE CENTRE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of people killed in the
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland have agreed to allow
filming of a television movie about how they've coped in the
aftermath of the terrorist attack.
   About 75 people, members of a relatives' group called Victims of
Pan Am Flight 103, voted unanimously last weekend to negotiate a
movie deal with Rainy Day Pictures.
   Peter Tsairis said some relatives reacted negatively at first,
but that they now believe a television movie could spur public
opinion toward changes in airline security regulations. The
survivors have been lobbying for stronger passenger safety measures
since the bombing.
   Rainy Day, a Los Angeles company, has produced one short drama,
called ``Lovestruck,'' which was nominated for an Academy Award in
1986, said Fredda Weiss, vice president of the company.
   Weiss said she conceived the idea for the Flight 103 movie after
meeting Tsairis, whose daughter Alexis was one of 35 Syracuse
University students killed in the bombing. A total of 270 people
were killed, including 11 on the ground in Lockerbie, Scotland.
   Weiss said the movie will deal only with events after the
bombing. She said she hopes to buy the story rights of about 25
relatives. Tsairis said all the victims' families will be offered
contracts and that money paid directly to the organization will go
to its lobbying efforts.
</TEXT>
