<FIRST>u w AM-AIDSBrochure Bjt   05-25 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Brochure, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>New AIDS Brochure Urges More Explicit Family Talks About Sex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government launched a campaign Thursday to
encourage parents to talk more explicitly with their children about
sex, saying their failure to do so has contributed to the AIDS
epidemic.
   ``The parent who does not take time today to teach his or her
child properly could end up later in a hospital room watching that
child die,'' said Dr. James O. Mason, assistant secretary of Health
and Human Services.
   Mason unveiled a $1.5 million campaign, involving a new brochure
and television advertisements, designed to spur family dialogues
about sex and AIDS.
   He said the program is taking a somewhat different tack,
stressing the advantages of sexual abstinence by youth, than
earlier AIDS-prevention campaigns, which put more emphasis on the
use of condoms as a ``safe sex'' option.
   ``Kids and condoms don't work awfully well,'' said Mason.
``We've done studies and we find that they act on impulse, they
don't plan ahead so a condom is there.''
   ``I think the fact that parents have not sat down and talked
with their children is the reason that we're today reaping the
harvest of HIV (human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS),''
said Mason. ``We're trying to bring the nation's parents into this
picture, and let them make the contribution that they are capable
of making.''
   Mason also blamed the lack of frank parental guidance for
contributing to other sexually transmitted diseases, and the 1
million teenage pregnancies annually.
   AIDS is an incurable disease that already has been diagnosed in
almost 95,000 Americans and caused more than 53,000 deaths.
Officials say that about 18,000 of the current cases involve people
aged 19 to 29 years. Since a person may be infected with HIV for up
to 10 years before AIDS symptoms appear, HHS scientists believe
many of the current cases result from teen-age infections.
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis W. Sullivan and Walter
R. Dowdle, acting director for the Centers for Disease Control,
concurred with Mason at the news conference that parental guidance
is essential if the epidemic is to be brought under control.
   ``Adults have to send a clear message to the young people they
care about,'' said Sullvan. ``No matter how young you are, you can
become infected with HIV if you have sex with an infected person.''
   The officials showed a series of short television commericials
that will be offered to the TV networks as public service
announcements. The ads themselves encourage parents to initiate
frank discussions with their children about AIDS, and give a
toll-free telephone number _ 1-800-342-AIDS _ that adults can call
to obtain copies of the more detailed brochure.
   The campaign calls for sexual abstinence by youth, monogamy for
adults, and the use of condoms for those who insist on having
multiple partners.
   The new guide includes special sections written for children of
various age levels. The Public Health Service is printing 500,000
copies in English and another 100,000 in Spanish. The television
ads are being produced in both languages.
   The guide's section for high school students advises ``don't do
drugs of any kind'' and offers five reasons for delaying sex,
including avoiding unwanted pregnancy.
   The guide for teens, however, goes on to say that ``when you
decide you are ready to become sexually active, do so only with one
uninfected partner in a mutually faithful, long-term relationship,
such as marriage.''
   Finally: ``If you have sexual intercourse outside of a mutually
faithful, long-term relationship with an uninfected partner, use a
condom. But remember that condoms are not foolproof and may break.
However, use a latex condom whenever having any type of sexual
intercourse.''
</TEXT>
