<HEAD>Agca Gets Two-Year Reduction in Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCONA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court decided Thursday to reduce by two
years the 30-year sentence given to Mehmet Ali Agca, who tried to
assassinate Pope John Paul II in 1981, the Italian news agency AGI
reported.
   A state prosecutor had called for a reduction in Agca's sentence
because of good behavior. Agca was awarded a reduction of 45 days
for every six months he had been in jail, or 720 days, AGI said.
   He received a life sentence, which in Italy is 30 years.
   Agca shot and wounded the pope on May 18, 1981, in St. Peter's
Square and wounded two American women. He has been serving his
sentence in prison in Ascoli Piceno, 85 miles northeast of Rome.
   He could be paroled in the year 2001.
