<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Murder     05-25 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Murder,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Sentence For Murderer Who Said Blacks Are Not Human</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white ex-policeman who said he
believes blacks are animals was sentenced to hang Thursday for
killing seven blacks and an Indian man in two shooting sprees he
hoped would provoke a race war.
   The killings by Barend Strydom were committed ``in an unfeeling
and cold-blooded manner that I have never before experienced or
heard of,'' said Justice Louis Harms. ``Mass murder or racial
murder will not be tolerated by this court.''
   In one of South Africa's most dramatic trials, relatives of the
black victims and white extremists supportive of Strydom crowded
into Pretoria Supreme Court for two weeks to hear testimony about
the 23-year-old defendant's racist beliefs.
   Harms convicted Strydom last week of killing seven people and
wounding 15 blacks in a rampage on the sidewalks of downtown
Pretoria on Nov. 15. A week earlier, Strydom said he killed a black
woman and wounded another at a squatter camp, using them as target
practice to determine whether he was ready for a larger-scale
massacre.
   After the sentencing, the white-supremacist Boerestaat Party
said it will campaign for clemency for Strydom. Boerestaat leader
Robert von Tonder said Strydom is ``a sensitive Afrikaner patriot.''
   Standing impassively for an hour while Harms read his ruling,
Strydom gulped a glass of water when the sentence was pronounced,
then was escorted to a police van and driven to death row at
Pretoria Central Prison.
   Police vehicles blockaded streets around the courthouse, and
scores of officers stood guard. They used dogs to control several
hundred people, mostly black, who waited in a park across the road.
   Harms gave Strydom eight death sentences and 30 years in prison
for 16 counts of attempted murder. No execution date was set, and
defense lawyers said they would appeal.
   Harms thanked Simon Mkonduleli, a black taxi driver who grabbed
Strydom's pistol to halt the Nov. 15 massacre. Mkonduleli said he
has been harassed and threatened by white men several times since
the rampage, including after Thursday's court session.
   Strydom had acknowledged that he smiled as he shot his victims,
telling the court last week, ``I'm a friendly person.''
   He testified he fired the first shots in a ``war of freedom''
for whites threatened by the country's black majority.
   ``I do not think blacks are human beings,'' he said.
   State-appointed psychiatrists concluded Strydom was sane.
   His father, also a former policeman, testified he taught his
children that blacks were animals.
   Defense lawyer Johan Engelbrecht argued Strydom viewed the
killings as self-defense, saying: ``He fears blacks, fears that the
government will yield and that whites will be sold out.''
   Harms drew a parallel between Strydom's case and that of Robert
McBride, a mixed-race guerrilla of the African National Congress
who argued he was taught to hate whites. McBride is on death row
after being sentenced for planting a bomb that killed three women
in 1986.
   The death sentence is mandatory for murder in South Africa
unless the judge determines there are mitigating circumstances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
