<DOCNO> AP890525-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Economy Bjt   05-25 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, Bjt,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reports Economy Growing at Moderate Rate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy grew at a moderate 4.3
percent annual rate in the first three months of the year, the
government said Thursday in a report which economists and the Bush
administration saw as a sign the country's record peacetime
expansion is continuing.
   The Commerce Department's revision in the first-quarter gross
national product to well below its original 5.5 percent estimate
came amid worries that Federal Reserve efforts to stem inflation
could move the economy into a recession.
   But Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said the report shows
that ``Fed policy over the past year appears to be succeeding in
steering the economy to a more moderate, but sustainable, growth
path.''
   Michael Boskin, chairman of President Bush's Council of Economic
Advisers, said the report made him ``confident the economy will
continue (its) growth, inflation will be contained and the economy
will remain solid.''
   Some private economists said flatly that the report rules out
any recession for at least the remainder of the year. A survey of
economic forecasting experts conducted before the latest GNP
release also discounted any recession in 1989.
   ``Not only is there no sign of a recession in sight,'' said
Allen Sinai of the Boston Co., ``but the question now is whether we
will get a significant rebound in the second and third quarters.''
   Michael Evans of Evans Economics, Inc., agreed that ``the last
chance for a recession this year has just evaporated.
   ``The economy is in amazingly good shape,'' he said. ``There
seems to be no signs of a serious slowdown.''
   Both the 4.3 percent growth rate and the earlier 5.5 percent
estimate included the statistical effects of last year's drought on
the farm sector. Removing that sector means the non-farm economy
grew at only a 1.8 percent rate, compared with the earlier estimate
of 3.5 percent. This is the slowest quarterly non-farm GNP advance
in more than two years.
   Not all economists were encouraged by the report, however.
Lawrence A. Hunter, deputy chief economist for the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said the non-farm growth rate means ``we have fallen
through the Fed's target for a `soft landing' and would be heading
directly to a `hard fall.'''
   The new report did not change the earlier 5 percent annual
inflation rate in the first quarter, compared with 4.2 percent in
the previous October-December period.
   As the Commerce Department announced the latest GNP, the
National Association of Business Economists released a survey
predicting a dramatic slowing in economic growth but also without
any recession during the remainder of the year.
   NABE President Jay N. Woodworth said in releasing the report
that the 54 forecasting experts in the survey ``might be just a
trace more optimistic today than they had said earlier this month''
when the survey was conducted.
   But the NABE survey suggested a moderate increase in
unemployment and higher inflation due to rising food and energy
prices.
   In yet another economic report, the National Association of
Realtors said rising mortgage rates continued their toll on
existing home sales. Sales fell by 1.1 percent in April, the fourth
consecutive monthly decline, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 3.36 million units, the report said. It was the slowest annual
rate since February 1988.
   Fed efforts to stem inflation by tightening credit have been
blamed for rising interest rates.
   The Commerce Department also reported Thursday that
first-quarter, after-tax corporate profits were off 1.7 percent.
The decline follows a 3.2 percent increase in 1988's last quarter
and was the biggest drop since a 2.5 percent fall in the fourth
quarter of 1987.
   In its GNP report, Commerce said the economy grew $43.1 billion
to $4.077 trillion in the first quarter when adjusted for
inflation. Without the inflation adjustment, growth increased $106
billion to $5.105 trillion _ the first quarter the GNP topped the
$5 trillion mark.
   A slower inventory build-up together with a faster export pace
than previously believed was most responsible for the downward
revision in the first-quarter GNP.
   The smaller inventory list was seen as a plus for the economy
because large build-ups without accompanying sales often mean job
layoffs.
   And the increased exports combined with fewer imports resulted
in a better-than-expected decline in the trade deficit. The report
said the deficit narrowed at an annual rate of $17.6 billion, the
first improvement since the spring of 1988. Exports in the
January-March quarter rose at a 15.3 percent annual rate compared
with a 0.9 percent increase in imports.
</TEXT>
