<FIRST>r a AM-BoatingAccident     05-25 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boating Accident,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Dead, One Missing After Lake Michigan Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Christyne is cq in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST CHICAGO, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carla Brouwenstyn says she ``prayed
like I never prayed before'' for hours in Lake Michigan's chilly
and turbulent waters, trying in vain to save the lives of two
companions when their boat wrecked.
   Two people were dead and one missing after a 23-foot powerboat
crashed into a concrete breakwater Tuesday night outside Indiana
Harbor, authorities said. Ms. Brouwenstyn and the boat's owner
survived.
   Ms. Brouwenstyn, 21, of Highland, was found by a fisherman
Wednesday morning, more than eight hours after the wreck, said
Deputy Police Chief Angelo Machuca.
   She was found clinging to the body of one of her friends,
21-year-old Rhonda Russell of Hammond, Machuca said. She had also
tried through the night to hang onto another friend, Christyne
Mason, 21, of Hammond, but lost her grip in the choppy, 52-degree
water. Ms. Mason was missing and presumed dead, authorities said.
The search for her body resumed Thursday.
   ``This brave lady, Carla, trying to hold on to her friends, was
in the water from 10 o'clock last night until the fisherman found
her at 6:30,'' Machuca said.
   The boat's owner, Gary Gaskin, 25, also of Hobart, was found
alive, hanging onto the damaged boat, which had drifted away from
where Ms. Brouwenstyn were found, Machuca said. But the driver of
the boat, John Clifford, 25, of Hobart, was found dead on the boat.
   Ms. Brouwenstyn was listed serious but stable condition Thursday
at St. Catherine Hospital in East Chicago. Gaskin was listed in
guarded condition at St. Mary's Medical Center in Gary.
   Brenda Brouwenstyn said her sister was ``a pretty strong girl. I
never would have made it.''
   ``I prayed like I never prayed before,'' the family quoted Ms.
Brouwenstyn as saying from her hospital bed. ``I kept asking for
God's help. I will have a different attitude on life from now on.''
   The five left from Portage on Tuesday night for a trip to
Chicago, but the choppy water changed their plans.
   ``About 10 o'clock the water started getting rough, and they
turned around to come back,'' Machuca said. ``The boat hit the
breakwall at the very north end of Inland Steel in our city. The
boat broke up.''
</TEXT>
