<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-25 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 12:29 p.m. Saturday, the sun here will be
straight overhead. For that moment skinny people, flagpoles and
buildings will cast no shadow.
   Among the 50 states, it's a phenomenon unique to Hawaii,
occurring twice a year because it's in the tropics.
   To mark the occasion, the Bishop Museum Planetarium issued a
tongue-in-cheek public advisory that:
   _It's a good day for taking outdoor group photographs, because
nobody will be in anybody else's shadow.
   _You can safely wax the sides of your car.
   _Moss won't be able to tell which side of the tree to grow on.
   _Bald men should stay indoors, wear hats or add extra sunscreen.
   _People who tell time with a sundial should get a wristwatch.
   _Shadow boxers should sit out the round.
   _You can play ``Who's shadow is the longest?'' with your tallest
friend and not lose.
   _It's a good time to wash and hang fadable fabrics on the
clothesline.
   The next no-shadow moment will be 12:37 p.m., July 15.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YPSILANTI, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So, like, there's this totally
outrageous showcase out in the hall with stuff like a McDonald's
hamburger for 19 cents and a book with this wicked Mustang
convertible that sold for, like, $3,000 new.
   Awesome.
   Such 20-year-old memorabilia is the talk of Willow Run High
School, where members of the Class of 1989 helped the Class of 1969
outfit a display case in preparation for an Aug.5 reunion.
   The display case also contains items such as a 1969 diploma, the
homecoming queen's tiara, items from the senior class trip to New
York, copies of the student newspaper and two prom dresses.
   ``The girls can't believe we wore that kind of junk,'' said
Karen Borgman, a member of the reunion committee. ``The students
and teachers have come up and said this is the best showcase. It's
really hit the kids.''
   The 342 students who attended Willow Run from 1965-69 have been
invited to the reunion in Ann Arbor.
   ``The message is, keep the friendships you have now and be proud
of where you came from,'' Borgman said. ``We're still proud to be
the Class of '69 and to come back.''
</TEXT>
