<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-WhyFoley     05-25 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Why Foley,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley, Who Would Succeed Wright, a Striking Contrast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley offers a
striking contrast to Speaker Jim Wright and that is a big reason
why so many congressmen _ Republicans as well as Democrats _ hope
he soon will become speaker.
   As House members scattered Thursday at the start of a long
Memorial Day weekend, there was a clear sense that the ethics
controversy surrounding Wright was overwhelming him and forcing him
to step down.
   ``I know of no plans for the speaker to retire,'' said Foley who
flew to Seattle to attend the funeral of former Democratic Sen.
Warren Magnuson. ``The speaker, as far as I know, intends to go
forward now with the regular process of the evidentiary hearing.''
   That was something Democrats clearly hoped was not the case. In
fact, some seemed eager to have Foley take over the leadership of
the House.
   ``There is near unanimity of support for Tom Foley,'' said Rep.
Pat Williams, D-Mont.
   During the period of turmoil and tension in the House, why is
the Washington congressman considered such a shoo-in to be the next
speaker?
   Part of the answer is tradition. As majority leader, Foley
occupies the post that customarily is the stepping-stone to the
speakership. Wright moved up after serving as majority leader and
so did his predecessor, Thomas P. O'Neil, as did his predecessor,
Carl Albert, and his, John McCormack.
   But that logic of succession doesn't fully account for Foley's
unique standing during this troubled time.
   It's more a case of perception.
   ``The speaker's problems have translated into institutional
problems for all of us,'' said Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas.
``The institution is getting a black eye.''
   During the little more than two years he has been speaker,
Wright proved a strong leader who gave the Democrats the initiative
on many issues during the last two years of Ronald Reagan's
presidency, though he was not given high marks for his more recent
handling of the unsuccessful push for a congressional pay raise.
   ``I think when the history of the House in this era is written,
Jim Wright's tenure in the 100th Congress will be compared with
Henry Clay in the 12th Congress or Joe Cannon in the 58th or Sam
Rayburn in the 76th,'' said Rep. Chester Atkins, D-Mass., a member
of the House ethics committee.
   ``But we're not here to stand in judgment of Jim Wright's
speakership,'' went on Atkins.
   What the committee was examining was the speaker's book deal,
his oil well deal, his partnership with Texas businessman George
Mallick.
   What finally confronted the Democrats were the allegations _
accurate or not _ that Wright profited from his power at the
pinnacle of the House.
   Ironically, as the case against Wright began to unfold early in
the 101st Congress, the Senate was flourishing under new
leadership, that of Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine.
   If anyone in the House leadership could be compared to Mitchell,
it was Foley. Both men come across as down-to-earth types, who
adhere to principles without being unduly partisan. Both are
effective on television.
   Some of the highest praise for Foley comes from Republicans.
   ``Tom Foley is just a very able, capable individual,'' said Rep.
Bob Michel of Illinois, the House Republican leader. ``He's well
liked on our side, and he's also recognized as a very formidable
opponent, one who will state the case well, and he is eminently
fair.''
   ``He's a man of total integrity,'' said Senate GOP leader Bob
Dole of Kansas.
   One rainy October evening in Seattle during the 1988
presidential campaign provided an example of Foley's self-effacing
style.
   Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis had just addressed a huge
downtown crowd. The speech over, the campaign retinue raced through
the downpour to the waiting vehicles.
   A rain-soaked Foley, a large, gray-haired bear of a man,
approached a Dukakis staff car and was waived away.
   As he started walking away, reporters in the next car invited
him to join them. He did and, laughing off the incident, regaled
them with stories of similar occasions.
   Already one of the nation's most powerful politicians, he
demonstrated an ability to avoid taking himself too seriously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
