<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--AIDSStudy     05-25 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--AIDS Study,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Learning More About What Does and Doesn't Cause AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Brochure, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Release After 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More and more Americans know people can get AIDS
from sexual intercourse with an infected person but not from casual
contact with an AIDS victim, a federal study released Thursday
shows.
   The study, based on about 3,500 interviews a month from August
1987 to August 1988 and conducted by the federal Centers for
Disease Control's National Center for Health Statistics, indicates
that Americans think they know more about AIDS than before and that
they may be right.
   But it may be years before the improvement shows up in a drop in
reported new AIDS cases, because some people can be infected with
the AIDS virus for 10 years before symptoms appear, federal
researchers say.
   The CDC's Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report released
Thursday in Atlanta said the overall gain in knowledge about
acquired immune deficiency syndrome coincides with a national
public awareness campaign.
   It said the effect of one element of the campaign, the mailing
of an AIDS fact brochure to most American households in May and
June of 1988, is being analyzed.
   The report said the percentage of parents who discussed AIDS
with their children remained constant at about 60 percent but that
those reporting their children had AIDS education in schools was up
from 36 percent to 59 percent.
   The adults correctly answering it was ``definitely true'' that
AIDS was an infectious disease caused by a virus rose from 44
percent to 64 percent.
   Other study findings included:
   _Those who knew it is very unlikely or impossible to contract
AIDS by working near someone who has the disease increased from 53
percent to 67 percent.
   _The percentage of people saying the knew ``a lot'' or ``some''
about AIDS increased from 60 to 66 percent.
   _Those correctly answering that it is ``definitely true'' that
AIDS can be transmitted through intercourse with an infected person
increased from 75 percent to about 85 percent.
</TEXT>
