<FIRST>r a AM-JuvenileDressCode     05-25 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Juvenile Dress Code,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>11-Year-Old Confined For Night For Refusing To Wear Tie To Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old boy appearing in
juvenile court for violating terms of a sentence was ordered locked
up for a night because he refused to wear a tie.
   The boy, whose name was not released because of his age,
appeared in court Tuesday wearing a T-shirt and shorts, in
violation of Circuit Judge Robert Foster's dress code for juvenile
court.
   The judge instituted the dress code about a year ago, telling
boys to wear neckties and trousers and girls to wear slacks or
dresses. Foster said this was the first time a child had been
detained for violating the code.
   The boy, convicted of petty theft, was brought into court
Tuesday for violating his sentence, which required him to work 40
hours in the Youth Mediation Program.
   Foster said the boy had been told at least five times that he
must wear a tie and slacks to court and had done so in past court
appearances.
   However, when the youth appeared Tuesday, his mother said he had
refused to wear a tie and the shirt she had ironed for him.
   Foster ordered the boy to spend the night at the detention
center and told the mother to take the shirt and tie to the
detention center. The boy returned to court Wednesday in the proper
attire.
</TEXT>
