<HEAD>Eds: SUBS Maggi McNellis item to CORRECT that her husband was not
member of communications industry family.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Maggi McNellis</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maggi Newhouse, who was host of radio and
television talk shows under the name of Maggi McNellis, died
Wednesday of heart failure at her home in Manhattan. She was 71.
   Mrs. Newhouse was born in Chicago and began her career as a
supper club singer. She moved to radio in 1943 as host of ``The
Maggi McNellis Show'' and ``Maggi's Private Wire.''
   She also participated in ``Leave It to the Girls,'' a radio show
that offered women advice on romance and marriage. She later became
host of a television version of the show, and of television's
``Maggi McNellis Show'' and ``Maggi's Magazine.''
   Her husband, Clyde M. Newhouse, an art gallery owner, died in
1986. She is survived by a daughter, a brother and a grandson.
