<SECOND>AM-Lao-US Excavation,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Laos Dig Crash Site For Lost Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Laos are about to begin
excavating an airplane crash site where American servicemen may
have died during the Vietnam War, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   The excavation, scheduled to begin Friday, will be the sixth
such joint project since the end of the war. Previous excavations
have resulted in the recovery of remains that were later identified
by a U.S. laboratory.
   ``The United States government appreciates this step by the Lao
government toward establishing a year-round program of cooperative
efforts to resolve the POW-MIA issue,'' the Pentagon said.
   The last excavation was conducted in March. The site about to be
searched was surveyed in December 1988, and is located in the
Savannakhet Province in southern Laos.
