<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     05-25 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rising Mortgage Rates Slow Home Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising mortgage rates slowed the sale of
existing homes in April to the worst pace in 14 months, the
National Association of Realtors reported Thursday.
   The trade group said sales of single-family homes declined last
month to an annual rate of 3.36 million units, down 1.1 percent
from March, off 4.3 percent from a year ago, and the lowest figure
since February of 1988.
   ``Higher interest rates have stymied efforts of renters to
become homeowners,'' NAR President Ira Gribin said.
   ``Trade-up buyers, in large part, are driving the market now,''
he added. ``First-time buyers, with no equity and a tight budget,
continue to be left behind, particularly in high-cost areas.''
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said that interest on
fixed-rate conventional mortgages ranged between 11.07 percent and
11.03 percent in April, up more than 0.5 percent from a year ago.
The interest-rate increase results from Federal Reserve efforts to
stem inflation by tightening credit.
   The NAR said a 7.5 percent
   drop in existing home sales in the West, which had recently
experienced heavy resale activity, led the April decline. And there
was flat activity in the South, which previously had the highest
sales volume.
   Sales in the West declined to an annual pace of 620,00 homes; in
the South the rate remained 1.27 million units yearly.
   Sales actually rose 7 percent in the Northeast, to an annual
rate of 610,000 units, and were up 2.3 percent in the Midwest, to a
rate of 890,000 units.
   The national median price for existing single-family homes was
$93,500 in April, the NAR said. That was up 6.3 percent from a year
ago and $1,500 higher than in March. Analysts said this primarily
reflected the higher costs of move-up homes.
</TEXT>
