<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CorporateProfits     05-25 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corporate Profits,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corporate After-Tax Profits Down in First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations' after-tax profits fell 1.7
percent in the first quarter of 1989, the biggest decline in more
than a year, the government said Thursday.
   In a report indicating earnings are slowing along with the
economy, the Commerce Department said after-tax profits dipped to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $171.6 billion during the first
quarter, down from $174.5 billion during the previous three-month
period.
   Decreases in profits were widespread within manufacturing
industries, while earnings in trade, transportation, public
utilities and other non-manufacturing industries also fell.
   After-tax profits had risen 14.7 percent during 1988, reflecting
the robust economic growth that occurred last year, but earnings
are widely expected to fade this year as the economy slows and
labor costs rise.
   Economist Allen Sinai of the Boston Co. called it a ``standard
late-stage business expansion phenomenon'' for earnings to fall as
an economic recovery ages.
   The first-quarter falloff in after-tax profits was the biggest
drop since a 2.5 decline registered in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   ``The momentum of growth in profits in the first quarter showed
significant signs of beginning to fade and that will be the story
on profits for the next year,'' Sinai predicted.
   Among the details in the profits report:
   _Before-tax profits edged down 0.2 percent last quarter, to a
seasonally adjusted annual level of $319.9 billion, after rising
2.1 percent during the previous three-month period.
   _Corporate profits, after adjusting for depreciation and
inventories, fell 6.3 percent last quarter, to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $319.3 billion, after rising 3.3 percent in
the fourth quarter.
   _Corporate cash flows, a measurement intended to show the funds
corporations have for investment, fell 5.3 percent last quarter, to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $388.1 billion, after rising
3.4 percent during the fourth quarter.
   _Dividend payments to stockholders rose 2.9 percent in the first
quarter, to an annual rate of $111.1 billion, following a 2.2
percent rise in the fourth quarter.
</TEXT>
