<FIRST>r w AM-Coelho     05-25 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coelho,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Democrats Worry Ethics Questions Could Make Coelho a Political
Target</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some House Democrats worried Thursday that
ethics questions raised about House Majority Whip Tony Coelho could
make him an inviting political target if the feisty Californian
becomes majority leader.
   But the former Democratic congressional campaign chairman, who
dispensed money for many members' successful re-election campaigns,
still enjoys significant backing among colleagues.
   Coelho could face a challenge from Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.,
who was an unsuccessful presidential candidate last year. One
Democratic member, who spoke only on condition he not be named,
said ``there's a good chance'' Gephardt would run for majority
leader.
   Democrats said in interviews their problems could be compounded
if Speaker Jim Wright resigned because of ethics charges, and _
after Rep. Thomas Foley, D-Wash., moved from majority leader to
speaker _ Coelho was sitting in the No. 2 spot with an ethics cloud
over his head.
   Some colleagues suggested that a way out would be to quickly
elect Foley as speaker and allow several weeks to pass before
deciding on other leadership positions.
   ``We must make sure nobody who is in a replacement mode has any
impediments that cause problems,'' said Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan.
``If we have a secondary ethics problem, it could be very
catastrophic for our party in the House. We're on somewhat shaky
footing now and need to re-establish our stability.''
   Glickman said a cooling-off period after election of Foley would
allow races to develop and time to gauge reaction to Coelho's
ethics problems.
   News stories have detailed, and Coelho has confirmed, that a
California savings and loan official purchased a $100,000
high-yield junk bond for the lawmaker in 1986 _ after Coelho found
himself unable to finance the purchase himself.
   A month later, the bank official sold the bond to Coelho for the
initial offering price, which saved the lawmaker about $4,000
compared with the market price at the time.
   House rules prohibit members from accepting gifts from anyone
with a direct interest in legislation. Coelho said he did not
violate House rules, and asked the ethics committee to review the
transaction.
   On Thursday, the Los Angeles Times reported the Justice
Department is conducting a preliminary criminal investigation of
whether Coelho received favors from Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
the firm that issued the junk bond.
   Coelho said in a statement, ``I am confident the story is
inaccurate and I so advised the Los Angeles Times, which chose to
go ahead with the story anyway. In Washington's current atmosphere,
such stories based on rumors or leaks are perhaps inevitable, but
no less regrettable.''
   The Associated Press reported earlier this week that Coelho
owned an interest in a dairy management company at the same time he
was pushing legislation to help maintain the profitability of some
dairy farms.
   Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., said House Democrats should not
immediately fill the majority leader, whip and caucus chairman
positions should Wright resign, but added the Coelho camp wants the
incumbents to quickly move up the ladder.
   Williams said some members believe Coelho has ``put a lid on the
junk bond matter,'' but when informed of the story on a possible
criminal probe, said, ``any continuation of the investigation ...
would of course have a negative effect on (his) chances.''
   Coelho's strongest support appeared to come from his own
California Democratic delegation, whose chairman, Rep. Don Edwards,
said, ``We just think Tony has been the best whip in the history of
the House, and deserves to be majority leader.''
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., said of Coelho's ethics
questions, ``People want answers, but I don't see a panic about it
at all.''
   And Rep. George Brown, D-Calif., a Coelho supporter, said that
``members will take into consideration the public reaction to the
situation.''
</TEXT>
