05-25 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pipeline Explosion, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0653-a0654,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gas Pipeline Explodes at Train Derailment Site, Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: COMBINES pvs urgent series. Minor editing throughout.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gasoline pipeline exploded today
in a cauldron of flames that engulfed the neighborhood where a
runaway train demolished a row of houses May 12. At least two
people were killed, 24 injured and seven homes destroyed, officials
said.
   Flames reached 500 feet into the sky, and black and gray smoke
towered thousands of feet following the blast at 8:11 a.m. in the
14-inch line.
   ``My windows started shattering. The houses were on fire, the
cars. One man ran out. He was in flames,'' said June Chung, whose
home in Rialto overlooks the scene about a mile away.
   ``It's just a terrible scene. It looks like a bomb went off over
Duffy Street,'' said City Attorney James Penman.
   The explosion occurred in a pipeline buried six feet below the
site of the train wreck earlier this month. The pipeline had been
inspected and reopened by Calnev Pipeline Co. several days ago
after the city was assured it was safe, Penman said.
   ``Obviously, in this case, the experts were wrong. Calnev has
got a lot of explaining to do,'' said Penman.
   At least two people died in the blast, city fire spokesman Paul
Allaire said.
   Sgt. Dan Hernandez said seven homes were destroyed by flames
across the street from where the freight train destroyed six houses
and damaged five earlier this month. Twenty homes threatened by the
inferno were evacuated, Penman said.
   Seven people who were burned, one seriously, were at San
Bernardino County Medical Center, said Eleanor Borkowski, a
spokeswoman. Five more people were being treated for minor injuries
at St. Bernardine's hospital, and 12 others at San Bernardino
Community Hospital, officials said.
   ``There's some people we are looking for,'' said Mayor Evlyn
Wilcox as she comforted a weeping woman who said she lost
everything.
   On May 12, a 69-car Southern Pacific freight train jumped the
tracks on a mountain pass at 90 mph, killing two crew members and
two boys in a home.
   Part of the pipeline, which carries fuel from Los Angeles-area
refineries to Las Vegas, was exposed after the train wreck, when
crews had to move earth to salvage the freight cars. The
neighborhood was evacuated for several days for fear the line had
been weakened.
   Railroad spokesman Jerry Pera said it is possible the
catapulting freight cars damaged the underground pipeline.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators who probed
the train wreck were returning. ``Obviously, we have to see if
there's a connection,'' said NTSB spokesman Alan Pollock in
Washington.
   ``I'm out of my house again. We don't have nowhere to go,'' said
LaRuth Littlejohn, 51, who lives a block from the explosion site
and was evacuated during the train wreck.
   Mrs. Littlejohn said she saw one girl burned and helped carry
away a woman hurt when her house exploded.
   ``I was astounded,'' said Kevin Chafee, describing the explosion
and fire from six miles away. ``There's a huge tower of black smoke
going up over San Bernardino. I thought downtown San Bernardino was
on fire.''
   A witness Steve Blade, reporting from 200 feet away, said six
homes were engulfed in flames moments after the explosion.
   It wasn't immediately known how much gas was burning, said Jed
Robinson, Calnev general manager.
   The flow of gas was shut off when an automatic alarm signaled a
drop in pressure, Robinson said. ``The fact the fire has continued
to burn makes us think there might be a leak in the check valve,''
he said.
   The line carries gasoline, diesel and jet fuel from a tank farm
in Colton, which is several miles from the blaze site, to southern
Nevada.
</TEXT>
