<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1546EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-People     05-25 0898</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0933</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENID, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Lee Majors says he didn't hesitate to
invest more than $3 million in two oil-patch businesses because he
considered their president and chief operating officer a friend.
   Television's former ``Six Million Dollar Man'' now claims he
lost $1.5 million because of his investments in two Enid
oil-drilling-rig companies operated by Vaughn Good.
   He appeared in court Wednesday to testify on a lawsuit that he
and investor Ray Davis filed against Good and his wife, Laura. The
two men are seeking $3 million in actual damages plus unspecified
punitive damages.
   Majors said Good was a father figure to him after they met in
1971 when Good was his host during the Grand National Quail Hunt,
which each year draws celebrities to Enid.
   The actor testified that he was flattered in July 1980 when Good
asked him to invest in one of his companies. Without contacting his
business manager, Majors said, he signed a personal line of credit
of $600,000 to get a 30 percent share in the company. Two months
later, Majors said, he invested $2.6 million in a second drilling
company operated by Good.
   He testified that he would not have invested in either company
had he known of a number of questionable financial transactions
that he claimed eventually cost him $1.5 million.
   In their lawsuit, Majors and Davis claim that the Goods used
company money to pay personal bills and buy expensive oil-field
equipment only to turn around and sell it and keep the profit for
themselves.
   The Goods' attorney, Stephen Jones, claimed the legal dispute
stems from ``sour grapes,'' partly because of the drop in oil
prices after the 1982 oil bust. The trial on the lawsuit continued
Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger Ebert gives a great big thumb's-up to
alphabetizing his video collection; Gene Siskel says deep-six that
A-to-Z nonsense.
   The two Chicago-based movie reviewers, famed for their bickering
on their syndicated television show, differ in their video habits
as well. Siskel collects old-time musicals, old TV game shows and
classic baseball footage; Ebert amasses opera, Hitchock, Japanese
movies and obscure examples of the ``film noir'' genre.
   Both prefer laser discs to tape; both have such films as
``Notorious,'' ``Raging Bull'' and ``Citizen Kane'' in their troves.
   But while Siskel owns one X-rated feature _ ``Last Tango in
Paris'' _ Ebert has a complete collection of the sexploitation
films of Russ Meyer, for whom he once wrote a screenplay, ``Beyond
the Valley of the Dolls'' of 1970.
   ``By definition, if I like a movie, it can't be bad,'' Ebert
says in the June issue of Self magazine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COCOA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A writer who claimed the makers of the
1986 hit movie ``Hoosiers'' stole his screenplay has agreed to
settle his 2-year-old lawsuit.
   Michael Lilly, 47, had sought $1 million from Hemdale Film
Corp., claiming ``Hoosiers,'' starring Gene Hackman and Dennis
Hopper, was based on his script ``Bird Man of Flat Gap.''
   ``There are no hurt feelings. It's an excellent story,'' Lilly
said after the settlement was announced. Lilly, who lives in Cocoa
Beach, said the settlement this week amounted to less than $100,000.
   Under the terms, Lilly agreed to drop the appeal, and Hemdale
will not be required to acknowledge whether the film was based on
Lilly's script.
   His script involved a new high school basketball coach in a
rural mining town in Kentucky. ``Hoosiers'' takes place in a town
in Indiana.
   In both stories, the team's coach falls in love with a teacher,
the son of the town drunk is the team's key player, and the
underdogs win the state championship because of the final shot by a
player who originally did not want to join the team.
   In January, U.S. District Judge G. Kendall Sharp threw Lilly's
lawsuit out of court in Orlando. Sharp ruled that Lilly failed to
get the script copyrighted before distributing it to movie agents.
   Lilly appealed that ruling on the grounds that many writers
register their works with the Writers Guild in Southern California
instead of getting a copyright.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard University on Thursday named
former Atlanta Journal-Constitution editor William Kovach as
interim head of the Nieman Fellowship program to replace the ailing
Howard Simons.
   The program offers journalists who are in midcareer a year off
to study any topic they want at Harvard.
   Simons, 59, is suffering from pancreatic cancer and has gone on
an indefinite medical leave of absence, school officials said. He
took charge of the Nieman program in 1984.
   Kovach, 57, was with The New York Times for 18 years, including
a stint as Washington bureau chief before moving to Atlanta. He
departed last year after a well-publicized dispute with the
Journal-Constitution's publisher, and is winding up a year as a
Nieman fellow.
   Harvard President Derek Bok said Simons, former managing editor
of The Washington Post, helped expand the role of journalists at
the university.
   ``Howard has brought to the program impressive experience, good
judgment, and a keen interest in each fellow,'' Bok said. ``We will
miss him more than I can say.''
   Simons was a Nieman fellow himself in 1958, and then rose from
science reporter at the Post to become managing editor in 1971. In
that role, he helped oversee the newspaper's Pulitzer Prize-winning
coverage of the Watergate scandal.
</TEXT>
