<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OilSpills     05-25 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Enforcement of Spill Liability Laws Said Flawed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laws intended to make polluters pay for oil
spills and toxic wastes are not working because the government
hasn't been willing to spend enough to assess the damages, a House
subcommittee was told Thursday.
   State environmental prosecutors from New York and Massachusetts
said Interior Department regulations, coupled with the lack of
funds for assessment studies, actually obstruct more than enhance
efforts to make polluters pay.
   ``The rules so severely limited the damages collectable that, to
our knowledge, no state trustees have used the regulations in the
almost three years since their promulgation,'' said New York
Assistant Attorney General Gordon Johnson.
   ``The only winners have been the polluters,'' Johnson told the
House Merchant Marine Committee's subcommittee on fisheries and
wildlife conservation.
   Administration officials conceded a dearth of damage
assessments, both for the hundreds of major oil spills that have
occurred since the 1972 Clean Water Act was passed, and for
corporate liabilities under the 1980 Superfund law to clean up
thousands of toxic waste sites.
   Officials for the Interior and Commerce departments as well as
the Environmental Protection Agency all said separate funds for
assessments were opposed by the Reagan administration, and that
none of their agencies have money for them.
   But they said the Bush administration is now ``rethinking'' that
view in light of the Valdez tanker spill in Alaska in March, and
noted that President Bush is seeking money to assess damages as
part of his proposal to establish a $500 million oil spill cleanup
fund.
   Louise Wise, deputy director of the EPA's office of marine and
estuarine protection, said her agency had opposed setting money
aside for assements out of fears it would deplete actual cleanup
funds provided for toxic waste dumps under the Superfund law.
   ``We are talking to our administrator about reconsidering our
position,'' she said.
   Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., the subcomittee's chairman,
encouraged that effort, saying of Bush, ``The president has enough
middle names without adding `maybe' to the list.''
   Because there is no money for the damage assessments, Studds
said, compensation cannot be obtained.
   Erik Olson of the National Wildlife Federation noted that the
government had to rely on the Exxon Corp. to put up $15 million for
the assessment of damages from its Valez oil tanker spill March 24
in Prince William Sound.
   ``This lack of money can lead to a subtle blackmail problem,''
he said. ``... Because Exxon is paying, it likely will argue that
it should have a lot to say about how the damages are calculated.''
</TEXT>
