<FIRST>r a AM-Newspaper-Brothel     05-25 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspaper-Brothel,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothel Owner Buys Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE MOUNTAIN, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The weekly Battle Mountain Bugle is
being sold this week to brothel owner Chuck Barrett, editor and
co-owner Linda Robertson said Thursday.
   Mrs. Robertson, who with her husband, Dayle, ran the paper for
the past four years, said Barrett had offered to buy the Bugle
after it was offered for sale nearly a year ago. Other offers were
made but weren't pursued.
   ``The fact that he owns a brothel disturbs us somewhat, because
we aren't in favor of brothels,'' Mrs. Robertson said. ``But nobody
else wanted to buy it. I haven't been in the best of health, and we
wanted to bail out.''
   The cost of the paper, with a circulation of about 1,850, wasn't
disclosed.
   Barrett plans to hire Jerry Teague as editor. Teague formerly
ran the Humboldt Sun and ``he's the same person I would have
hired,'' Mrs. Robertson said.
   Barrett owns several businesses in this northern Nevada town,
including the Calico Club and Desert Club brothels, a bookstore and
dress shop, and T-shirt print shop.
   Bordellos are legal in Nevada, under county option. The state's
largest counties, Clark and Washoe, ban brothels, but many of the
outlying counties permit them. Las Vegas is in Clark County and
Reno is in Washoe.
