<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovietGas     05-25 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Gas,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Physicians Say Soviet Troops Used World War I Gas on Civilians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet neurosurgeon who was gassed during an
ethnic protest in Soviet Georgia has helped American doctors
identify the poison as a World War I-era field gas named
chloropicrin, the doctors said Thursday.
   ``He gave us an exquisitely detailed account of the symptoms,''
said Dr. Barry H. Rumack, director of the Rocky Mountain Poison
Center in Denver. ``They couldn't have gassed a better guy _ at
least in terms of getting complete neurological findings.''
   Soviet officials have said Red Army troops used two chemical
agents, the tear gasses CN and CS, to disperse a crowd of 8,000 to
10,000 people demonstrating April 9 in the Georgian capital of
Tbilisi.
   But because more than 350 people were hospitalized and at least
20 died during and after the protest, Georgian officials have
charged for weeks that something more potent than tear gas must
have been sprayed.
   Rumack was one of three medical experts sent by Physicians for
Human Rights, a 1,300-member group based in the Boston area, to
investigate those charges. The American doctors spent May 17-22 in
Tbilisi at the invitation of Georgian health officials and Andrei
Sakharov, the Soviet physicist and human rights activist.
   After interviewing dozens of doctors and patients, examining
videotapes of the protest and analyzing some gas canisters
allegedly used by Soviet troops, the American team is ``99 percent
certain'' that chloropicrin was used, Rumack said.
   The chemical, also known as nitrochloroform, was first used on
humans on a World War I battlefield in 1916. It causes potentially
lethal chest irritation and pulmonary edema, or fluid leakage into
the lungs.
   Until the 1960s, chloropicrin occasionally was used for civilian
crowd control in the United States, but is now banned because of
its toxicity. It can be used legally in the United States only by
licensed applicators as a fumigant against insects, Rumack said.
   The strongest evidence that it was used in Georgia, he said, was
the patients' symptoms, including burns in their mouths and
throats, and a molecular analysis of a gas canister by a highly
accurate technique known as gas chromatography-mass spectroscopy.
   Rumack said he watched as Soviet laboratory technicians analyzed
the canister and came up with results ``consistent with
chloropicrin.''
   He also said some of the symptoms, such as dry mouths and
dilated pupils, could not have resulted from tear gas or most nerve
gasses, but would be expected with chloropicrin.
   Citing the possibility of retribution against the neurosurgeon
who helped describe his own and other people's symptoms, Rumack
declined to name him.
   Besides Rumack, who is a professor of toxicology at the
University of Colorado Medical Center in Denver, the members of the
American delegation were Dr. Jennifer Leaning, chief of emergency
services for the Harvard Community Health Plan in Cambridge, and
Dr. Ruth A. Barron, a psychiatrist at McLean Hospital in Belmont.
   Rumack said he believed four demonstrators died instantly when
they were sprayed directly in the face with an aerosol propellant
used with tear gas. He said neither tear gas nor chloropicrin alone
would account for such rapid deaths.
   How many later died from chloropicrin is uncertain, because
autopsy reports were impounded by the military and more than a
month has gone by, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
