<FIRST>r a AM-NASA-Test     05-25 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA-Test,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Engine Test Shuts Itself Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A test firing of a modified space
shuttle rocket engine aborted automatically after 2.5 seconds when
instruments detected excessive vibration, the Marshall Space Flight
Center said Thursday,
   But spokesman Jim Sahli said Wednesday's test, scheduled to last
2{ minutes, was not a failure because it can still provide
information about the engine's operation.
   Sahli said engineers attempting Thursday to trace the cause of
the abort, which could be related to a test detonation of an
explosive within the engine's combustion chamger.
   The cut-off occurred a fraction of a second after engineers were
to detonate explosives inside the combustion chamber of the engine,
which was mounted in a 300-foot-high rocket test stand.
   John McCarty, head of Marshall's Propulsion Laboratory, said the
explosives and a second device that may not have detonated were
placed inside the engine to show how engine systems perform during
unexpected occurrences.
   Steve Richards, McCarty's technical assistant, said the
explosive device could have caused systems to sense changes and
shut down the engine.
   Sahli said the test was part of a five-year program aimed at
developing a ``better, more efficient and better performing''
engine. He said it was a ``technology development'' test and not a
flight test.
   Wednesday's test firing was the seventh since the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration began the program at Marshall
in October.
   Sahli said the test would be rescheduled in about three weeks.
   Marshall is responsible for shuttle main engines, booster
rockets and external fuel tanks.
</TEXT>
