<FIRST>r a AM-RemingtonRecord     05-25 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Remington Record,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remington Sculpture Sold for Record $4.4 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederic Remington's 1902 bronze ``Coming
Through the Rye,'' depicting four cowboys firing pistols into the
air at full gallop, was sold at auction Thursday for $4.4 million,
a world record price for a piece of American sculpture.
   The piece was bought by an anonymous telephone buyer, said Dana
Micucci, a spokesman for Christie's auction house in Manhattan.
   The work was part of a group of important American paintings,
drawings and sculptures of the 18th, 19th and 20th centuries.
   The statue, a first cast, is one of Remington's most recognized
works. The turn-of-the-century sculptor and painter was known for
works which captured the spirit of the American West.
   Christie's had estimated the piece would sell for $2 million to
$3 million. The record price includes the auction house's 10
percent buyer's premium.
   The previous world record for a piece of American sculpture was
Elie Nadelman's ``Tango,'' which sold for $2.86 million at
Christie's New York in December 1987, said Micucci. That piece was
painted cherrywood of a couple dancing.
   The previous high price for a Remington was $715,000 for
``Norther,'' which was sold in New York in 1982.
</TEXT>
