<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-CapertonJr     05-25 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Caperton Jr,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father of West Virginia Governor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   W. Gaston Caperton Jr., the father of
Gov. Gaston Caperton and a co-founder of a small insurance company
his son made a giant, died Thursday from complications from a
stroke. He was 83.
   He had suffered a stroke May 2 and had remained hospitalized
since. He died shortly after 12:30 a.m. Thursday at the Charleston
Area Medical Center.
   ``My father was truly a great man. His love for God, his family
and his state was greater than that of any man I have ever known,''
the governor said. ``He was a successful businessman and civic
leader who will be greatly missed by all who knew him.''
   The elder Caperton was born William Gaston Caperton Jr. in
Wright.
   In 1936, he helped found McDonough-Caperton-Shepherd-Goldsmith,
a general insurance agency, in Charleston. McDonough was Caperton's
brother-in-law.
   In 1964, Caperton was Hulett Smith's campaign director in
Smith's successful bid for governor. He also was a member of the
committee on export expansion for the U.S. Department of Commerce.
   His son, West Virginia's future governor, began working for the
firm in 1963. In 1970, the younger Caperton bought out his father
and uncle when the insurance group had just 13 employees.
   At the time his son became governor, the firm had more than 500
employees and 19 offices and was one of the top 20 insurance
brokers in the nation.
   His son was a political novice when he upset incumbent Gov. Arch
Moore in the November 1988 general election. He took office in
January and placed the insurance company in a blind trust.
   Caperton Jr. is survived by his wife, Eliza Ambler Caperton; his
son, the governor; a daughter, Cary Caperton Owen of Asheville,
N.C.; six grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
   Services were scheduled Friday at St. John's Episcopal Church in
Charleston.
</TEXT>
