<FIRST>u w AM-ICCResignation     05-25 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ICC Resignation,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>ICC Chairman Resigns in Face of Senate Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heather J. Gradison resigned Thursday as
chairman of the Interstate Commerce Commission rather than face a
tough re-confirmation fight in the Senate.
   ``The White House and I have concluded it was not in our
interest to fight the Senate Commerce Committee,'' said Mrs.
Gradison, a member of the commission since 1982 and its chairman
since December 1985. She said she will leave when a successor is
confirmed.
   The White House did not respond immediately to a request for
comment.
   Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., a member of the committee, said Mrs.
Gradison, wife of Rep. Willis D. Gradison Jr., R-Ohio, probably
would not have been reconfirmed.
   ``Most of the Democrats and most of the Republicans on the
Commerce Committee had the feeling that she had not during her term
followed the intent of the Railroad Deregulation Act,'' said Exon,
reached in Nebraska. Asked whether he would have voted for
reconfirmation, Exon said: ``I would not.''
   The senator called Mrs. Gradison ``a dedicated and talented
woman'' but said ``We felt that the president could select someone
that would be maybe a little more in tune with what the Congress
intended when they wrote that bill.''
   The act that freed railroads from government regulation had
provisions to protect the so-called ``captive shipper'' _ the coal
mine operator or wheat farmer who had only one a single source of
transportation available.
   Under the act, the ICC could hold hearings and bring pressure to
bear on railroads if it felt they were out of line, Exon said. ``We
felt that under Mrs. Gradison, the ICC did not perform as was
intended.''
   Mrs. Gradison, 36, had spent eight years in the railroad
industry with the Southern Railway System when she was appointed as
one of the five ICC commissioners by President Reagan. She is a
strong supporter of transportation deregulation and, said the ICC
in a news release, she ``firmly maintained throughout her tenure
that reduced governmental regulation encourages the development of
new and better ways for transportation companies to serve the
public.''
   Exon said, however, that she did little to help the captive
shipper.
   ``One of the classic cases in this regard was the Public Power
Company in Nebraska being charged exorbitant rates by the
railroad,'' he said. ``The company took it to the ICC which said it
couldn't or wouldn't do anything about it.''
   The case went to court, he said, and the railroad was ordered to
pay back a substantial amount of money.
   Mrs. Gradison announced her resignation to about 100 co-workers
in a brief and emotional speech.
   ``I think it's time to move on,'' said Mrs. Gradison.
   Her voice breaking, Mrs. Gradison said: ``I think the time has
come to take advantage of the free market opportunity I have talked
about and find some for myself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PhysiciansPay     05-25 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Physicians Pay,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owens: ``The Current System Is Completely Out of Whack''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicians and lawmakers urged Congress
Thursday to overhaul the system of Medicare payments that enables a
doctor in New York to receive $7,500 for triple-bypass surgery
while a Kansas colleague only gets $3,500.
   ``The current system is completely out of whack,'' Rep. Wayne
Owens, D-Utah, told the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
health and the environment.
   Witnesses who testified before the House panel agreed that the
Medicare physician reimbursement system discriminates against
doctors practicing in rural areas, but they disagreed over ways to
eliminate the inequities.
   The focus of the debate were the recommendations of Physician
Payment Review Commission, an independent agency that monitors
Medicare payments and has proposed replacing the present system
with a Medicare fee schedule.
   Under the plan, developed by the Harvard School of Public Health
and outlined by commission chairman Dr. Philip R. Lee, the fee
would be based on a physician's work including his time, effort and
the skills needed to perform the task and the overhead cost of a
practice. A physician's cost-of-living expenses would not be
included in the fee schedule.
   The new formula would replace the current system in which
payments are based on ``customary, prevailing and reasonable'' fees
charged in an area.
   Dr. Robert Graham, executive vice president of the American
Academy of Family Physicians, argued that the cost of operating a
practice in rural areas is higher than the cost in a metropolitan
area.
   ``I support a plan for a single fee for single service
regardless of speciality or geographic area,'' Graham said.
   Rep. Jim Slattery, D-Kan., had told the panel earlier that
although rural physicians pay less for office space and salaries
for assistants, they usually treat a wide range of problems and
have more than one office.
   Slattery had raised the problem of vast discrepancies between
the reimbursement payments for doctors in metropolitan areas such
as New York City and Beverly Hills, Calif., and those in his home
state of Kansas.
   Specifically, he said physicians in all but two counties of
Kansas receive $49.68 for a limited consultation while general
practitioners in New York City receive $49.88 and specialists get
$117.59.
   He also cited the disparity between the payment for
triple-bypass surgery.
   The main point of contention, however, was the commission's
solution to the increasing cost of Medicare expenditures and the
rise in the number of unnecessary procedures.
   The panel proposed imposing expenditure targets which would
reflect ``increases in practice costs, growth and aging of the
enrollee population and a decision concerning the appropriate rate
of increase in volume of services per enrollee.''
   Tied to the targets would be an emphasis on common practice
guidelines for all physicians in the community.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., expressed reservations about
implementing the targets when adoption of practice guidelines may
take a few years to work out. But Lee said the targets should not
be delayed and the guidelines eventually will be set.
   ``That sounds a little like wishful thinking,'' Wyden said.
   Representatives from the American Medical Association, the
American Society for Internal Medicine and the American College of
Physicians complained about the expenditure targets, saying such a
plan would force physicians to ``ration'' services.
   ``Expenditure targets can only work if individual doctors
decline to provide certain services to their patients that they
otherwise would have provided,'' said Dr. Joseph F. Boyle,
executive vice president of the American Society of Internal
Medicine.
   ``It is also unclear how the medical profession can collectively
control utilization across the country in order to meet the
expenditure target,'' Boyle said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
