<FIRST>r a AM-HealthCare     05-25 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Care,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Attend Hearing on Nation's Health Care System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS PARK, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's health care system is
``expensive, bureaucratic and often cruel,'' an elderly woman told
more than 400 people at the first of several hearings by a
congressional commission.
   ``As one who has faced the problems associated with paying for
the acute care of my husband and the nursing home care for my
mother, I know first-hand the complexities and costs of our present
system,'' said Grace Nelson, 80, of Edina.
   Nelson represented the Minnesota Long Term Care Campaign, a
coalition of various community services organizations with chapters
in 26 states, as well as the Minnesota Senior Federation and the
Minnesota Health Care Coalition.
   Also testifying at the hearing conducted by the U.S. Bipartisan
Commission on Comprehensive Health Care was the Rev. Joseph Head, a
90-year-old World War I veteran from Minneapolis who uses a
wheelchair. His wife, he said, is bedridden and they cannot afford
outside help.
   ``We need help, long-term care for two patriots who have served
their country,'' Head testified.
   ``We love this country and have always done our part, but now we
are helpless and not getting all we need,'' said Head, a past
president of the National Chaplains of the Veterans of Foreign Wars.
   Nelson and Head were among more than 20 people who testified as
the 15-member commission began its public inquiry into how to help
Americans who lack health insurance and how to provide long-term
health care.
   U.S. Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., vice chairman of the
commission, told the hearing that action must be taken ``to avert
an impending catastrophe in the American health care system.''
   Noting that some people are unable to get the kind of care
readily available to others, he said, ``every American must have
membership in a health plan which provides financial access to
health care and manages the provision of all medical services.''
   The commission will submit its final report to Congress in
November after conducting six more hearings around the country. It
includes 12 congressmen and three White House appointees.
   Many of those testifying were in tears.
   ``I've worked hard to make a good life for me and Jennifer,''
Sue Stevens of St. Louis Park said of her 12-year-old daughter. But
she said they are unable to obtain medical insurance for their
asthma and other allergies.
   ``I don't know how much longer I can go on each day wondering if
our health-care problems are going to drag us down,'' Stevens said.
   James Reinertsen, a rheumatologist and president of Park
Nicollet Medical Center where the hearing was held, suggested an
approach to the medical ``haves'' and ``have-nots.''
   The average American, he said, uses more services than necessary
to maintain good health. He called on the ``haves'' to give up
coverage of such procedures as baldness treatment, breast
reductions and wart removal so that the ``have-nots'' could receive
basic coverage.
   ``I believe that reduction in health-care costs for those
Americans who now enjoy overinsurance would be more than enough to
pay for the costs of those who now have no insurance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
