<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DroughtRelief     05-25 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Relief,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Plans for An Unrainy Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers whose crops are lost to drought this
year would get relief from a bill passed Thursday by the House
Agriculture Committee.
   The original purpose of the legislation was to extend the 1988
drought relief emergency bill to cover winter wheat crops being
harvested this year.
   But the amendments offered by lawmakers from non-wheat states
that could also experience drought problems expanded the bill to
cover many more crops.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter told the committee through
a letter that he would not recommend that President Bush sign the
bill unless it was ``budget neutral,'' applicable only to 1989
crops affected by drought and accompanied by a promise that
Congress would agree to use crop insurance as the sole vehicle for
disaster assistance after this year.
   ``I think we are in the ballpark,'' said Kika de la Garza,
D-Texas, chairman of the Agriculture Committee, after the vote.
   He said the improvements to the crop insurance program would not
be ready in time for action on this bill, but the progress the
House is making should stand as an indication that continued
emergency relief like this legislation will not be necessary in the
future.
   ``The secretary is going to say, `how much does it (the bill)
cost?''' said John Campbell, deputy agriculture secretary in charge
of commodities. ``We have a lot of work to do in analyzing the
bill.''
   He praised the strict crop insurance component of the bill, but
noted that policy changes would have to be made in how crop
insurance works.
   The adminstration wants farmers to purchase crop insurance
rather than depending on the government to always bail them out
when bad weather causes crop failures. But farmers are unhappy with
the current crop insurance program and haven't been participating.
   The bill requires them to buy insurance for 1990 as a
qualification for getting relief for 1989.
   Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., chairman of the subcommittee on
wheat, soybeans and feed grains, called the inclusion in the bill
of crops besides winter wheat a ``political accommodation'' to
lawmakers from other states.
   ``I think we can sell this program,'' said Glickman.
   De la Garza estimated that the bill would cost about $1 billion
in relief payments, which is close to the amount of money the
government has saved in assistance payments to wheat farmers.
   In other words, the drought caused a shortage in supply which
means higher prices and no need for government subsidies. The money
that had been set aside for the subsidies would be used to pay the
farmers who lost their crops to drought.
   That's why the lawmakers call the legislation budget neutral.
   Glickman said the money farmers would receive in relief,
however, is not as much as they would have gotten if they had had a
crop.
   ``It's about a third,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-High-RiseRazing Bjt   05-25 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-High-Rise Razing, Bjt,0900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Tours Inner-City Housing Project Set for Demolition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge considering whether to block
the largest demolition of public housing stepped over a pile of
trash and broken furniture Thursday as he toured a building that is
slated for dynamiting.
   U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise passed through the
dim, graffiti-marred hallways in the Kretchmer Homes project to
gather background for the court case that is before him.
   ``I can visualize better what the plaintiffs are talking about
on paper,'' said the judge, who has been attempting to mediate the
dispute.
   The Kretchmer Homes complex was begun in 1953. But already,
vandalism and neglect have taken their toll, and the project is now
only about one-third occupied.
   In one vacant apartment, Debevoise stepped over a ripped
mattress and trash piled on the floor, passed tattered wallpaper
and gaping holes in the walls.
   He paused briefly at a large window in the eight-story building
to peer through dirty, broken panes of glass at a barren complex of
12 similar buildings across the dusty courtyard.
   Housing officials are seeking to demolish Kretchmer's 730 units
and more than 5,000 other government-built apartments elsewhere in
Newark, more public housing than any other city has demolished.
Fighting the proposal is a coalition of tenants and homeless
advocates.
   ``The whole silly notion of having these buildings torn down is
beyond me,'' said Modesto Hill, 22, who has lived in the Kretchmer
project for 19 years. He spoke Thursday as he and his mother
prepared to move to another apartment, while the judge toured
elsewhere in the building.
   The battle in this city, where one-third of the 316,000
residents receive public assistance, reflects a national trend by
housing authorities who say high-rise projects are unmanageable and
dangerous and should be replaced by townhouses and low-rise
buildings.
   ``High-rise housing in a lot of areas is a concept that just
doesn't work,'' said Bill Glavin, a spokesman for the U.S.
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   The targeted projects in Newark are ``beyond redemption''
despite millions of dollars poured into them for renovation, sid
Pamela Goldstein, a spokeswoman for Mayor Sharpe James.
   ``When you pile people in degrading circumstances on top of one
another, it just doesn't lend itself to good living,'' she said.
   But activists contend that with thousands of people living on
the streets _ an estimated 16,000 homeless in Newark and up to 3
million nationwide _ demolition is folly.
   They urge other solutions: closer tenant management that might
cut down on vandalism, reconfiguration of apartments and hallways,
keeping families with children on lower floors, and renovation
through grants.
   ``Rather than try to solve the problems, they decided to
eliminate them,'' said Melville D. Miller Jr., president of Legal
Services of New Jersey and a signer of the court suit that
Debevoise is considering.
   The first major project to be razed was St. Louis' Pruitt-Igoe
complex, which were destroyed in the mid-1970s after only about 20
years of use. The site is still vacant.
   From 1982 to 1987, more than 12,500 of 1.4 million federally
funded apartments were dynamited, Glavin said. Just Wednesday, a
10-story building was demolished by the wrecking ball in
Providence, R.I., after attempts to bring it down with dynamite
failed.
   Similar actions are planned in Jacksonville, Fla; Bridgeport,
Conn.; Houston; and New Orleans. Friday marks the deadline for
housing authorities to submit requests for federal funds to replace
demolished apartments. Glavin said about 20 communities had
applied, but he could not identify them.
   The lawsuit before Debevoise names the Newark housing authority
and HUD, which itself has criticized the authority for
mismanagement.
   The Newark authority, eighth-largest in the nation, controls
13,000 apartments and has a waiting list of 10,000 families. Nearly
40 percent of the apartments are vacant _ including many of those
awaiting demolition. More than 800 units have already been razed.
   The authority plans to replace the high-rises eventually with
smaller, more manageable builings, and to combine subsidized and
market-rate homes. The suit alleges that those replacement plans
are inadequate, citing a 1988 federal law requiring each demolished
apartment to be replaced.
   Activists largely have been unsuccessful in legal challenges to
the demolition of deteriorating public housing elsewhere. But
Debevoise, who before he became a judge was the founder of the
state's first legal project for the poor, has tried to settle the
dispute here.
   The parties agreed to Debevoise's temporary ban on demolition,
and he took the unusual action of assigning a mediator to meet with
them, ordering weekly updates.
   ``I knew from the outset that this was a no-win situation in the
litigation context,'' he said.
   The temporary halting of demolition has not halted the city's
effort to relocate tenants from buildings that are on the
demolition list.
   Hill and his mother are among the lucky ones, because they are
being relocated to a modern, subsidized townhouse rather than
another high-rise that might also be targeted for destruction.
   As she packed belongings Thursday, she pointed out new cabinets
and fixtures in the kitchen she was leaving behind. The vandals,
she said, are ``going to come tonight to strip all this out of
here.''
</TEXT>
