<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PesticidesSuit     05-25 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pesticides Suit,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Sued Over Pesticides In Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two environmental groups joined the state of
California and the AFL-CIO on Thursday in suing the Environmental
Protection Agency for allegedly failing to protect consumers from
dangerous pesticides in food.
   The suit asks that the federal courts require the EPA to impose
more stringent regulations on cancer-causing chemicals in food,
especially in processed fruits and vegetables often consumed by
small children.
   Al Meyerhoff, an attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, said the suit is aimed at forcing the EPA to be more
aggressive in prohibiting the use of pesticides on food and to ban
them altogether if they are found to cause cancer.
   Under current EPA procedures, the agency allows the use of some
older pesticides even though agency officials concede that if the
same chemicals were newly introduced they would not be approved
because of health concerns.
   The agency is in the midst of re-examining scores of older
pesticides using current health criteria, but that process could
take years.
   At the same time, the agency applies a ``negligible risk'' test
when determining whether a cancer-causing chemical should continue
to be used, banning it if the increased risk is one in one million.
The suit asks the court to direct the EPA to automatically take a
chemical off the market for food use if there is any proof it is
carcinogenic, no matter what the expected risk.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Sacramento, Calif.,
accused the EPA of a ``consistent failure'' to carry out the
requirements of the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act, which requires the
regulation of unsafe residues from pesticides on food products.
   The EPA had no comment on the suit.
   Jay Vroom, executive vice president of the National Agricultural
Chemicals Association, criticized the suit as ``a political move
for additional publicity to further confuse and confound the
public'' about the dangers of pesticides in food.
   The industry has consistently argued that the levels of
pesticides in food products is so low as to pose no health danger.
   In addition to the Natural Resources Defense Council, plaintiffs
in the lawsuit are Public Citizen, a private environmetnal and
consumer group in Washington, the state attorney general of
California and the AFL-CIO. The NRDC is a private, non-profit
environmental organization.
   The suit also charges the EPA with not requiring enough
information from processsed food manufacturers to determine residue
levels of many pesticides, including some that have been found to
cause cancer.
   ``The law requires EPA to identify cancer-causing pesticides in
processed foods ... By refusing to collect the data and to apply
the law, EPA jeopardizes the public health and violates the public
trust,'' said William Schultz, an attorney for Public Citizen, a
private environmental and consumer group.
   In addition to the suit, the plaintiffs filed a petition with
the EPA asking that seven cancer-causing pesticides immediately be
banned in processed foods. They argued such a ban is required under
a 1958 law, although the chemicals were in use prior to that.
   These pesticides have been found to have higher concentrations
of residues in processed foods than in raw agricultural products,
the petition maintains, and should be subject to a provision of the
1958 law that prohibits any levels of a carcinogenic pesticide in
certain foods.
   The EPA has said that the so-called Delaney clause in the 1958
law does not apply to pesticides that were approved for use prior
to the law's enactment even though latest tests showed them to be
carcinogenic. In such cases, the agency allowed if they are
perceived to pose merely a ``negligible risk.''
   The plaintiffs claim there are at leat 20 pesticides now allowed
by the EPA in processed foods despite links of various degrees to
cancer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     05-25 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Demand Students Stop Burning U.S. Flags</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean authorities Thursday
ordered radical students to stop burning U.S. flags at
anti-American protests on college campuses and said those caught
would be punished.
   School officials were told to prevent students from defiling the
Stars and Stripes, education officials said. Offenders face
two-year jail terms under South Korean Law.
   On Monday, radical students began a week of anti-American
protests in Seoul and other cities. They have repeatedly burned
flags and effigies of Uncle Sam wearing the Stars and Stripes.
   Protests were to call for the withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S.
troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense treaty.
Radicals and dissidents say the U.S. troops hamper unification with
communist North Korea.
   They also say the United States props up authoritarian rule in
South Korea.
   On Thursday, about 500 radical students calling for the
overthrow of President Roh Tae-woo battled riot police at Korea
University after an anti-government rally. Students hurled
firebombs and rocks and police responded in kind. There were no
reports of injuries or arrests.
   At Dankook University, about 200 students held a peaceful rally
to denounce Roh and the United States. Riot police surrounded the
school, but did not intervene.
   Meanwhile, police raided a gallery in downtown Seoul Thursday
and seized a large painting of the U.S. flag displayed on the floor
where it was walked upon by visitors. Students at four schools in
Seoul painted huge Stars and Stripes on campus roadways so
pedestrians and vehicles could walk or drive on them.
   Newspapers in Seoul Thursday carried critical commentaries and
editorials urging radical students to stop their harassment of a
friendly nation.
   ``Defaming a nation's flag is a deplorable act,'' the Foreign
Ministry said in a statement Monday.
   Korean government officials are concerned that anti-U.S.
sentiment may create an anti-Korean backlash in the United States,
South Korea's largest trade partner.
   The Korea Herald, an English-language newspaper in Seoul, said
in an editorial Thursday: ``That uncivilized outrage of soiling and
disgracing the flag of a nation is self-degrading and
self-defeating at the same time.''
   Most South Koreans support the presence of U.S. troops.
Officials have said American forces will remain as long as they are
wanted by the Seoul government. Radical students lack public
support because of their violent tactics and extreme views.
   Meanwhile, about 700 teachers nationwide took part in sit-ins
calling for better working conditions and trade unions. They were
protesting a government threat to bring criminal charges against 34
colleagues who were called in for questioning, sources said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
