<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Congress-Players     05-25 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Congress-Players,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some of the Key Players as New Soviet Congress Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at some of the key players in the
first session of the Soviet Congress of People's Deputies on
Thursday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MIKHAIL S. GORBACHEV _ Age 58, received a renewed stamp of
approval for his reform program and personal leadership, winning
95.6 percent of the vote in his bid for the presidency. But in
pre-election debates he was subjected to unprecedented questioning
from deputies who took him to task for his policies on ethnic
relations, party privileges and legal changes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ANDREI D. SAKHAROV _ Age 68, 1975 Nobel Peace laureate, was
exiled to the closed city of Gorky in January 1980 for speaking out
against the Soviet military intervention in Afghanistan. Gorbachev
allowed him to return to Moscow in December 1986, and he has since
become a vocal but not uncritical supporter of Gorbachev and a
rallying leader for the progressive faction among deputies.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   BORIS N. YELTSIN _ Age 58, was elected from Moscow with the
largest popular vote of any deputy. His outspoken criticism of
privileges for the elite and calls for more radical reform appeal
to many Soviets. But his bluntness cost him a Politburo seat and
his job as Moscow party chief in early 1988. He turned down a
nomination for president Thursday, but said he would not withdraw
from any more races.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ALEXANDER OBOLENSKY _ A middle-aged scientist at a polar
research institute in Leningrad, not a member of the Communist
Party. He declared himself Gorbachev's rival for the presidency,
saying he wanted history to record that there was an alternative
candidate. But he admitted he had no chance against Gorbachev, and
the Congress voted not to put his name on the ballot despite strong
applause for his pro-reform platform.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MARJU LAURISTIN _ A professor at the University of Tartu in the
tiny Baltic republic of Estonia and an outspoken leader of the
Estonian People's Front. She pushed Gorbachev for answers to
questions on nationalities-related and legal issues. Other
non-Russian deputies also brought before the Congress tensions in
Georgia, Azerbaijan and the restive Baltic republics.
</TEXT>
