<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     05-25 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Predicts Normal Relations Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said
Thursday he expects normal relations with the United States to be
achieved next year, after Vietnam ends its decade-old military
occupation of Cambodia.
   ``The United States has repeatedly stated that relations with
Vietnam would be normalized after complete withdrawal of Vietnamese
troops,'' he said. Hanoi has promised its soldiers will be out of
Cambodia by Sept. 30.
   ``I am of the opinion that the United States will keep the words
of a big country,'' Thach said in an interview with The Associated
Press. ``The sooner it is normalized, the better, and it is better
late than never.''
   Asked when, he said ``the middle course'' _ meaning a reasonable
guess _ would be next year.
   ``It is the end of the tunnel,'' he said of the Cambodian
conflict. ``Now we can get out of the tunnel.''
   Central to any peace agreement is Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
former ruler of Cambodia and now leader of the guerrilla alliance,
who has been negotiating with the Vietnam-sponsored government.
   Thach said Sihanouk often has changed his behavior and tactics,
but always had the same objective: to be head of state. Since the
pro-Vietnamese government now has offered him that post, the
foreign minister said, ``I don't think he will miss the
opportunity.''
   Washington has not recognized the communist government that has
ruled all of Vietnam since winning the war in April 1975. The
Carter administration came close to recognition in the 1970s, but
that fell apart when Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978.
   The United States, which supports the Cambodian resistance, has
said it will not consider ending its trade and aid embargo or
establishing relations until the last Vietnamese troops leave.
   Relations with the United States are essential if Vietnam is to
get the aid and investment necessary to develop its economy, one of
the world's poorest.
   Vietnam also has been pressing China to fulfill what Hanoi says
was its pledge to discuss restoring normal relations once Vietnam
began withdrawing from Cambodia. China supports the rebels and the
Soviet Union backs Vietnam.
   In recent years, the United States and Vietnam have made rapid
progress on humanitarian issues, including resettlement of refugees
and migrants to the United States and resolving the fates of
American soldiers still listed as missing in action.
   Private U.S. citizens also have increased their contacts with
Vietnam.
   Arnold Schecter, a leading American researcher, said Wednesday
the Vietnamese were allowing him to open an office in a Hanoi
medical school to study the health effects of Agent Orange, the
herbicide U.S. forces sprayed on Vietnam during the war.
</TEXT>
