<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Expulsions     05-25 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Expulsions,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Expels Four Czechoslovaks, Soviets Say Journalists Spied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain expelled four Czechoslovak diplomats
Thursday, a week after ordering out 11 Soviets. Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher said the crackdown was vital ``regardless of the
effect upon our relations.''
   In Moscow, the KGB said it had evidence that three British
journalists expelled last week engaged in spying. It was the first
time the Soviets had published detailed accusations against the
three.
   The employers of the British journalists denied the charges, one
calling them ``part of the tit-for-tat going on at the moment.''
   The Foreign Office accused the four Czechoslovaks of
``activities incompatible with their status,'' diplomatic parlance
for spying, and said they must go within two weeks.
   Foreign Office political director Sir John Fretwell summoned
Czechoslovak Ambassador Jan Fidler and said Britain deeply
regretted that the Prague government ignored a warning to rein in
diplomats last September, when three others were expelled.
   In the House of Commons, Mrs. Thatcher brushed aside opposition
charges she is jeopardizing what had been Britain's best relations
with the Soviet Union since World War II.
   ``The action had to be taken, regardless of the effect upon our
relations,'' she said. ``The worst thing of all would have been to
say because we had better relations, we could ignore those
unacceptable activities.''
   She said such activities were uncovered ``both in the Soviet
Embassy _ we have to take action against them _ and also in the
Czech Embassy.''
   Fidler termed the British allegations ``totally unfounded.''
   An embassy spokeswoman, who demanded anonymity, said Fidler told
Fretwell the move undermined British-Czechoslovak relations and
``damages positive developments in Europe as well.''
   The Czechoslovaks ordered expelled were Jan Pavlicek, 39, third
secretary and press attache; Helena Krepelkova, 38, a second
secretary; Jan Sarkocy, 35, third secretary, and Rudolf
Kasparovsky, 35, technical adviser.
   The expulsions reflected a tough stance with communist countries
despite what Mrs. Thatcher has hailed as the ``end of the Cold
War'' as Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev pursues his reform
policies. Despite giving Gorbachev a warm welcome on a visit six
weeks ago, Britain has complained that Soviet agents continue
widespread espionage.
   Britain has also sought better relations with Czechoslovakia,
partly to get help in trying to make more detectable the
Czechoslovak-manufactured explosive Semtex used by the Irish
Republican Army and other militant groups.
   The Foreign Office said Fretwell made a point Thursday of
thanking Fidler for Czechoslovak cooperation over Semtex.
   Foreign Office officials said allegations against the expelled
Soviets and Czechoslovaks were not linked.
   The 11 Britons expelled from the Soviet Union included eight
diplomats and three journalists.
   In Moscow Thursday, KGB spokesman Vladimir Strunin told a news
conference that: ``Competent organs possess information that
testifies to the involvement of these journalists with British
intelligence services.''
   The journalists _ Jeremy Harris of the British Broadcasting
Corp., Ian Glover-James of Independent Television News and Angus
Roxburgh of The Sunday Times _ on Saturday were given 14 days to
leave the Soviet Union.
   Britain said the move was revenge for Britain's decision on
Friday to expel 11 London-based Soviets _ also eight diplomats and
three journalists _ accused of spying.
   The most serious accusation leveled was against Roxburgh. The
KGB accused him of trying to enlist a Soviet citizen to obtain
information on unspecified ``government installations.''
   It said Roxburgh gave the Soviet equipment for listening and
recording telephone conversations, and promised to pay a monetary
reward for information that was interesting. It also accused him of
violating regulations that restrict foreigners' travel in the
Soviet Union.
   Andrew Neil, editor of The Sunday Times, said the charges
announced earlier Thursday by the Soviet KGB were obviously part of
continuing inter-government reprisals.
   ``These allegations are clearly absurd and obviously part of the
tit-for-tat going on at the moment,'' Neil said. The BBC and
Independent Television News also denied the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
