<FIRST>r w AM-SudaneseRebel     05-25 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudanese Rebel,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Of Sudan's Rebels Making First US Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the Sudan People's Liberation
Army is coming to the United States on his first official visit to
seek support for his organization's war against the U.S.-backed
government, an organizer said Thursday.
   John Garang will meet with members of Congress and journalists
during his three-day visit beginning June 6, said Roger Winter,
Director of the private non-profit United States Committee for
Refugees.
   He will also be granted meetings with State Department officials
if he asks, said an administration source who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Garang is coming at the invitation of former President Jimmy
Carter, who has undertaken an attempt to advance negotiations
between the SPLA and the government in Khartoum, Winter said.
   Carter visited Sudan in April, meeting with government officials
and with Garang's lieutenants, but the SPLA chief was ``in the
bush'' at the time and did not meet with Carter, Winter said. He
will meet with him in Georgia before coming to Washington.
   Carter's mission had the blessing of the Bush administration,
which has made an end to the Sudanese civil war a priority item on
its foreign policy agenda.
   Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen visited Khartoum
earlier this week for talks with the government on ending the war,
and he plans to meet too with representatives of the SPLA, said the
administration official.
   Cohen will also discuss the Sudan situation with his Soviet
counterpart in Rome this weekend, the official said.
   The SPLA began fighting in 1983, demanding greater autonomy for
the southern provinces which are populated mainly by Christians and
animists. The rebels and their supporters in the West accuse the
Moslem-dominated government of waging genocide against the
southerners by preventing food convoys from reaching them and by
attacking population centers controlled by the SPLA.
   In recent months, Garang's troops have scored successive
victories over government forces and consolidated their control of
the south.
   But in early May, Garang announced a unilateral one-month
cease-fire to assist a U.N.-sponsored relief program that is trying
to stockpile enough food to save some 100,000 Sudanese from
starving. Both sides have used food as a weapon in the war,
resulting in hundreds of thousands of deaths.
   Garang, a U.S.-educated renegade army colonel, is seeking to
build up public opinion and official support in the United States
in the event that negotiations get underway with the U.S.-backed
government, Winter said.
   The government has shown some willingness to discuss a peace
proposal offered by the SPLA last year, but Moslem fundamentalists
have so far derailed the process.
</TEXT>
