<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     05-25 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Candidates Again Defy Ban on Demonstrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders toured a hospital
Thursday to the cheers of hundreds of patients, visitors and
employees and said they will keep fighting they until they win
recognition of having won the election.
   It was the fifth time the candidates defied a government ban on
demonstrations, which is in effect until a visiting Organization of
American States delegation turns in its report.
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara and his two
running mates told OAS delegates Wednesday that they won the May 7
election and want their victory recognized and Panama's ruler, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, ousted.
   ``The OAS can help in one of two ways, either by starting us on
the road to a negotiated solution or by establishing a strict
quarantine of the Noriega regime,'' said Ricardo Arias Calderon,
the candidate for first vice president.
   Arias Calderon said the candidates' campaign-style appearances
were meant as ``a message of faith in ourselves.''
   ``We're telling the government we will continue to fight,'' he
said.
   The OAS mission was sent to help fashion a solution to Panama's
political impasse following the vote. The delegation had no
meetings scheduled Thursday, a spokesman said.
   International observers say the Endara ticket won the
presidential vote by a 3-to-1 margin, but the government nullified
the vote, claiming that foreign interference made an accurate vote
tally impossible.
   The OAS then condemned Noriega and called for a transfer of
power in Panama.
   Noriega's backers claimed their presidential candidate, Carlos
Duque, had been ahead by 2-1 when the election was voided.
   In his meeting with the OAS delegation Wednesday, Noriega blamed
Panama's crisis on a long history of U.S. intervention.
   In brief comments to reporters, Noriega warned it would be a
dangerous precedent for the OAS to do anything that would be
considered interference in another country's internal affairs.
   ``Today it's Panama, tomorrow it could be any other country,''
he said.
   Maj. Edgardo Lopez, a Noriega spokesman, said OAS delegates
raised the issue of Noriega's retirement during one meeting but
that officers said they were loyal to Noriega and the question
would be decided by the Defense Forces.
   Noriega holds power through his command of the Defense Forces,
which have remained faithful despite U.S. and opposition signals
that a coup would be welcome.
   In Thursday's visit to the public Social Security Hospital in
Panama City, the opposition candidates were greeted by chanting,
autograph-hunting crowds on every floor.
   Operating room staff members in green gowns, caps, masks and
gloves emerged briefly into a waiting room.
   ``I'm between operations, but I have to get back to work,'' said
one after joining a chant of ``Justice! Justice!.''
   ``That beautiful man kissed me,'' boasted one woman to friends
in a waiting room after she hugged Endara.
   A nurse who works in the hospital laboratory said conditions
have grown worse in the last few years.
   ``We have minimal supplies,'' she said. ``We have to get rid of
the corruption.''
   The first demonstrations against Noriega began in June 1987. He
was indicted in Florida on U.S. drug charges in February 1988, and
U.S. economic sanctions were imposed on the Panamanian government.
   Noriega denies the charges and called them part of a U.S. plot
to abrogate treaties under which Panama gains control of the Panama
Canal at the end of 1999.
</TEXT>
