<FIRST>u w AM-WorldSugar     05-25 0106</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Sugar,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says Sugar Production Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World sugar production in 1989-90 is forecast
at 107.3 million metric tons, raw value, up by 1.2 percent from an
estimated 106 million tons produced in 1988-89, the Agriculture
Department said Thursday.
   Production is expected to show its biggest gain in Eastern
Europe, if weather is normal. Yugoslavia, East Germany and Romania
are expected to account for most of the increase after a poor
sugarbeet crop last season.
   Increases are also expected in China and the United States,
while declines from last season are forecast for Thailand, Brazil,
Argentina and the European Economic Community.
</TEXT>
