<HEAD>Solar Powered Cars Begin Montpelier-Cambridge Road Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with results of first day, delete
outdated material and CORRECT to $30,000 sted $80,000 in 9th graf pvs.
Picks up 15th graf pvs, `And then.... SUBS 21st graf pvs, `New Hampshire...,
to CORRECT to Don sted Bob King.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sun warmed to the occasion Thursday,
powering the entries in the first American Tour de Sol, a race for
solar-powered cars from Vermont to Massachusetts.
   The trip, which takes four hours for internal combustion-engined
vehicles, will take these competitors four days.
   All five entries _ plus a pint-size speedster driven by a
preschooler _ had large panels of photovoltaic cells, which turn
sunlight into electricity to run electric motors and charge
batteries.
   The solar cars were running the route in four legs of several
hours each day, with overnight stops at Hanover, N.H., Concord,
N.H., and Lowell, Mass., before reaching the finish line, scheduled
Sunday at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in Cambridge,
Mass.
   The MIT entry, Solectria V, easily won the first leg of the race
Thursday, covering the 59 miles from the Statehouse lawn in
Montpelier to the Dartmouth College Green in just under 1 hour, 40
minutes.
   The car entered by the New Hampshire Technical Institute from
Concord finished second, in 2:33:17, and the Dartmouth College
entry finished in about 3:01.
   The Worcester (Mass.) Polytechnic Institute team had what it
called last-minute bugs that caused it to take more than seven
hours to arrive at Dartmouth. And a unique, wedge-shaped vehicle
brought by a two-man team from Alabama broke down on the first leg
of the race.
   Participants said they hoped for Thursday's sunny weather to
continue through Sunday. Clouds could make it impossible to finish
the race in the four days allocated.
   Race organizer Jim Kirby, of the Brattleboro-based Northeast
Solar Energy Association, said the aim of the event is to promote
interest in and development of cleaner transportation technologies.
   ``Only a few years ago this would have been thought of as a
rather novel and bizarre event,'' said Gov. Madeleine Kunin, who
waved a flag to start the race Thursday morning.
   But with heightened concern over environmental damage caused by
cars, she said, the racers might be offering ``a preview of what
life will be like in a couple of years.''
   Costs of the solar-powered vehicles were said to range from
about $10,000 in materials ``plus labor'' for the New Hampshire
Technical Institute entry to $30,000 for the state-of-the-art model
from MIT.
   One of the MIT innovations is brakes that, when applied,
generate electricity to help recharge the batteries, said team
member Lee Weinstein of Lexington, Mass.
   The four school cars were of a basic streamlined design.
   The fifth car, an independent entry driven by Ed Passarini of
Tuscaloosa, Ala., was taller and roomier. ``This is the commuter,''
Passarini said. ``You can carry your groceries in this one.''
   And then there was the sixth vehicle in the race, the favorite
entry of many but sure not to finish, said the driver's mother.
   Four-year-old Ian Cotter of Waldoboro, Maine, showed off and
then took off down the road after the others in a solar-powered
mini-car, bearing a big number ``6,'' that his father designed and
built for him.
   Asked how fast it would go, Ian said, ``about five miles.''
   Organizers said it is the first race of its kind in the United
States, and was modeled on an event that has been held annually in
Switzerland since 1982.
   Kirby said some of the cars can top 70 mph, going downhill. He
said they can get about two hours of use for about eight hours of
the sun's recharging. ``That makes them ideal for commuting,'' he
said.
   Dartmouth driver Lara Horner and others said a key part of the
strategy is not to go too fast uphill. ``That really runs the
batteries down,'' she said.
   New Hampshire Tech driver Don King said one of the best features
of the cars is their novelty. ``It's really neat. People wave,
their jaws drop open.''
   He said he's never been stopped by police, ``but a couple of
times, they nearly snapped their necks when we went by.''
</TEXT>
