<SECOND>AM-Missionaries, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0708,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Missionaries Gunned Down; Terrorists Targeting `Yankees'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 16th graf, `All young...' to CORRECT that Mormons encouraged
to serve as missionaries, sted required.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Mormon missionaries from Utah were
gunned down and killed in La Paz, and left-wing terrorists who
claimed reponsibiliity threatened a ``war to the death'' against
``Yankee invaders.''
   Todd Ray Wilson, of Wellington, and Jeffrey Brent Ball, from
Wanship, were returning to their home in a poor suburb late
Wednesday when unidentified men shot them with machine guns. One of
the victims died immediately, the other on the way to a hospital.
Both were 20 years old.
   The radical Zarate Willka Armed Liberation Front claimed
responsibility shortly after the shootings. It is the same group
that last summer tried to kill former Secretary of State George
Shultz when he was visiting La Paz.
   ``The violation of our sovereignty cannot go unpunished,'' the
revolutionaries said in a statement. ``The Yankee invaders who come
to massacre our fellow farmers are warned. ... We the poor have no
other road than to rise up in arms.
   ``Our hatred is implacable and our war is to death.''
   The slain missionaries lived in a neighborhood around the corner
from a church that was seriously damaged by a bomb explosion last
year, local church president Stephen R. Wright said in an interview.
   Two other bombs have been planted in the past nine months, he
said. One dmaaged a church and another was discovered before it
exploded.
   ``We are being targeted unfairly and inappropriately as being
imperialists,'' Wright said. ``We have been targeted because we
have a high profile, our missionaries wear shirts and ties and we
have nice churches.''
   Police say they have no suspects in the killings or bombings.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Mark Jacobs said American officials will
work closely with Bolivian investigators.
   ``The U.S Embassy in La Paz deplores and condems the
assaassination of two American citizens in La Paz in an act that
can only be described as cold-blooded murder,'' Jacobs said.
   The slayings were the first politically motivated killings of
Mormon missionaries in memory, spokesman Don LeFevre said at the
church's headquarters in Salt Lake City.
   ``They have died as martyrs in the cause of the Lord. We extend
our love and sympathy to their families and pray that they may be
comforted and sustained in this hour of tragedy,'' the governing
First Presidency of the Mormon faith said in a statement.
   Wright said Ball and Wilson came to Bolivia voluntarily and at
their own expense nearly a year ago to preach the gospel and enrich
lives of Bolivians. There are about 40,000 Mormons in the country.
   ``I feel great sadness and anger at the loss of these fine young
men,'' Wright said.
   All young Mormon males are encouraged to serve two years as
missionaries. Older couples and women serve 18 months.
   Church officials said the an autopsy was conducted Thursday and
bodies of the missionaries would be flown to Utah this weekend.
   Last year, the terrorists claimed responsibility for a bomb that
exploded near vehicles carrying Shultz, his wife and delegates in
La Paz for talks with government officials. No one was injured in
the attack.
