<FIRST>r a AM-SuperCops     05-25 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super Cops,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Felony Charges Filed Against Two `Super Cops'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY NEMEC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of an elite police crime-fighting unit
have been charged with 17 felony counts accusing them of perjury,
doctoring evidence and staging a crime to entrap habitual criminals.
   Larry Subia and Daril Cinquanta, members of the Police
Department's Career Criminal Unit, were charged Wednesday with
first-degree perjury, attempting to influence a public servant,
false reporting and tampering with physical evidence. They were
immediately suspended without pay.
   El Paso County District Attorney John Suthers and his chief
deputy, Robert Brown, serving as special prosecutors, filed the
charges in Denver and Arapahoe County courts following a two-week
investigation.
   ``This is something we don't like to see,'' said police
spokesman Bill Phillips. ``We're not in a position to break rules.
Obviously something was wrong, something was not monitored.''
   ``Any time you file charges against a public official, it's not
great,'' said Arapahoe County District Attorney Bob Gallagher.
``This is not a happy time. I do have faith in the criminal justice
system that everything comes out okay.''
   Questions about Denver's so-called ``super cops'' operation came
to light during an investigation of a burglary in the Arapahoe
County city of Littleton last June that was allegedly staged for
television.
   Cinquanta and Subia allegedly paid an informant to get John
LeFebre and Martha Bell to burglarize a Littleton residence. Police
and KMGH-TV of Denver were at the home when the burglary attempt
was made and officers arrested LeFebre and Ball.
   Englewood attorney Robert Ransome told prosecutors that LeFebre
and Ball had been recruited by police informant Pete Lopez, who
allegedly helped break into the home but was allowed to escape.
   After evidence surfaced that the burglary may have been set up
by Denver police, the Arapahoe County district attorney's office
dropped felony charges against LeFebre and Bell.
   The Denver charges stem from a robbery case a year ago in which
Subia and Cinquanta allegedly gave false testimony at pretrial
hearings.
   Roy Lee Tyler and Dale Robinson were convicted in the case. But
in March, Denver District Attorney Norm Early said the two would be
released because of the possibility that tainted testimony had been
given.
   Cinquanta's attorney expressed disappointment and surprise
Wednesday after his client and Subia were charged.
   ``We thought there might not be any charges filed at all,''
Robert Dill said. ``We've presented a lot of information and had
the expectation that would prove beyond a reasonable doubt'' the
officers' innocence.
   Dill said Cinquanta is ``sad and upset that he's been charged,
but he's confident he will be vindicated ... and I'm not just
saying that.''
   In Arapahoe County, Cinquanta is charged with one count of
attempting to influence a public servant and three counts of filing
false police reports. Subia is charged with one count of perjury,
one count of attempting to influence a public servant and one count
of filing a false report.
   In Denver County, Cinquanta faces two counts of perjury and five
counts of attempting to influence a public servant. Subia has been
charged with one count of perjury and two counts of attempting to
influence a public servant.
</TEXT>
