<FIRST>r a AM-AgricultureDispute     05-25 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agriculture Dispute,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clements, Texas Lawmakers to Save Agriculture Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers have struck a deal that saves the
state Agriculture Department from extinction, but strips the
embattled commissioner of his power over pesticide regulation,
officials said Thursday.
   Commissioner Jim Hightower had angered conservatives and
chemical interests with tough new pesticide rules his department
wrote and enforces. He upset others with his efforts to sell
hormone-free beef to Europe earlier this year.
   Republican Gov. Bill Clements, who has the power to veto the
Agriculture Department out of existence _ as some have urged _
promised to sign a compromise bill that would turn pesticide
regulation over to an independent board.
   ``It would mean a more reasoned, more effective, more consistent
and more coordinated enforcement of pesticide rules,'' Clements
said in a statement that never named Hightower, a Democrat and
self-described populist.
   Hightower's press secretary, Andy Welch, said the two-term
commissioner would wait until the Legislature finishes with the
bill before commenting.
   Under the compromise, a new nine-member Agricultural Resources
Protection Authority would set all policies and regulations on
pesticide use.
   The board would coordinate efforts of all state agencies,
including the Water Commission and Structural Pest Control Board,
which rule on pesticide use.
   The panel would be headed by the agriculture commissioner and
include officials from universities and state agencies. The
governor would appoint a consumer member and an agricultural
producer.
   The plan also requires that licensed pesticide applicators _
private farmers or commercial applicators _ ensure that their
employees are familiar with the pesticides they work with, said
Glenn Smith, an aide to Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby, who proposed the
provision.
   A key part of the deal says the new board can't weaken existing
rules, said State Rep. Lena Guerrero, a former farm worker.
   ``They are not allowed to change a law ... when the effect would
be less protective of the public's health, safety or welfare,'' she
said.
   Creation of the board appeared to be the best deal Hightower's
allies could get, Ms. Guerrero said.
   ``It's probably not the best way to set regulatory pesticide
policy in this state, but it's a legislative agreement,'' she said.
   Rep. Rick Perry, a Hightower opponent, called the plan the best
for all concerned.
   ``I've just got some problems with a single individual with
total control over the pesticide regulation in this state,'' Perry
said. ``I just think the board's a lot better way to go.''
   A coalition of 40 agricultural groups that have opposed
Hightower, including the Texas Farm Bureau and the Texas and
Southwestern Cattle Raisers Association, called the board ``a small
step in the right direction.''
   Hightower's political problems mounted as the Legislature
considered the Agriculture Department sunset bill, legislation that
must be approved every 12 years to keep each state agency in
business.
   If the bill fails to pass _ or is vetoed by Clements _ the
department would cease to exist on Sept. 1, 1990. If Clements signs
the bill, the department would continue for another 12 years.
   The Texas Farm Bureau had urged lawmakers to abolish the elected
agriculture commissioner's post and replace it with an appointee.
   Clements says he only has the power to kill the department, and
doing so wouldn't eliminate the elected commissioner's post.
   Saving the department was a top goal, Ms. Guerrero said.
   ``I also wanted to make sure we maintained an elected
agriculture commissioner,'' she said. ``Everybody eats, and
everybody should have a right to elect their agriculture
commissioner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
