<FIRST>u i AM-ArabSummit 1stLd-Writethru   05-25 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0696,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Quarrel Over Lebanon Drags On</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs 6-7, `The meeting...over Lebanon' with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with compromise to be considered. Pick up 8th pvs, `Syria, stressing...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab leaders continued arguing
heatedly Thursday about Lebanon, and differences over Syria's
military presence there threatened to wreck the summit and further
fragment the Arab world.
   Iraq is insisting on a total withdrawal of all 50,000 Syrian
troops in the war-plagued country. Syria, resisting pressure from
its traditional foe, is refusing to pull out even from Beirut,
where its soldiers and Christian Lebanese troops battled again
Thursday.
   Underscoring the general frustration, Kuwait resigned Thursday
from chairmanship of the league's six-nation committee on Lebanon.
   Behind closed doors, foreign ministers searched for a compromise
acceptable to Syria and Iraq, which is the only outspoken Arab
supporter of Lebanese Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tarik Aziz told reporters after a
five-hour session: ``We are still looking at the options. The main
one is for total Syrian withdrawal. If that is not achieved, there
cannot be a solution.''
   Aziz returned to the hotel lobby late in the evening to announce
that a Kuwaiti-Egyptian compromise solution was being submitted to
the summit for approval at a late night session.
   He gave no details of the compromise but said the Syrians
continued to block every compromise suggested on Lebanon.
   Unless there is a last-minute change, he said, ``I think the
situation is going to deteriorate very badly.''
   The summit had been delayed from closing Wednesday by the
quarrel over Lebanon.
   Syria, stressing its geographic proximity and historic links to
Lebanon, claimed its withdrawal would leave a security vacuum
facing Israel and fuel the 14-year civil war. Syrian troops have
been deployed there since 1976 under an an Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein argued at a late-night closed
summit session Wednesday that Syria no longer is a neutral mediator
in Lebanon because its troops are fighting alongside Moslems.
   Conference sources said Saddam also accused Syria of introducing
a new complication by allowing Iranian Revolutionary Guards into
Lebanon.
   The sources said most Arab countries agree on the need to
curtail, if not end, Syria's monopoly in Lebanese affairs.
   King Hussein of Jordan suggested compromising with a joint Arab
peace force but said Syria must have a role.
   ``It is high time for the Arabs to lift the heavy burden that
Syria and its forces in Lebanon ... have had to carry alone,'' he
said. But a solution would come ``only through a comprehensive Arab
effort in which Syria would have its role alongside its Arab
brethren.''
   But only Jordan openly has expressed willingness to send troops
to Lebanon, the sources said on condition of anonymity. Jordan's
delegation made available the text of Hussein's speech.
   He backed Iraqi demands that Iranian forces should be withdrawn.
About 2,000 Iranian Revolutionary Guards deployed in Lebanon in
1982, ostensibly to help fight the invading Israeli army. It was
not clear if Hussein was suggesting that more Iranians lately have
entered Lebanon.
   The Jordanian leader also called for Israel's withdrawal from
its self-designated security zone in south Lebanon, carved out
after the 1982-1985 invasion, and suggested the U.N. Security
Council mediate.
   The Lebanon crisis and Palestinian issue have dominated a
conference convened primarily to reinstate Egypt in the Arab League
after 10 years of ostracism for signing peace with Israel.
   Conference sources said Syria has voiced reservations over
Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat's peace
moves, including his recognition of Israel.
   But the sources said the Syrians would not block a resolution
backing Arafat because they already are too isolated on the Lebanon
issue.
</TEXT>
