<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MissionaryFervor     05-25 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missionary Fervor,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missionary Work Long Tradition For Young Mormons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Missionaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Mormon missionaries killed in Bolivia
were part of a long tradition that sends thousands of young Mormons
into the far corners of the world to share their faith.
   Since The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints was
founded in 1830, its members have been taught that the task of
reaping converts was a high and holy calling _ more important than
school, career or courtship.
   Todd Ray Wilson and Jeffrey Brent Ball, shot to death on their
way home in La Paz late Wednesday, were products of a missionary
zeal that has made Mormonism one of the world's fastest growing
religions.
   The radical Zarate Willka Armed Liberation Front claimed
responsibility shortly after the shootings. It is the same group
that last summer tried to kill former Secretary of State George
Shultz when he was visiting La Paz.
   Ball, 20, of Wanship, Utah, left college and a girlfriend to
become a missionary.
   Wilson, 20, of Wellington, Utah, also forsook his studies and
worked at a restaurant to finance two years of missionary service.
He, too, had a girlfriend.
   Ball's older sister is serving a mission in Guatemala and in
both families brothers of the victims also are preparing for
missionary service.
   Among Mormons such sacrifices are not uncommon. Worldwide the
faith is served by about 36,000 volunteer missionaries who work
without salary. Most either pay their own way or are supported by
their families or local congregations.
   Each year, they bring about 200,000 converts to the 6.6
million-member church.
   All young men are urged to serve missions before marriage or
completing college. In recent years the church increasingly has
urged older couples and single young women to join the ranks.
   ``It's a scriptural mandate and early presidents of the church
and church leaders down through the years have emphasized that
mandate,'' said church spokesman Don LeFevre.
   The faith's founder, Joseph Smith, taught that all other
religions were false and told his followers to carry his message to
``every nation, kindred, tongue and people.''
   Proselytizing even reaches beyond the grave. Mormons conduct
proxy baptisms for non-Mormon ancestors in the hope they will
accept the faith in the hereafter.
   John Jaussi, former bishop of the Wanship congregation, said
that typically about five people from the mostly Mormon community
of 250 are serving missions at any given time.
   Currently, Wanship has a missionary in London and three just
returned from Argentina, North Carolina and Texas, he said.
   ``The average mission costs about $10,000, so it's quite a
sacrifice financially, but it's a sacrifice that's well worth it.
Families are quite happy to see their sons go out,'' he said.
   On Thursday, a new group of missionaries arrived at the church's
Missionary Training Center at Brigham Young University to study
doctrine and learn foreign languages before departing for their
assignments.
   Ed Pinegar, the center's director, declined to discuss the
shootings in Bolivia. He said through his secretary that the
trainees had not been informed of the tragedy, but would be told
later.
   During any given week, about 1,500 missionaries are at the
center, said LeFevre.
</TEXT>
