<FIRST>r a AM-Missionaries-Reax     05-25 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missionaries-Reax,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Express Sorrow At Missionaries' Deaths In Bolivia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Missionaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mormon missionary who was a star athlete
and another who was an honor student enjoyed Bolivia, where their
young lives were cut short by men with machine guns, their fathers
said Thursday.
   Jeffrey Ball and Todd Wilson were shot to death as they entered
their apartment in a poor neighborhood in La Paz on Wednesday. The
leftist Zarate Willka Armed Liberation Front claimed responsibility.
   Ball ``dearly loved it in Bolivia. Every letter we got was how
much he loved it there,'' said his tearful father, Brent.
   Arvil Wilson, a mine electrician in the coal-rich mountains near
his Wellington home, said his son wrote often, telling the family
how much he enjoyed the country and his prosyletizing.
   ``He loved the people,'' the elder Wilson said.
   Ball and Wilson, both 20, had been in Bolivia since last fall.
They were machine-gunned as they were entering their apartment in a
poor neighborhood. The leftist Zarate Willka Armed Liberation Front
claimed responsibility.
   ``Everyone's totally stunned,'' said Sandra Jaussi, a neighbor
of the Ball family in Wanship, about 65 miles east of Salt Lake
City.
   ``This is something we never would have imagined could happen to
one of our fine young men. We are so broken-hearted,'' she said.
   Her husband, John Jaussi, Ball's former bishop and high school
teacher, said the killings ``hit us particularly hard because it's
such a far-off place and it happened in such an unexpected manner.''
   At North Summit High School, Ball's ``whole dream was to play
football,'' said Earl Blonquist, his principal and coach.
   Ball, a stocky 200-pounder, played on the varsity as a freshman
and sophomore and was an all-state player his last two years. He
also was vice president of the student body.
   A knee injury in junior college put an end to football, the
coach said.
   ``His goal got changed,'' Blonquist said. ``He was a competitor.
I felt he was doing what he should have been doing.''
   Ball's sister, Wendy, is a missionary in the Guatemala-Guatemala
City North Mission.
   Arvil Wilson said his son was the seventh of 10 children and an
honors graduate of Carbon High. During his few quarters at the
College of Eastern Utah, he was the night manager of a restaurant
in nearby Price.
   However, unable to keep up the pace, he dropped out of school
and worked to save money for his mission.
   ``He was a very joyful kid, liked to kid around,'' the elder
Wilson said. ``He was good at what he did.''
   Another of his sons, Brad, is preparing to leave on a mission
this summer for the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   ``We're all very emotionally hurt,'' said Roger Branch,
president of the church's Wellington Stake. ``But we're all doing
fine, the family's doing fine. It hurts, but there is no anger, no
meanness.''
</TEXT>
