<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SovietCongress-Scene     05-25 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Congress-Scene,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Pulls The Strings, But Deputies Savor Taste of Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the new Soviet parliament opened Thursday,
the free debate that characterized the session took a little
getting used to.
   Vitaly Korotich, editor of the avant-garde weekly Ogonyok,
compared the session to ``dancing lessons for legless people.''
   ``We don't really know how to move in conditions of democracy,''
he said.
   At the start of the proceedings, the only leader on the stage
was a towering statue of Soviet founder and veritable Communist
saint Vladimir Lenin.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev was just another portly, balding party man
in the front row until he was elected temporary chairman and left
his fellow deputies to take charge of the Congress under Lenin's
watchful gaze.
   Then Gorbachev became puppetmaster, pulling strings to set the
session dancing to his desires.
   Dozens of deputies strode decisively to the one microphone in
the well to argue procedural points or offer frank criticism and
probing questions of Gorbachev and his government. Their colleagues
in the Kremlin's starkly modern glass-and-granite Palace of
Congresses laughed, booed, glowered and listened avidly _ an abrupt
contrast to the bored perusing of Pravda typical in the old
parliament.
   Defeat did not discourage the vanquished, so thrilled were they
to hear the debate.
   ``We've never had anything like this,'' said Alexander N. Kraiko
of Moscow, undeterred by his side's defeat in an attempt to hear
the candidates before voting on them.
   The vote on that proposal was overwhelming, with only 379 of the
2,250 deputies voting on Kraiko's side. But it was only last
October that the old Soviet parliament experienced its first ``no''
votes when 13 brave souls raised their hands to oppose a law on
using paramilitary troops against demonstrators. At the time,
colleagues gasped, smirked and pointed at the handful making a
historic break with decades of unanimity.
   ``Debates are going on,'' said Deputy Dmitri S. Likhachev on
Thursday. ``That's democracy.''
   Gorbachev displayed a surprising mastery of parliamentary
trickery. He ignored amendments he didn't like, ordering votes on
the original proposals instead. He gave early speakers five
minutes, later ones only 30 seconds.
   Vitas Tomkus, a Lithuanian delegate, observed that when
Gorbachev agreed with a suggestion, he genially asked for the
hall's opinion.
   ``He carries on like a god, permitting others to speak,'' Tomkus
said with reluctant admiration for the leader's skill. ``He's like
a great actor, attuned to the hall.''
   Outside the vast auditorium, reporters who in the past were
hemmed into a distant balcony and only occasionally released for
brief meetings with chosen delegates were stunned to find
themselves wandering about the lobby surrounded by hundreds of
deputies. Some journalists even bumped into members of the ruling
Politburo, who are almost never seen in public.
   In a hallway on the ground floor of the auditorium, masses of
chain-smokers reduced visibility to about 10 yards, but there was
no indication of politicking or caucusing in the room. It was
strictly for smoking.
   At the lunch break, Tomkus and several of his fellow Lithuanian
deputies relaxed in the Kremlin sunshine, cracking strained jokes
about the impossibility of winning approval for their radical
proposals for Baltic sovereignty. They looked thoroughly out of
place among deputies generally 25 years their senior.
   ``Look,'' Tomkus joked, pointing at some passing deputies
sporting distinctive felt caps that marked them as representatives
of conservative Central Asia. ``There are some more who won't vote
for us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
