<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan     05-25 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto Removes General Who Distributed US Aid to Afghan Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto has
removed the army intelligence chief who distributed millions of
dollars worth of U.S. military aid to Afghan guerrillas, officials
reported Thursday.
   Lt. Gen. Hamid Gul, director of Inter Services Intelligence, was
transferred to army headquarters in neighboring Rawalpindi and
replaced by retired Gen. Shamsur Rahman Kallu, a Defense Ministry
spokesman said privately. Gul distributed the aid to insurgent
groups based in Pakistan. Both Pakistan and the United States have
helped finance and supply guerrillas fighting the Soviet-supported
Afghan government.
   Moderate Afghan guerrilla organizations accused Gul of giving
most of the assistance to the Islamic fundamentalists Hezb-e-Islami
led by Gulbuddin Hekmatyar.
   He also was believed to be behind the much-criticized attack by
guerrillas on Jalalabad, their first major assault after Soviet
troops withdrew Feb. 15 after nine years of involvemnt in the
Afghan civil war.
   Some insurgent leaders predicted the eastern city would fall
within a few days after the attack began March 6, but the battle
has been stalemated for weeks.
   The Afghan government welcomed the news about Gul. Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said in Kabul: ``Maybe
Pakistan is not continuing to pursue a military option. ... This
may be a step toward a peaceful settlement with Pakistan.''
   Gul was appointed by President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, a general
who was killed in a plane crash last year that investigators
described as sabotage.
   Zia forced Kallu to retire after Kallu said he should step down
as army chief of staff while serving as president.
   Analysts said Gul's removal indicated Ms. Bhutto's growing
strength in Pakistan, the first Moslem nation in modern times to be
governed by a woman. In 1977, Zia overthrew her father, Prime
Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who was hanged two years later.
</TEXT>
