<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RewardsofPatience     05-25 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rewards of Patience,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say Patience Among Children Pays Off Later In Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four-year-olds who were able to wait the
longest in pre-school for rewards of candy treats tend later in
life to accomplish more, to be more intelligent and to have higher
scores on college entrance exams, researchers said Thursday.
   That's the finding of three Columbia University researchers who
followed up on experiments conducted in the 1970s among students at
a Stanford University pre-school. The study is to be published
Friday in the journal Science.
   Columbia researchers Walter Mischel, Yuichi Shoda and Monica L.
Rodriguez reported in the study that ``children who tend to prefer
delayed rewards ... tend to be more intelligent, more likely to
resist temptation, to have greater social responsibility and higher
achievement strivings.''
   And when those children later took Scholastic Aptitude Tests for
college, the co-authors said, the patience they demonstrated in
pre-school is reflected in higher scores and better academic
performance.
   The early studies at Stanford involved teaching pre-schoolers a
game in which they were shown a pair of treats of different value
prior to being left alone in a room. The first treat, for instance,
could be one marshmallow, and the more valuable treat could be two
marshmallows.
   Each child was told that they could receive the more valuable
treat by waiting until the experimenter returned to the room.
   The wait could be ended at any time by ringing a bell, but this
would result in the least valuable of the treats. In effect, the
rule was, the longer they waited, the more they got.
   After a child was left alone, the researchers recorded the
length of the delay and observed the child without being seen.
Typically, the child was left alone for about 15 minutes, unless
the child ended the wait himself.
   A recent follow-up, said the researchers, showed that ``those
who had waited longer in this situation at 4 years of age were
described more than 10 years later by their parents as adolescents
who were more academically and socially competent than their peers
and more able to cope with frustration and resist temptation.''
   At least 35 of the children tested in the 1970s in one variation
of the experiment have since taken SAT examinations for college
admission and the researchers said, ``their verbal and
quantititative SAT scores were significantly related to seconds of
preschool delay time.''
   The more seconds that a child was able to wait while a
pre-schooler, the study said, the higher the child later scored on
the SAT tests.
   Since there was only a small sample in the group that has taken
SAT exams, the Columbia researchers said that the finding
``dictates special caution.'' They said more research is needed to
establish the relationship between learning at an early age to
``delay gratification'' and the later effects in life.
   Science, which published the study, is a the journal of the
American Association for the Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-TallShip-Rescue     05-25 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tall Ship-Rescue,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Tall Ship Rescues Two From Fishing Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American tall ship Pride of
Baltimore II, which replaced a topsail schooner that sank in 1986,
on Thursday rescued two men whose fishing boat was sinking.
   Officials at the Halifax search and rescue center said most
rescue aircraft in the area were grounded by dense fog when the
distress call came in from the 36-foot Miss Clara at 2 p.m.
   The Pride of Baltimore II, which was sailing for Halifax to
promote Maryland tourism, picked up the call and was near the site
about 25 miles off Nova Scotia's south shore near Port Mouton.
   Coast guard vessels, four other fishing boats and an aircraft
from Prince Edward Island had set out when the rescue center was
told at 2:21 p.m. that the Pride II had taken the two men off a
life raft.
   ``They picked up the two chaps and everything was fine,'' said a
spokesman for the center.
   No reason was given for the sinking of the Miss Clara, which
went down in light seas with waves of only about 18 inches.
   The Pride II represents Maryland state and is a replica of a
Baltimore clipper from the early 1800s. It replaced the Pride of
Baltimore, which sank in a storm off Puerto Rico in May 1986 with
the loss of four lives.
   Last Sunday, the ship began a four-month cruise to Canada and
the Great Lakes to promote tourism and economic development in
Maryland. It is scheduled to visit Halifax, Montreal and Toronto,
then call at American cities on the Great Lakes.
</TEXT>
