<DOCNO> AP890525-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Tiananmen-Sanitation     05-25 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tiananmen-Sanitation,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poor Sanitation Endangers Health of Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at the fore of China's wave of political
dissent live in a makeshift city of appalling squalor, in unheated
rag tents with no sewage or plumbing facilities.
   Tens of thousands camped out on the vast Tiananmen Square in the
heart of Beijing risk epidemics of flu, enteritis and
conjunctivitis because of poor sanitation, medical officials say.
   ``There are just too many people here. How can you clean all the
corners and get rid of all this garbage?'' said a nurse from Temple
of Heaven Hospital.
   ``About 40 garbage trucks come to Tiananmen every day to pick up
the trash, but look what's still here,'' she said, gesturing to one
of hundreds of piles of refuse dotting the 100-acre square.
   The students, whose numbers in the square at times have topped
200,000, have occupied it since May 13 to press for democratic
reforms.
   Thousands of plastic soda bottles, juice cartons and jagged
glass fragments are strewn among the tents. Television news said
Thursday that 143 tons of garbage had been collected.
   Buckets of waste stand beside bicycle carts distributing food.
Two public buses have been converted to toilets.
   On Wednesday, the Red Cross Society of China asked the students
to leave the square to avoid an outbreak of contagious diseases. It
urged caution in handling food and drinking water and warned
Beijing residents, who have been drawn to the scene by the hundreds
of thousands, to avoid the area.
   The Beijing Evening News said Thursday that 9,158 students had
been taken to local hospitals, most of them for stomach and eye
ailments.
   ``It's awful. We all eat with our hands, and several people
drink from the same bottle,'' said a young woman from Beijing
Agricultural Institute.
   ``Our tent's only two by three meters (6{ by 10 feet), but 14
people sleep in it lying down and several others sleep sitting up
around the sides,'' she said. ``We only have cotton jackets spread
on the ground, but they all got wet in the rain, so we were sitting
around on soggy jackets.''
   Students complain of stale air inside the tents, fouled by the
odor of unwashed bodies.
   Qi Bing, a freshman at Hubei Law School in Wuhan, a 20-hour
train ride from the Chinese capital, said he hadn't bathed in three
days and would not be able to for the next three.
   Another dozen students take shelter in a canvas-covered frame
used to cover a hospital truck. ``We have enough water to drink,
but for washing our hands and face it's something else,'' said
Zhang Fuzhi of Beijing No. 1 Light Industry School.
   Temporary latrines have been set up outside the Museum of
History on one side of the square.
   Several hospitals, including the Temple of Heaven, have pitched
their own tents among the student squatters. ``We're doing all
right as far as medicine goes, though we're getting low on
antibiotics,'' said a doctor from the hospital.
   ``I tell the students ... to take it easy and go to a hospital
if they can,'' he said. ``It's a bad environment out here. It's
dirty, it gets real hot, then real cold. It's hardly a place to get
well.''
</TEXT>
