<HEAD>Network Reports Zhao on Way Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC News reported from Beijing Thursday that
sources close to the Politburo said Communist Party chief Zhao
Ziyang will be stripped of power.
   The report said Ziyang and some other members of the hierarchy
would be branded as having formed an anti-party clique.
   It quoted the sources as saying the decision was made at a
special meeting of the Politburo, the party's ruling body, led by
Deng Xiaoping, China's 84-year-old senior leader.
   An announcement on the purges is expected within days, the
report said.
   The sources told ABC that for the power shift to be enforced, a
military occupation of Beijing may be imminent.
   Others to be stripped of power are Defense Minister Qin Jiwei,
believed to have opposed the imposition of martial law in Beijing;
propaganda chief Hu Qili, who allowed the press freedom to report
the protests; and Vice Premier Tian Jiyun, who has helped implement
Zhao's liberal economic policies, ABC said.
   Weeks of mass demonstrations in Beijing and other Chinese cities
are believed to have provoked a power struggle between Zhao, a
relative moderate, and conservatives led by Premier Li Peng and
Deng.
   Also involved in the decision to make the purges was President
Yang Shangkun, ABC said. Yang has said he was embarassed by the
protesters during the recent visit by Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev.
