<FIRST>r w AM-SeabrookLicense 2ndld-writethru a0721 05-25 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook License, 2nd ld-writethru, a0721,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Poised To Issue License Friday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update, INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf pvs, bgng, `The court...
to add Dukakis, Shannon reax; INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf pvs, bgng,
`Energy Secretary... to add plant reaction; DELETE 10th graf pvs, bgng,
`While the... to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said it will
issue a low-power test license for the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear
reactor Friday, after a federal appeals court rejected a last-gasp
plea by opponents.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in a ruling issued late
Thursday afternoon, refused to impose an emergency stay on
low-power tests at Seabrook, a $6 billion plant that is already a
decade behind schedule and billions over budget.
   The court order had been sought by Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis and other opponents who have tried for three years to block
low-power testing.
   In Boston, Dukakis attacked the planned low-power licensing,
saying there is no acceptable plan to evacuate nearby residents in
case of an accident ``nor is there any evidence that such a plan
can even be produced.''
   The governor and Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon
vowed to continue the fight against a full-power commercial
operating license. ``We're not out this by a long shot,'' said
Shannon.
   NRC Chairman Lando W. Zech Jr. said a commercial license could
come as soon as this fall, but Shannon predicted ``we have a long
fight ahead of us,'' with a web of regulatory and court appeals
still to come.
   In a one-page order, the appeals court said, ``Petitions have
failed to demonstrate the requisite irreparable injury and
likelihood of success on the merits to warrant the preliminary
relief sought.''
   NRC spokesman Frank Ingram said the license would be issued
Friday morning.
   Seabrook officials said they would start preparations for atomic
testing immediately after receiving commission authorization and
begin the plant's first nuclear tests within 10 days.
   Low-power testing, which would allow the reactor to operate at 5
percent capacity, would be the biggest milestone in the checkered
20-year history of Seabrook.
   The 1,150-megawatt reactor on the southern New Hampshire coast
has been set back 10 years by protests, politics, regulatory
obstacles and financial crises that have increased the project's
cost tenfold and left the lead owner seeking bankruptcy protection.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins this week jumped into the
fray, saying the plant is badly needed to meet New England's
increasing energy needs and avoid brownouts and other regional
energy emergencies.
   An elated Edward Brown, president of Seabrook operator New
Hampshire Yankee, said: ``We will successfully complete low-power
testing. We will go into commericial operation and we will produce
safe, efficient, clean electricity, electricity that will supply
more than 1 million New England homes and businesses.''
   ``Seabrook Station is the safest power plant that's ever been
built, and we are staffed with a team of operators and engineers
that I think are unsurpassed anywhwere in the world,'' Brown said
at a Seabrook news conference.
   The low-power license became the rallying point for Seabrook
opponents, many of whom have been trying to kill the plant for two
decades.
   Seabrook's three-year quest for a low-power license was first
halted in 1986 when Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, in the
wake of the Chernobyl accident in the Soviet Union, refused to
cooperate with evacuation planning for the six northeast
Massachusetts towns near the plant.
   Dukakis says it is impossible to quickly evacuate the coastal
area, especially when beach goers swell the area's summer
population.
   A low-power license was set back again last year when Seabrook's
lead owner, Public Service Company of New Hampshire, filed for
federal bankruptcy protection.
   The NRC approved the license after Seabrook officials set up a
$72.1 million fund to cover the estimated added costs of
mothballing the plant if it undergoes low-power testing but never
operates commercially. But the commissioners, in a 4-0 ruling last
Thursday, said it would delay issuance of the license for one week
to give the court time to rule on the stay petition.
</TEXT>
