<HEAD>Bush Gives Medal of Freedom to Pepper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday awarded the
nation's highest civilian award to Claude Pepper, the 88-year-old
congressman from Florida who lies gravely ill in Walter Reed Army
Medical Center.
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, visited the hospital to present the
Presidential Medal of Freedom to Pepper. The accompanying citation
praised the lifelong champion of the elderly for his ``career
dedicated to preserving the values that make American great.''
   ``As a champion of the most vulnerable among us, Claude Pepper
has enhanced America's national character,'' it said. ``Through his
legislative efforts and personal example, he has helped the
disadvantaged and elderly gain self respect and dignity. During six
decades of public service, Claude Pepper has built bridges that
span the generations.''
   It was the second time the president has visited the
hospitalized congressman.
   Pepper, the oldest member of Congress and chairman of the House
Rules Committee, is known for his efforts to establish and
strengthen the Social Security and Medicaid programs.
   Pepper is suffering from an undisclosed stomach ailment.
