<FIRST>u i AM-China-Reax     05-25 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Reax,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Crisis Hits Hong Kong Stock Market, Gives Vietnam Jitters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   By The Associated Press
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   China's political crisis gave the Hong Kong Stock Exchange a bad
case of the jitters Thursday and stirred concern in Vietnam that
China might attempt ``outside adventures'' to distract from its
domestic problems.
   The European Parliament, representing the 12 European Community
member states, called in Strasbourg, France, for China's leaders to
talk to student demonstrators who for five weeks have been
demanding more democracy.
   Share prices took their worst beating in Hong Kong's morning
session since the October 1987 worldwide market collapse. They
rebounded in the afternoon but still ended the day sharply lower.
   Brokers attributed the fall to nervousness over China's power
struggle. The market snapped back after China's Foreign Affairs
Ministry announced that both antagaonists, Premier Li Peng and
Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, still held their
posts.
   British-run Hong Kong reverts to Chinese rule in 1997. Investors
there remain skittish over political shifts in China even though
the Beijing government has promised to preserve the territory's
social and economic lifestyle for 50 years.
   The Hang Seng Index of blue chips closed at 2,752.51, down
256.22 points from Wednesday. The morning session ended at 2,668.70
points, a drop of 340.03 points, before rebounding.
   Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach expressed concern in
Hanoi on Thursday that China's government may start something
outside China to deal with its political crisis at home.
   ``Over the past 40 years China has witnessed one political
upheaval every 10 years,'' he said. ``What worries foreign
countries is whether China would carry out outside adventures to
solve its internal crisis.''
   He spoke in an interview with The Associated Press.
   China shares a long and often embattled 800-mile border with
Vietnam.
   Rivalry between the two dates to 111 B.C., when China's Han
Dynasty annexed what is now Vietnam and the Vietnamese began
fighting off Chinese invasions.
   They were close allies during the Vietnamese communist war
against the Americans, but later fell out again over other issues.
   Philippines Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus said in Manila on
Thursday that the unrest in China shows that the radical ideology
of Mao Tse-tung is dying there.
   ``I think Maoism as we knew it has been dying and, with this
development, is probably to be considered in agony,'' he told
reporters. ``I don't think anybody in China anymore seriously
believes in the old Maoist ideology.''
   ``Certainly, the developments in China will have an impact on
the region,'' Manglapus added, without citing what changes could be
expected.
   In Budapest, Hungary, about 30 members of the FIDESZ independent
youth group held a two-hour rally in front of the Chinese Embassy
on Thursday in a show of solidarity with the Beijing students, the
state MTI news agency said.
   Some held aloft posters calling for more democracy in China. One
poster, addressed to the Chinese students, said, ``We Are With
You.''
</TEXT>
