<FIRST>u a AM-TapDay     05-25 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tap Day,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tap Dancers Shuffle Across Golden Gate During National Tap Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chorus line of shuffle-stepping tap
dancers hoofed it across the Golden Gate Bridge on Thursday,
celebrating National Tap Dance Day on the birthday of legendary
tapper Bill ``Bojangles'' Robinson.
   The wind and salty air threatened to blow off their hats as
about 30 dancers shim-sham-shimmied across the span dodging
befuddled joggers and bicyclists.
   ``I don't care if I'm overweight and pushing 40. I feel like a
star,'' said tap dancer Debby Keleher, thrusting her arms out like
Ethel Merman.
   The BART escalator mechanic, who practices on broken subway
escalators in her cowgirl costume, passed a gold-sequined ``torch
of tap'' during the single-file relay watched by wide-eyed drivers.
   Against a backdrop of San Francisco skyscrapers and a vast
expanse of water below, the tappers made their way from Marin to
the San Francisco side where they received a City Hall proclamation.
   In Washington, Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., got a resolution
approved by the House declaring Thursday National Tap Dance Day.
Conyers, who admitted being a frustrated tap dancer soon to begin
lessons, was playing host to celebrations in the nation's capital
by the Tap America Project.
   ``Tap dancing is widely recognized as America's only original
form of dance, yet for years it has been in danger of becoming a
lost art,'' Conyers, said in a telephone interview.
   He said Bojangles' former dance partner, 65-year-old Lloyd
Story, tried to tap on the House floor but was barred by the
parliamentarian, who said it violated rules against demonstrations.
   On the bridge, English tourist Joan Burke let out a whoop when
the dancers assembled.
   ``Oh great. We saw `42nd Street,' the musical in London. Yes,
it's super. This is a bonus,'' Burke said as her husband, Paul,
snapped pictures of dancers from the group Rosie Radiator and the
San Francisco Supertappers.
   The troupe, led by Rosie in her red flared skirt, white tuxedo
vest, and sailor hat, is listed in the Guinness Book of World
Records for longest tap dance for its 7.3-mile performance in 1987.
   Seven tap dancers with sandwich boards were barred from crossing
the span by officials who feared written words would distract
commuters on the six-lane bridge.
   But everything was copacetic, as Bojangles used to say, for an
``aerobitapper,'' with metal taps on her running shoes, and a
tapping clown, who stomped their way across.
   Tap, a rhythmic art that blends African dance with the Irish jig
and lively English clog, originated among black dancers performing
on street corners and in saloons.
   Unlike ballet dancers, tap dancers hold their body limp like a
rag doll and use the natural movements to belt out rhythms with
their feet.
   Tap greats such as Bill ``Bojangles'' Robinson, who died in
1949, and Howard ``Sandman'' Sims popularized the dance in musical
extravaganzas of the 1930s and 40s.
   ``There is a happiness there when I tap dance,'' said hoofer
Marilyn Winston. ``There are very few ways that comes out of my
body. It's a natural happiness that comes out of me. I have to tap
to live.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
