<DOCNO> AP890525-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-WrightProbe 3rdLd-Writethru a0729 05-25 1035</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0729,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Say Wright All But Decided to Resign</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: new 4th graf to summarize Foley news conference; SUBS 14th graf,
The ethics ..., to clarify connection between resignation as speaker and
from House; INSERTS one graf after 17th pvs, Foley publicly ..., to give
Foley quotes.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright has all but decided
to resign his leadership post, friends said Thursday, but he
remained torn over details of his leaving and insisted he had
``done no serious wrong'' despite numerous ethics allegations.
   Congressional sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
plans were being made for Wright to make a farewell address to the
House on Wednesday.
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley of Washington appeared to be the
odds-on favorite to replace him in the top post in the House.
   Foley, at a news conference in Seattle, said he knew of no plans
by Wright to resign, but he said Wright expressed a desire to state
his case next week or shortly afterward.
   Wright, first elected to Congress 34 years ago, remained in his
Capitol office during the day. From there, he issued a statement
proclaiming there would be ``no deal'' in which he would quit his
post in exchange for dismissal of some of the ethics committee
charges.
   But his departure seemed ever more likely.
   ``There are plans for Wednesday, but we don't know if he'll do
it,'' said one friend of the Texas Democrat. ``He's torn between
wanting to be heard (in an ethics committee hearing) and doing
what's best for himself and the House.''
   The speaker was said to have been personally hurt by reports on
Wednesday that he had sought to negotiate a plea bargaining
arrangement with the ethics committee, which charged him April 17
with 69 violations of House rules.
   In his statement, he said: ``There is no deal now. There will be
no deal in the future. ... I earnestly believe that I have
committed no serious wrong in the conduct of my official duties or
of my private affairs.''
   But it was clear that there had been a flurry of proposals and
counter-proposals between Wright's representatives and the ethics
panel on Wednesday. Those efforts fell short of agreement, but some
on both sides still held out hope that a negotiated settlement
could be achieved.
   Rep. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., a member of Wright's legal
defense team who was involved in the talks, said he believed a
consensus was emerging among ethics committee members that charges
Wright improperly accepted gifts from a businessman friend with a
direct interest in legislation were not well founded.
   The other serious charge against Wright _ that he evaded House
limits on outside income through bulk sales of his book to groups
to which he had delivered speeches _ was believed by panel members
to be on solid ground, Torricelli said.
   Wright spokesman Mark Johnson said the Texas Democrat planned a
weekend getaway with his wife Betty to an undisclosed location. One
lawmaker close to the talks speculated that Wright would spend the
time writing his final speech.
   ``I think he just wants his day in the well,'' said the source,
referring to the front of the House chamber.
   The ethics panel was scheduled to meet again next Thursday. But
that session could be rendered moot if Wright both stepped down as
speaker and, as associates have reasoned, resigned his House seat.
Friends of the speaker said he was making his plans independent of
any action by the ethics committee and was not deterred by the
collapse of Wednesday's talks.
   As the planning continued, would-be successors to Wright and
other House Democratic leaders who might move up or out in a
shake-up could not restrain behind-the-scenes campaigning.
   ``There's a certain amount of inappropriateness in mounting a
campaign before the funeral,'' said Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont.
``Our bizarre system in Congress somehow puts the hanging in front
of the trial, and Jim Wright looks up and it's his corpse that's
swinging,'' he said.
   Foley publicly dismissed assertions that Wright was poised to
resign. But fellow House Democrats were already privately assuming
he would shortly be speaker.
   ``I have no expectations that the speaker is going to resign,''
Foley said in Seattle. ``He repeated his desire to have an
opportunity to state his case, his side of the case, to the widest
possible audience and he's determined to take that opportunity at
the first time that seems appropriate. I assume that will be with
either next week or shortly thereafter.''
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., was being urged strongly by
supporters to run to replace Foley as majority leader, the No. 2
position. It was unclear whether the third-ranking Democrat in the
House, majority whip Tony Coelho of California, would seek to move
up or would be prevented from doing so by separate ethics questions
that have arisen over his business dealings.
   Contenders also were lining up for the No. 3 whip's spot,
including Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., the current chief deputy
whip, and Democratic Caucus Chairman Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa.
   Congressional sources confirmed that Wednesday's talks,
including offers by Wright's lawyers for him to resign his
leadership post in return for dropping some of the most serious
charges, had fallen apart.
   One lawmaker close to the discussions said there was still a
willingness on the part of ethics committee members, Democrats and
Republicans alike, to craft a negotiated settlement.
   However, Rep. John T. Myers of Indiana, the ethics committee's
senior Republican, said any sort of ``plea-bargaining'' arrangement
would be unprecedented and would set a nightmarish example for the
future.
   ``There have been members who have quit rather than face
charges, but we have no control over that,'' Myers said. ``But
where we have control, we say, we'll drop this if you'll do that.
... I don't really think the House of Representatives should do
this.''
   The effort was complicated by publicity about the dealing, said
one legislator who commented only on condition he not be named. He
said committee chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., ``doesn't want to
be perceived as asking for a negotiated settlement, and the speaker
doesn't either.''
</TEXT>
