<DOCNO> AP890525-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ireland-Election     05-25 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ireland-Election,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ireland's Minority Government Calls Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey's minority
government, elected 28 months ago by the narrowest margin possible,
on Thursday called for a general election June 15 in a bid to
capitalize on Ireland's economic revival and gain a majority.
   Haughey rose in the Dail, or parliament, and in a one-line
statement said he would ask President Patrick Hillery to formally
dissolve the 166-seat legislature.
   The election is timed to coincide with elections to the
12-nation European Parliament.
   Haughey is midway through a maximum five-year term. His fiscal
austerity has brought a turnaround from harsh recession, reflected
in a low inflation rate of 3.3 percent, a trade surplus and a
moderate economic growth rate.
   But with interest rates creeping up this month to 9.25 percent
and signs inflation may rise, Haughey wants to try for an outright
parliamentary majority before the economic situation deteriorates.
   In February 1987, Haughey and his Fianna Fail Party failed to
win a majority in the Dail for the second time. He won power on the
vote of a lone left-wing maverick, toppling the 1982-87 coalition
government of Garret FitzGerald.
   Fianna Fail is riding high in opinion polls, and critics say
opposition parties, led by the main opposition Fine Gael under its
new leader Alan Dukes, are in disarray and unable to offer a
credible alternative.
   An opinion poll published in the Sunday Independent newspaper on
May 7 gave Fianna Fail a 50 percent approval rating against 28
percent for the opposition. It said Haughey's personal approval has
climbed to a 54-percent peak.
   Critics complain that the improvements in this island republic
of 3.4 million people are not filtering through to the poor and the
young. Unemployment remains at 17.9 percent and emigration, at an
estimated 32,000 a year, is at its highest level since the 1950s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
