<FIRST>r a AM-KennedyAward     05-25 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kennedy Award,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kennedys Announce `Profiles in Courage' Award'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Jacqueline Onassis and President Kennedy's two
children looked on Thursday, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy announced the
creation of an award honoring political courage in public officials.
   The ``John F. Kennedy Profile in Courage Award'' was created to
honor the slain president and promote individualism among the
nation's public officials.
   ``Too often, contemporary elected officials are captives of
popular opinion and public opinion polls,'' Kennedy told a news
conference at the John F. Kennedy Library. ``They're unwilling to
resist partisan or regional pressures or offend powerful interest
groups.''
   The name of the $40,000 award is based on John Kennedy's book
``Profiles in Courage,'' which won the Pulitzer Prize in 1957.
   ``Ever since then, he has been closely linked in the public mind
with that idea,'' said Kennedy, D-Mass. ``We feel that the concept
of political courage captures the essence of President Kennedy's
enduring appeal, his vision of public service, and the continuing
challenge of elective office.''
   After Kennedy's remarks, reporters called on Mrs. Onassis,
wearing a hot pink jacket and a black miniskirt, to speak. But she
touched her son John's shoulder, saying, ``He'll speak for the
family.''
   The younger Kennedy spoke briefly, saying the award ``means a
great deal ... hopefully it will be administered well in years to
come.''
   His sister, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, also attended the news
conference.
   The award will be presented each year to those in public life
who demonstrate a ``principled stand for what they believe is right
on fundamental issues of the day, even though they are risking
their careers and the wrath of their constituents.''
   Award recipients will be named on John Kennedy's birthday May
29, according to the Kennedy family. The president, who was
assassinated in Dallas in 1963, would have been 72 years old this
Memorial Day.
   The first award will be presented next year.
   ``Our family is attempting to shift the tributes to President
Kennedy from the date of his assassination in November to the date
of his birth in May,'' Sen. Kennedy said. ``We want to remember his
life, not relive his death.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
