<HEAD>Doctors Say Khomeini Progressing Satisfactorily</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Khomeini shown on TV. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini got out of his hospital bed Thursday and rested in a
chair, two days after undergoing surgery on his digestive tract,
state-run Tehran television reported.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, showed Khomeini propped up
in bed in a Tehran hospital and saying a few words with his eyes
shut, and a tube in his nose. It did not show him sitting in a
chair.
   The medical team treating the 89-year-old leader said in a
statement that his condition was ``very good.'' It said his
``cardio-vascular system, blood pressure, pulse, respiration and
kidneys are satisfactory.''
   The statement said the internal bleeding that prompted the
operation was ``completely under control'' and that he had no need
of a blood transfusion after the operation.
   The medical statements issued on Khomeini's condition have not
named his illness.
   The television also repeated footage of Khomeini in the hospital
before the operation in response to thousands of telephone calls, a
commentator said.
   The film showed the Iranian leader sitting up in bed combing his
beard and performing his prayers.
   The commentary said, ``This is the hour not to think of the
operation but to be with God.''
