<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--TransplantDeath     05-25 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Transplant Death,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heart-Pancreas Transplant Patient Succumbs to Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A common virus killed the nation's first
heart-pancreas transplant patient, doctors at the Washington
Hospital Center said Thursday.
   About 80 percent of the population has carried the cytomegalo
virus at some point, but when Barry Katz contracted it he was
unable to fend it off, said Dr. John Macoviak, director of
transplant surgery.
   Katz, a 45-year-old Defense Department physicist from Silver
Spring, Md., died Wednesday night with family and friends at his
side, Macoviak said. Katz had been in critical condition since
undergoing surgery on March 25.
   Katz initially was given an 80 percent chance of surviving for a
year following the operation.
   Doctors were hopeful immediately after the surgery, when Katz
responded well, said hospital spokesman Alexander Sinclair, but he
suffered a setback in April, when an ulcer developed near the
transplanted pancreas and was removed.
</TEXT>
