<DOCNO> AP890525-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Hospitals     05-25 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Hospitals,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survival of AIDS Patients Better At Experienced Hospitals, Study
Suggests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS patients with a form of pneumonia commonly
fatal to them are more than three times as likely to survive in
hospitals experienced in treating AIDS sufferers than in other
hospitals, a study suggests.
   The findings support the belief that regional centers are needed
to provide the best care for people with the AIDS virus, said
authors of the study published in Friday's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   The study involved 257 AIDS patients with the infection called
pneumocystis carinii pneumonia. It found that the in-hospital death
rate was only 12 percent at experienced hospitals, compared with 33
percent at hospitals less familiar with AIDS.
   After making statistical adjustments to correct for differences
in severity of illness, the in-hospital death rate for AIDS
patients with the pneumonia was about 3.6 times higher than in less
experienced hospitals, the study said.
   Researchers said they studied patients with the pneumonia
because it is a common complication of AIDS, often treated
successfully, but frequently leading to death.
   Hospitals considered experienced in the study were those that
discharged at least 30 patients with AIDS-related medical problems
for every 10,000 patients discharged overall.
   All patients studied were at 15 California hospitals,
researchers said.
   It is likely that the technology for fighting AIDS is being
developed unevenly among the nation's hospitals ``and that
hospitals with low AIDS familiarity are at a marked disadvantage in
the treatment of patients with AIDS,'' said the researchers, led by
Dr. Charles L. Bennett of the RAND@University of California at Los
Angeles Center for Health Policy Study and the UCLA School of
Medicine.
   Creating regional AIDS centers soon would be a tough job,
according to an accompanying JAMA editorial in which Dr. Deborah J.
Cotton of Beth Israel Hospital in Boston said the nation's health
care system is already in crisis.
   Problems would include how to meet the patients' needs for
long-term care and community services outside the centers and the
possibility that special hospitals ``might increase the isolation
and stigmatization experienced by patients with AIDS.''
   ``Nonetheless, the creation of such centers should be considered
urgently as part of along-term planning strategies,'' she wrote.
``As AIDS therapy becomes more complex, the ability of many
acute-care hospitals to provide such therapy will become
increasingly difficult.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0689 05-25 0982</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,1013</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Chosen President by New Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with quotes, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB3,4,16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new parliament on Thursday reaffirmed its
predecessor's choice of Mikhail Gorbachev as president in a session
marked by unprecedented debate and tough questioning of a Soviet
leader.
   Gorbachev won more than 95 percent of the vote in uncontested
balloting at the opening session of the Congress of People's
Deputies, the first competitively chosen Soviet parliament.
   Maverick Communist Boris N. Yeltsin withdrew his name before the
vote, and the new parliament rejected a member who tried to
nominate himself.
   Although opponents of the established leadership were a distinct
minority, the combative atmosphere contrasted sharply with that of
previous Soviet parliaments that rubber-stampedthe actions of the
Kremlin leadership.
   Gorbachev received 2,123 of the 2,210 votes cast, Yuri A.
Osipyan, chairman of the commission that counted the ballots,
announced during the nationally televised proceedings. Eighty-seven
deputies voted against the Communist Party chief, Osipyan said, and
11 abstained.
   Gorbachev, who has led the Soviet Union since 1985, had been
elected president on Oct. 1 by the congress' predecessor, the
Supreme Soviet. He succeeded Andrei A. Gromyko in what was then a
largely ceremonial post.
   In the new governmental structure, the five-year presidency is
to be invested with greater powers, including the chairmanship of
the Defense Council and the right to propose laws and negotiate
with foreign powers.
   In a clear reference to past Soviet dictatorships, Gorbachev
vowed ``to pursue the line of democracy until the very end, so that
what has happened in this country will never again be repeated.''
   Communist Party ideology chief Vadim A. Medvedev told reporters
the party's victory in nationwide balloting in March entitled it to
pick its leader as president.
   ``The party went through the election process, it won support,
therefore the so-called Cabinet will be formed from its leaders,''
Medvedev said.
   One deputy sought to nominate Yeltsin to run against Gorbachev
for president, and a little-known engineer from Leningrad offered
himself as a sacrifice alternative to the Soviet leader.
   ``I'm no idiot, and I understand perfectly well that I have no
chances in a struggle with Mikhail Sergeyevich Gorbachev,'' said
Alexander Obolensky, the engineer. ``But I want there to be a
precedent of an alternative in elections in our history.''
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov, who was voted down
when he tried to require a state-of-the-union report from Gorbachev
before the election, said he would not take part in the secret
ballot.
   ``We can't let these elections just be a formality,'' the 1975
Nobel Peace Prize winner said. Sakharov was one of four deputies
who abstained when the body voted to place Gorbachev's name on the
ballot. No one voted against.
   Estonian activist Marju Lauristin offered Gorbachev her vote on
condition he answer some tough questions first.
   She said she wanted to know who in the ruling Politburo knew
about plans to use troops to break up a pro-independence
demonstration in Soviet Georgia last month and how soon Gorbachev
learned of them. Twenty people died in the unrest.
   ``There have been mistakes, major oversights,'' Gorbachev said.
``And some of them didn't have to happen. I'm suffering because of
them, too.
   ``We understand with our brains that it's necessary to change,''
he said. ``But the system doesn't let us.''
   Gorbachev said he had intended to send Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze, a Georgian, to Tbilisi before the demonstration
but was advised the situation was under control.
   Others demanded explanations for the privileges enjoyed by
Soviet leaders and of a decree banning statements that discredit
authorities. Some questioned whether he should serve as both
Communist Party chief and head of state.
   Yeltsin, whose populist campaign garnered 90 percent of the vote
in citywide elections in Moscow, took himself out of the running
after being nominated by a deputy from his native Sverdlovsk region
in the Urals.
   Yeltsin noted that as a member of the party's Central Committee,
he was bound by its decision to support Gorbachev. Only 14 deputies
opposed a motion not to put his name on the ballot.
   With the exception of the secret ballot, the entire session was
televised live, offering Soviets a rare look at the workings of
their government. Still, the Soviets' lack of experience with
parliamentary democracy was apparent.
   Gorbachev, as presiding officer, arbitrarily called for votes on
some procedural issues while ignoring others. Only a few deputies
objected.
   There was fierce debate over procedural issues, but the agenda
hammered out in advance by Gorbachev and a few hundred deputies in
a private caucus Wednesday was adopted by a lopsided margin.
Sakharov and economist Gavril Popov led the fight against the
establishment.
   Sakharov, once the nation's most famed dissident and now a
member of the parliament, praised Gorbachev.
   ``I don't see another person who could lead the country at this
time,'' said the winner of the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize. But he added
Gorbachev should first be required to give an account of the
mistakes and achievements of his reform program.
   Gorbachev, a giant statue of Vladimir I. Lenin at his back,
frequently intervened in the debate amid shouts from the floor,
guiding and controlling the assembly in the vast auditorium of the
Kremlin's marble-and-glass Palace of Congresses.
   At least 80 percent of the deputies are Communist Party members,
but the presence of a small band of reformers _ including
grassroots activists from the three tiny Baltic republics _ assured
that the congress will differ from the docile parliaments of the
past.
   Deputies squabbled over every point of the agenda.
   ``Just a moment, I haven't given you the floor,'' Gorbachev told
one deputy who walked to the podium and began to speak. ``I'll give
you the floor, but you have to ask for it.'' The member was then
permitted to speak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0209 </DOCNO>
