<FIRST>u a AM-LukensTrial     05-25 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lukens Trial,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Investigator Says Lukens Admitted Sex with Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTIN a0769 to fix overline. Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens acknowledged
having sex with a girl he knew was a minor, a private investigator
testified Thursday at a trial at which the congressman had no
defense witnesses.
   ``He admitted that he did have sexual intercourse with Rosie
Coffman,'' said J.D. Caudill, the final witness called by
prosecutors.
   Lukens' attorney Thomas Tyack, who called no witnesses, said the
defense was strapped by Judge Ronald Solove's refusal to allow him
to bring up Ms. Coffman's juvenile delinquency and school records.
   ``It puts us in the position of this man being tried in a
vacuum,'' Tyack said.
   Lukens, a 58-year-old conservative Republican, is being tried on
a misdemeanor charge of contributing to the delinquency of a minor.
The Franklin County Domestic Relations Court jury is expected to
get the case Friday. If convicted, Lukens could be sentenced to 180
days in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Assistant Prosecutor Rita Mangini said she had proved that Ms.
Coffman engaged in prostitution and consumed alcohol, both elements
of unruliness and delinquency, as a result of Lukens' actions.
   ``I would submit under these facts that Mr. Lukens is an immoral
person,'' she said.
   Caudill, a former Dayton police officer hired by Lukens' former
attorney, said the congressman admitted to the sexual encounter
when he came to Caudill's office for a polygraph examination Jan.
30.
   Caudill testified that Lukens, who is divorced, told him that
when the congressman and Ms. Coffman had sex at his apartment on
Nov. 6 she told him she would turn 18 the next day.
   Ms. Coffman, who actually was to turn 17, on Wednesday testified
that she had lied to Lukens by telling him she was 18 or 19. But
she said she also gave him her real birthdate: Nov. 7, 1971.
   Earlier Thursday, the jury heard a taped telephone conversation
in which Lukens, unaware that the FBI and police were recording the
call, denied to Anna Coffman, Rosie's mother, that he had sex with
the girl.
   In the tape, Lukens told Anna Coffman that her daughter had been
calling him and asked that she stop it. Mrs. Coffman said on the
tape that her daughter had confessed to her that she had sex with
Lukens on Nov. 6, the previous Sunday.
   ``She was there with Mercedes. What Mercedes and I did was
private. Your daughter had nothing to do with it,'' Lukens replied
on the tape. Mercedes was the name used by Rosie Coffman's friend,
Michelle Foster, then 19, who had invited Ms. Coffman to Lukens'
apartment that night.
   But Lukens in the phone call also asked Anna Coffman whether she
was still ``interested in the job.'' Mrs. Coffman has testified
Lukens earlier that day met her at a restaurant and tried to bribe
her with an offer to help her find a government job. Lukens claims
she was trying to extort money from him in exchange for her silence.
   Reporter Ted Hart of WSYX-TV in Columbus, who arranged to
secretly videotape the meeting between Anna Coffman and Lukens at
the restaurant, acknowledged the station paid for Anna and Rosie
Coffman's two-night stay at a hotel beginning Feb. 22, the day
Lukens was indicted.
   He denied that the station paid the Coffmans any money before
that for their story. Anna Coffman was first interviewed in
November after she called WSYX for help.
   Rosie Coffman had testified Wednesday that Lukens made her wear
a black robe to have sex with him and made racial slurs during the
evening. Lukens is white; Ms. Coffman is black.
   The outcome of the case will not directly affect Lukens'
standing in the House, to which he was elected in 1986 after
serving two terms in the 1960s. However, he could be subject to
disciplinary action by the ethics committee.
</TEXT>
