<FIRST>r i AM-SovietSub     05-25 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Sub,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Sunken Sub Was Powered By Water-Cooled Reactors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has informed Norway that a
submarine that sank in the Norwegian Sea on April 7 was powered by
conventional water-cooled reactors with low-enriched uranium cores,
officials said Thursday.
   Officials had thought that the Komsomolets was powered by more
dangerous liquid-metal-cooled reactors with high-enriched uranium
cores. Forty-two Soviet crewmen died in the accident.
   Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Sigrid Romundset said the Soviet
Foreign Ministry gave the information in a letter delivered to the
Norwegian Embassy in Moscow on Wednesday.
   ``The Soviet reply was surprising but reassuring. It will now be
studied by experts to make sure there are no misunderstandings
concerning the reactor types,'' said Knut Gussgard of Norway's
nuclear inspection agency, which had asked the Soviets for
information on the reactors.
   ``Some of our questions still remain unanswered, among them the
exact reactor size and the quantity of radioactive material in the
cores,'' he said.
   Johan Baarli, director of the Norwegian National Institute of
Radiation Protection, said earlier that tests last month showed
that the submarine's reactors and weapons have withstood tremendous
water pressure. Water samples collected near the sunken sub showed
no radiation that could be attributed to the vessel, the institute
said.
</TEXT>
