<FIRST>u a AM-FolsomViolence     05-25 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Folsom Violence,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worst Melee in Seven Years Leaves One Dead, Several Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FOLSOM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prisoner was killed and 48 others were
reported injured Thursday after some of the worst violence at
Folsom Prison in several years erupted in an exercise yard,
officials said.
   Guards fired 10 shots to break up the melee, wounding three
prisoners, said prison spokeswoman Lt. Cammy Voss.
   The three were hospitalized, as were two convicts who were
stabbed, Voss said.
   The fight appeared to have been racially motivated, Voss said.
Mostly black and Hispanic prisoners and a couple of white prisoners
were involved.
   Authorities don't believe the fight was gang-related, she said.
``We don't know why it erupted. There was no buildup that led up to
this ...''
   Officers locked all 7,000 inmates at the maximum-security prison
20 miles east of Sacramento into their cells.
   The slain inmate, who was black, was identified as Michael
Coleman, 29. He arrived at the prison April 20 to serve a four-year
term for a Los Angeles County armed robbery.
   Forty-three inmates were treated at the prison infirmary for
minor stab wounds, scrapes and cuts, said prison spokesman D.L.
Porter.
   However, not all the injuries were believed to have been
suffered in the fight, said state Department of Corrections
spokesman Tipton Kindel.
   Guards strip-searched the approximately 300 men who were in the
yard during the fight, Kindel said. Officers were required to list
all injuries not previously reported to authorities.
   ``Some of the injuries they said they knew were at least a day
old,'' he said. ``But by the procedures, they had to write those
down.''
   Voss said the fight was the worst violence at a new wing of the
prison that opened in 1986 and perhaps the worst at the entire
prison since racial violence involving mainly Hispanic and black
prison gang members led to an extended lockdown seven years ago.
</TEXT>
