<FIRST>u a AM-TeenAssault 1stLd-Writethru a0713 05-25 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Assault, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0713,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Divided Over Sexual Assault Case Of Mentally Retarded Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf to UPDATE with suspension of five
students who were charged; picks up 5th graf, `Damian DeVito.... Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN RIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrest of five high school boys _
including twins who co-captain the football team _ in the sexual
assault of a mentally retarded teen-ager has some students
condemning their classmates and others rallying to their defense.
   Eight other male teens, including the son of a police lieutenant
in the affluent town, cheered while they watched the attack,
investigators said. They are considered witnesses and have not been
charged.
   The five Glen Ridge High School students were arrested Wednesday
and charged with sexually assaulting the then 17-year-old girl with
a broomstick and miniature baseball bat.
   The case sparked taunts, threats and incidents of vandalism at
the school of 340 pupils. Thursday was the annual ``spring day'' at
Glen Ridge High and along with the picnics and games there were
fights, car vandalism and graffiti scrawled on walls inside the
school, students said.
   The five who were charged were suspended from school Thursday
for 10 days ``because of the disruption their presence in the
school would have on the educational program,'' said Superintendent
Rose McCaffrey.
   Damian DeVito, a 17-year-old junior, defended the accused
teen-agers, two of whom are his football teammates. He said he has
known the victim since elementary school and said he believes she
willingly participated in the March 1 incident.
   ``I know them well enough to know they wouldn't do anything
against somebody's will,'' DeVito said. ``These kids are really not
bad kids at all.''
   Nearby, one student removed a rock and shards of glass from the
back seat of his car. Some passers-by in cars shouted ``rapists''
as they went past the school.
   Students said one school wall inside had messages directed
against the youths accused in the case.
   Some students who were interviewed refused to give their names,
saying they were frightened by threats made by friends of the
accused students. A junior said he received a death threat
Wednesday from a telephone caller who warned him against talking
about the case.
   A girl who gave her name as W. Sanford said some students were
pulling together to support those involved. ``You've got to give
sympathy to both sides,'' she said.
   School officials refused Thursday to allow journalists onto the
campus, saying it would be disruptive. Reporters spoke to students
in the parking lot of the school in this community of 8,000 people
about 20 miles from New York City.
   The unidentified victim, now 18, met a group of youths in a
local park and then went to the nearby home of two of the teens
charged in the case, 18-year-old twins Kevin and Kyle Scherzer,
said Essex County Prosecutor Herbert Tate. The twins are
co-captains of the school football team and Kyle captains the
baseball team.
   The prosecutor said the girl is mentally retarded but refuses to
elaborate on the seriousness of her condition.
   Tate said the girl told a teacher about the attack on March 4
and that relatives and school officials took the information to
police on March 22. Police notified the prosecutor's office a week
later. The prosecutor's office took charge of the investigation
April 12.
   The teen-agers were arrested Wednesday morning. Tuesday night,
WNBC-TV in New York had broadcast a report on the case.
   Karl Greiner, a spokesman for the Association for Retarded
Citizens-New Jersey, called the attack demeaning.
   ``I suppose that she was treated like an object ... a
dehumanizing affair at best, with spectators cheering on,'' Greiner
said. ``It's difficult enough to live your life with a handicap.
It's especially difficult to be treated in a dehumanizing way.''
   Kevin Scherzer was charged with one count of conspiracy to
commit sexual assault, and two counts each of aggravated criminal
sexual contact and aggravated sexual assault.
   Kyle Scherzer and Peter Quigley, 18, were charged with
conspiracy and two counts of aggravated sexual assault. Quigley was
accused of cheering on the assault.
   A 17-year-old male and another student who has since turned 18
are charged as juveniles on all three counts, Tate said. Both boys
have appeared in Family Court, said Ray Weiss, a spokesman for Tate.
   The three students charged as adults are free on bail. One of
the two charged as juveniles was released to his parents, and the
other was in a juvenile detention house.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina     05-25 0825</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Reshuffled; Political, Economic Paralysis Spark Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lame-duck President Raul Alfonsin
on Thursday replaced his economy minister after weeks of political
paralysis and economic deterioration led hungry people to loot food
stores.
   Over the past three days, about a dozen supermarkets and food
stores in three of Argentina's biggest cities _ Cordoba, Rosario
and Mendoza _ were raided. Groups of men, women and children
entered the stores and filled shopping carts with food _ or ate it
on the spot _ and then fled.
   The Cabinet reshuffle was forced by the loss of Alfonsin's
Radical Civic Union to the Peronist Party in the May 14 national
elections. Alfonsin and President-elect Carlos Menem had discussed
plans to let Menem take over before Alfonsin's term expires Dec.
10, but the talks broke down.
   Jesus Rodriguez, chairman of the Budget and Treasury Committee
in the Chamber of Deputies, was named economy minister to replace
Juan Carlos Pugliese, who lasted less than two months in the job.
   Rodriguez, 33, is Alfonsin's fourth economy minister. Pugliese,
74, moved over to the Interior Ministry.
   Foreign Minister Dante Caputo, who recently was elected to the
Chamber of Deputies, was replaced by his top aide at the ministry,
Susana Ruiz Cerrutti.
   Most of the looting disturbances were relatively peaceful, but
police in Rosario used tear gas and rubber bullets Wednesday to
disperse a crowd of about 500. Several people suffered minor
injuries and several were arrested.
   In the capital, Buenos Aires, riot police were stationed at the
biggest supermarkets Thursday. No incidents were reported.
   Store officials initially withheld details of the disturbances
and presidential press secretary Jose Ignacio Lopez urged
newspapers to play down the incidents so as not to encourage
further raids.
   The two biggest newspapers in Buenos Aires, La Nacion and
Clarin, carried reports of the raids on inside pages. The Buenos
Aires Herald, however, bannered the story on the front page.
   Argentina has suffered a 90 percent devaluation of its currency,
the austral, since February. Inflation may hit 70 percent this
month. A severe budget deficit has forced double-digit rate hikes
for public services and delays in wage increases.
   Alfonsin's government has been in a quandary since Menem and the
Peronists won the May elections.
   Alfonsin retains political power, but Menem has the public
support needed to implement an unpopular economic program. But the
two could not agree on Menem taking office early, and on Tuesday
Alfonsin pledged to remain as scheduled until Dec. 10. He was to
swear in a new Cabinet Friday and unveil a new program Sunday.
   It was unclear what policies the new Cabinet would implement to
stabilize an economy whose deterioration cost Alfonsin's party
re-election.
   Recently the crisis in Argentina has had even more of an impact
on ordinary citizens. Meat prices jumped 70 percent this week and
consumption has dropped. Shoppers stare at packages of coffee or
cartons of milk, shake their heads and walk away without making a
purchase.
   Bakers say flour is so expensive they can't buy it to make
bread. Pharmacies, supermarkets and department stores that used to
sell on credit now insist on cash. Some have rationed supplies.
Many have bare shelves.
   ``The clerk told me, `We're not a bank,' when I went in to buy
medicine for my husband,'' said a middle-aged woman who asked that
she not be identified. ``He was on the operating table and the
hospital didn't have the drug. I grabbed the medicine and left my
watch'' at the pharmacy.
   Aldo Bignola, a 23-year-old auto mechanic waiting in line at the
Spanish consulate for a work visa, said, ``This is my home and I
hope to return to it and live here and die here. But not if it
means starving to death because I don't have any work.''
   Teachers, airline personnel and workers for the state oil
company say they will strike or stage job actions next week to
press demands for pay raises.
   A survey this week by the Latin America Research Foundation
indicated that businesses are operating at 66 percent of capacity,
and stocks are extremely low. Four of every 10 described their
economic situation as ``bad.''
   Dealers were allowed to raise new car prices by 105 to 183
percent effective Thursday. Many apartment owners now charge in
dollars and even middle class Buenos Aires residents find it
difficult to pay the rent, let alone save enough to buy their own
homes.
   Banks, some of which are on the verge of collapse, limit
withdrawals to 20,000 australs, or about $100, every two days.
   Begining Friday, the Central Bank will issue 5,000-austral
notes. In June 1985 when the austral was introduced, each was worth
about $1.20. Today, each is worth less than one cent.
   La Semana magazine taped an austral to each cover of its current
edition, the lead story of which was entitled, ``The Death of the
Austral.''
</TEXT>
