<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-USTrade     05-25 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Criticizes U.S. For Targeting Japanese Trade Barriers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Violators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan lashed out at the United States Friday for
targeting Japanese trade barriers under a U.S. trade law that could
lead to stiff tariffs on Japanese exports to its biggest market.
   Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno called the action ``extremely
regrettable.''
   He said it was unfair ``because the United States has
unilaterally made such a decision on the trade practices of other
countries including Japan, despite the fact that the U.S. itself
maintains import restrictive measures and practices to a
considerable degree.''
   The Foreign Minister urged the United States to reduce its
``huge budget deficit.'' He said the so-called ``Super 301'' list
of unfair trade practices was an attempt to ``divert attention from
the major cause of the trade imbalance'' between the two countries
and to deny U.S. responsibility for faltering economic policies.
   ``As a result of many market-opening measures which have been
taken to date, the Japanese market has now become a widely open
market,'' Uno said. ``None of the identified `priority practices'
can be considered to constitute trade barriers.''
   The Bush administration announced Thursday it had named trade
barriers in Japan, Brazil and India under its massive trade law
enacted last year. U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said the
administration will immediately begin negotiations with the three
countries to try to get the barriers removed so that any threatened
U.S. trade sanctions would be unnecessary.
   If the talks are unsuccessful, the U.S. government can levy
tariffs of up to 100 percent against selected imports from an
offending country.
   Mrs. Hills, who made the announcement in Washington, cited Japan
for refusal to buy American-made satellites and supercomputers as
well as its barriers on U.S. lumber products.
   ``This framework, by which the United States forces us to
negotiate by selfishly imposing sanctions, violates the fundamental
idea'' of multilateral trade negotitions under the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or GATT, said Hiroshi Mitsuzuka,
Japan's minister of international trade and industry.
   ``We will raise this issue at mutinational meetings,'' Mitsuzuka
added.
   ``Our government is ready to talk about (the matter) at
international levels including GATT. But we would not consider any
U.S.-Japanese bilateral negotiations in the framework of Super
301,'' said Mitsuzuka.
   Foreign Minister Uno said Japan would prefer to solve trade
problems between the two nations ``through quiet talks and joint
cooperation with the United States.''
   In Washington, outgoing Japanese Ambassador to the United States
Nobuo Matsunaga said his government would strongly oppose any
future sanctions.
   ``In light of the good faith efforts that have been made, the
government of Japan and the Japanese people are greatly
disappointed by this one-sided decision,'' Matsunaga said in a
statement. ``There may well be some domestic backlash in Japan
which will make the resolution of the various problems even more
difficult.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
