<FIRST>u a AM-LATeachers 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 05-25 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0748,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Teachers Approve 3-Year Contract</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from board members;
picks up 5th graf, `Things in ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking teachers Thursday approved by
acclamation a contract with a 24 percent pay raise over three years
and more authority for instructors whose walkout crippled education
for a half-million students.
   Teachers will return to the classroom Friday after an 11-day
strike in the nation's second-largest school district.
   ``Our children will have their teachers back,'' Board of
Education member Julie Korenstein said after the board approved the
pact in a 4{-hour close-door meeting.
   ``It's done as far as we're concerned,'' said board member
Warren Furutani.
   The tally of the board's vote was not known, and an official,
public vote was scheduled on June 19. But board member Rita Walters
criticized the contract, and refused to stand with her six
colleagues at a news conference.
   She said the $600 million salary plan for teachers would drain
the budget in other areas. The union has disputed that any cuts
would be needed.
   Teachers union President Wayne Johnson characterized the
settlement as historic.
   ``Things in the Los Angeles Unified School District, as far as
teachers are concerned, have changed for all time,'' a jubilant
Johnson declared minutes before the voice vote by teachers in the
Sports Arena.
   Union members who filled the arena on the strike's 11th day
still had to fill out ballots to satisfy bylaws. But it was
apparent during an hour-long meeting that virtually all points of
the contract, including yearly 8 percent wage increases, were
enthusiastically accepted.
   The board of directors of United Teachers-Los Angeles had voted
to make no recommendation to the rank-and-file on the agreement,
reached early Thursday morning after a 16-month labor dispute in
the nation's second largest school district.
   ``I hope this signals a new era of working together, of
cooperation, rather than confrontation,'' said school board
President Roberta Weintraub.
   Johnson expects the strike to leave no hard feelings between the
union and district, but said a rift would remain between striking
teachers and those who crossed picket lines.
   Teachers had been earning $23,440 to $43,319 a year, depending
on experience and level of education. The new pact raises those
salaries in the first year of the contract to $25,316 and $46,594
and at the end of three years to $29,529 and $53,938 respectively.
   Teachers, whose contract expired in July 1988, will receive a
retroactive pay raise for the first year of the new contract.
   The agreement also provides teachers a greater say in management
by creating councils at each school with half the members from the
teachers' ranks and the other half made up of administrators, other
staff and parents. The district would no longer have veto power on
curriculum decisions.
   The union made several compromises, including agreeing that
teachers work some hours to recover pay docked when they wouldn't
hand in grade reports or perform such duties as yard patrol in
protest actions preceding the walkout.
   Johnson estimated high school teachers were docked, on average,
$1,000 each, and elementary teachers lost up to $700 each.
   Education in the district had slowed to a crawl since the union
representing 22,000 of the district's 32,000 teachers, counselors
and librarians went on strike May 15.
   About half the district's 594,000 students stayed away from
school, going instead to the beach, shopping malls or home. Many of
the students who did attend school encountered more games, cartoons
and film strips than lessons.
   The impasse broke Tuesday after officials on both sides met
privately in Sacramento with state legislators to discuss the
issues and how the district might receive part of a recently
announced $2.5 billion state surplus. Negotiators said the
legislators prodded them to resume talks.
</TEXT>
