<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   05-25 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, May 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Origins of Entrepreneurs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The origin of entrepreneurship _ the
overwhelming desire to create an original, inventive course in life
no matter what the risks _ seems to become mistier rather than
clearer with each new study.
   Among claims is that the seed can be found in economic or
psychological deprivation, in a newspaper route, in a rural
environment, in a youngster's age relative to siblings, in having
had a mentor, in having moved while a child.
   Most claims can be made to sound reasonable. Deprivation may
spur ambition. Newspaper routes teach self-reliance. Rural
economies offer an understandable microcosm of larger economies.
Mentors show the way. Moving arouses curiosity.
   Perhaps there is some truth in such assertions, and at least a
bit also in some of the other claims, legends and myths that
surround the subject. Neither can you dismiss the role of venture
capitalists, who supply the wherewithal.
   Seldom, however, are teachers given much credit, but of late
there is no denying their role. From grammar school to graduate
school, individual teachers _ entrepreneurs themselves _ have
accepted the assignment of showing the way.
   In many instances, the spur to these teacher-entrepreneurs has
been the very failure of the educational system to tackle the job.
Even now, youngsters may go through school without ever considering
the self-employment option.
   At the University of North Carolina at Charlotte, Professor
Irvin B. Tucker III faced the problem by investing his own money to
establish Tucker Press in 1987. His purpose was to produce a high
quality economics textbook.
   Keeping costs to a minimum, he published ``Economics For Young
Americans,'' along with a teacher's guide. The State of North
Carolina adopted the text last year for a five-year period. The
book has sold thousands of copies.
   For his work, Tucker received a $15,000 award from the Freedoms
Foundation, Valley Forge, Pa., a non-profit, non-sectarian,
non-political organization that seeks to foster an understanding of
American freedoms and opportunities.
   For 12 years the foundation has honored educators who seek to
teach the rewards and risks of the free enterprise system, of which
entrepreneurship is one of the most dramatic expressions.
   Among those honored this year were Sister Mary Adelaine of Notre
Dame Academy, Los Angeles, who structured a course on ``Wall
Street-Main Street,'' and Terry Applebaum of Northwestern
University, who seeks to develop among artists an appreciation of
business, the better to pursue their careers.
   Steve Mariotti was discovered teaching in New York's Jane Addams
Vocational High School. His course, ``South Bronx Entrepreneurial
Education Program'' encouraged several black and Hispanice students
to found businesses.
   Gay Burden Ferguson, economics teacher at McLean County High
School in rural Calhoun, Kentucky, was honored for putting her
class to work developing and producing a marketing video and
brochure to lure businesses into the area.
   Entrepreneurs, teachers included, aren't the kind who easily
turn down money. But one thing is known for sure about this breed:
their primary motive isn't cash but the development and fulfillment
of ideas.
   Twenty-one teachers in all were honored with cash gifts, but the
big payoff may come later.
   That payoff would be if they helped produce a Sam Walton, as in
Wal-Mart Stores, a Steve Jobs, as in Apple Computer, an An Wang, as
in Wang Labs, or a Fred Smith, as in Federal Express.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, May 26.</NOTE>
</DOC>
