<FIRST>a i AM-Pope-Scandinavia Adv31   05-25 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Scandinavia, Adv 31,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs May 31 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope May Find Scandinavia Alien Territory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note pope's trip begins June 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II is coming to
Scandinavia where Roman Catholicism, vanquished by the Protestant
Reformation, was proscribed for more than 300 years until a century
ago.
   The pope will spend 10 days in Norway, Iceland, Finland, Denmark
and Sweden, starting June 1.
   Overwhelmingly secular and affluent, Scandinavians, especially
the young, show little patience with traditional moral standards.
   Attitudes toward sex are liberal and marriage is optional. In
Sweden, for example, the statistics bureau said last year that some
50 percent of all couples living together don't bother to exchange
vows. The figure is higher in Iceland.
   Couples who register as cohabitants have virtually the same
legal rights as do man and wife.
   In Sweden and Denmark, homosexual couples have equal rights.
   Birth control is encouraged. Abortions occur at a rate of about
20 per 1,000 women, while slightly lower in Finland. An abortion is
available without questions to any woman above the age of consent
up to the 12th week of pregnancy.
   In the era of AIDS, condoms are distributed in many schools and
advertised on billboards.
   ``We are in a helpless situation,'' said Ake Goransson, director
of studies for the Roman Catholic diocese in Sweden.
   ``We have many Catholics who don't marry, not because they are
afraid they won't be able to divorce, but because marriage is just
not common in Sweden.''
   Swedish Catholics, a community of 135,000, had only 260
marriages last year.
   The Scandinavian dioceses run education classes, usually on
Saturdays, to teach the Vatican's position on such questions as the
sanctity of marriage and the purpose of sex.
   ``We have a broad program of Christian education for our kids so
they can make their own decisions,'' said Goransson. ``The church
doesn't want to tell Catholics what to do. You must follow your own
conscience, but your conscience must be taught.''
   The pope was expected to speak on issues of man's faithfulness
to God and to each other, and parental responsibility, said
Goransson.
   To one degree or another, the Lutheran Church is an arm of the
state in all five countries. About 90 percent of the populations
belong to the official tax-supported churches.
   Membership in the state church is automatic for anyone born of
Lutheran parents. Clergymen are civil servants paid by the state,
and bishops are appointed by government.
   But religion plays little role.
   In Sweden, about 10 percent say they are regular churchgoers. In
Norway, cities are virtually shut down for the Easter holiday while
Norwegians go skiing.
   Some say Christianity never really took root when it came to the
Viking cultures 1,000 years ago.
   The Benedictine monk Ansgar brought Christianity to Denmark and
Sweden in the 9th century, but it took two centuries to spread
throughout Scandinavia.
   Danish chroniclers say a monk called Poppo convinced King Harald
Bluetooth of Christianity's power by carrying a red-hot iron in his
hands in the year 960.
   The Roman church came to Finland by way of an English-led
crusade in 1155. It vied with the Orthodox Church from Russia,
which still has a strong foothold.
   The 16th-century Protestant Reformation was the tool for the
Scandinavian kings to seize church property and the wealth of what
had become a powerful force. In Sweden, the church owned one-fifth
of all farms.
   For one brief period in Denmark, being Catholic was a capital
offense.
   Freedom of religion was restored throughout the region in the
19th century, and today Catholics are a small but growing minority.
   A liberal policy toward refugees in Sweden, Norway and Denmark
has brought Catholics, mostly from Chile in the last several years.
Thousands also came from Poland after the labor unrest that began
in 1980. In the 1950s others came from Hungary and elsewhere in
eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed AMs May 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-LanguageBoom Adv29   05-25 1107</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Language Boom, Adv 29,1145</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, May 29, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Under Economic Gun, U.S. High Schoolers Are Thinking Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HIRSH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not far from the corporate towers of Manhattan,
where an older generation jostles daily with foreign competitors,
Michael Rubin's high school students are itching to get into the
game.
   These teen-agers aren't thinking softball at the local park in
Queens. They want to play economic hardball. So they're doing what
comes naturally in the business-minded 1980s _ they're studying
Japanese.
   Throughout the United States, the study of Japanese and other
so-called ``exotic'' languages such as Chinese and Russian, once
the preserve of colleges, is booming in high schools, junior high
schools and even on the elementary level, educators say.
   As global economic forces shift from what was once blithely
called the ``American Century'' toward what some have dubbed the
``Pacific Century,'' American youth are going with the flow,
delighted educators say.
   ``I took (Japanese) because I see Japan as the next Pacific
power,'' said Alwin Eversley, a bony, bespectacled 15-year-old who
makes it plain he respects economic muscle. Like many students in
Rubin's class at Townsend Harris High School, Alwin plans to be a
business major in college.
   ``A lot of businessmen in America, they don't speak the language
of Japan well,'' he said. ``And so the Japanese are not influenced
by them that much. They look down upon them a little.''
   While new interest in Russian and Chinese has been spurred by
liberalization in the Soviet Union and China's rapid social
changes, and Arabic is on the rise, the biggest surge in high
school language study has been in Japanese, said C. Edward Scebold,
executive director of the American Council on the Teaching of
Foreign Languages.
   Educators say years of media lamentation over the
uncompetitiveness of U.S. industry marked not only businessmen, but
also a business-oriented younger generation.
   ``Every time a student turns around, there's either a Japanese
product or an article in the paper about Japan. It's like a
built-in P.R. program,'' said Fred Lorish, a teacher of Japanese at
South Eugene High School in Oregon.
   In a high school in Battle Creek, Mich., officials were
astonished when they offered a Japanese class in the only slot
available _ 7 a.m. _ and 28 students showed up. In Bloomington,
Ill., Japanese studies blossomed after Japan's Mitsubishi and
Chrysler Motors jointly opened a plant last October. In New York
state, junior high schools will be authorized to offer Japanese for
the first time next fall.
   California, Oregon and Washington now proudly consider
themselves the eastern bulwark of the bustling Pacific Rim and have
embraced Japanese business and culture.
   ``I don't want to sound corny and say the future's in the
Pacific Rim, but it's true,'' said Tanya Renee Hamlin, a
15-year-old freshman at Franklin High School in Seattle.
   Oregon, which had an early taste of Japanese power when its
coastline was bombed by Imperial Navy submarines in World War II,
has sponsored a virtual invasion since 1980. The state has gone
from one high school with 15 students of Japanese to 26 schools
with nearly 1,700 students this year.
   In 1988, Oregon began the nation's first full-time grade 1-6
immersion program in Japanese, in which students are taught
subjects half the day in English and half in Japanese, said David
Arlington of the state Department of Education.
   ``There's definitely a correlation between the rise of the yen
and the rise in interest in Japanese,'' said Rubin, 44, a New
Yorker who lived in Japan for five years and studied at Keio
University. ``I think money talks.''
   The National Governors Association concluded as much when its
task force on international education issued a critical report this
year.
   ``The international frontier is no longer the future _ a new age
has arrived,'' said the task force's chairman, Virginia Gov. Gerald
L. Baliles.
   ``International education, teaching and learning about other
countries, their citizens, and their languages _ just how important
is it to our country? As important as economic prosperity, national
security, and world stability,'' the task force report said.
   But old habits die hard. Only one in five American high school
graduates takes more than two years of any foreign language,
according to a 1987 Department of Education study. Not one state
requires a foreign language for a high school diploma.
   Probably fewer than 500 Americans can speak Japanese fluently
today, said Seiichi Makino, a visiting professor of Japanese at
Harvard University. By contrast, Japanese children begin studying
English intensively in junior high school.
   With the exception of the West Coast states and Hawaii, most of
the high school Japanese programs have started in the last seven
years. About 270 high schools in 35 states offer Japanese, a jump
of 50 percent from just two years ago, according to the Center for
Improvement of Teaching of Japanese Language in High School, based
in Urbana, Ill.
   ``I think communities around the country are beginning to see
there's a real economic advantage to communicating in Japanese.
They want to attract Japanese businesses,'' said Carol Bond,
director of the center.
   But more powerful forces than mere economics are at work,
teachers say. U.S. preeminence has ebbed, and Japan has eclipsed
the United States as the world's largest creditor and supplier of
foreign aid.
   ``My sense of the kids I teach is that there is a real, almost
subconscious desire to be international, to be part of it,''
Lorish, the 45-year-old Oregon teacher, said. ``What I didn't have
in the '50s is the sense that my language is a passport to the
world. These kids have it.''
   There are problems, of course. Like any new demand, the language
boom has outstripped supply _ in this case that of qualified
teachers and adequate textbooks, teachers say. Few states offer
certification in Japanese.
   ``We get the same message from teachers over and over again.
They don't know if they're doing things right,'' Bond said.
   Because of the difficulty of the language, there is also a high
dropout rate, teachers say. According to the State Department's
Foreign Service Institute, it takes 1,320 hours of Japanese study
to reach the same level of speech attained in 240 hours of Spanish
or even Vietnamese.
   Interest in foreign languages has been cyclical in the past, but
Scebold of the foreign language council believes the latest upswing
may be more permanent.
   ``There is a realization in the minds of citizens that we've got
to push kids into these programs. ... God knows, those languages
open a million doors.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-IowaDrought Adv28   05-25 1052</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Iowa Drought, Adv 28,1086</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Deceptive Green as Wells Dry Up and Ponds Shrink in Iowa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note 6th graf time element, Yeutter visit Tuesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT AYR, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Randy Bishop home in the heart of
south central Iowa's parched cattle country, the well has been dry
since September and hauling water has become routine.
   So has wearing clothes longer between washings for Bishop, his
wife, Christine, and three young children, turning off the shower
between lathering up and rinsing and leaving to Mommy the decision
on when to flush the toilet.
   Farming is now even more of a gamble in the stunted pastures
nestled amid roller-coaster hills along the Iowa-Missouri border,
where rainfall has been less than 50 percent of normal since
January 1988.
   There were a few generous showers in May, allowing newly planted
corn and soybeans to sprout, raising spirits and turning pastures
green. Farmers now say that with a few more timely rains, they may
have enough moisture to raise corn stalks tall enough to chop up
for silage to sustain their cattle, even if there's not enough rain
for the crop to mature and be harvested.
   ``I'm not sure we can catch up in one year and get back to even
halfway normal,'' says Bishop as his pickup truck bumps across a
pasture seven miles south of Mount Ayr. G I mow it, there's
nothing to rake up.''
   Normally, the Memorial Day Weekend is when farmers begin to
harvest the first of several cuttings of the hay crop.
   ``I don't know when it's going to be this year,'' Smith says.
   Smith, 65, remembers his father surviving the Dust Bowl years of
the 1930s without electricity and air conditioning.
   ``It seemed hotter in the '30s. But it certainly didn't last as
long,'' he says.
   Average rainfall in Iowa from May 1988 through the end of April
1989 is 22.08 inches, 10 inches below normal and nine inches less
than the same period a year earlier that led up to the Drought of
1988.
   At Blockton, total rain from Jan. 1, 1988, through the end of
April came to 16.86 inches, just 40 percent of the normal 41.91
inches for that 16-month period and the lowest of 162 official
measuring sites in the state.
   Blockton Mayor Richard Melvin had to scramble up to the roof of
his plumbing supply business to make repairs after a recent rain.
``We didn't have enough rain to go through the cracks before
then,'' he said.
   The National Guard has been hauling water for household use to
one southeast Iowa community and eight in south central Iowa since
May 8. Four of those cities are around Blockton.
   Although Blockton's municipal well is deep enough to ensure
water supplies to the community's 120 households, most surrounding
farms are in trouble and some farmers are traveling almost 80 miles
roundtrip to haul water.
   ``Last year the wells went dry, but we had ponds. Now the ponds
are going dry,'' Melvin said.
   In Corning, where water shortages following droughts in the
mid-1970s led to the development of ample water supplies, water
sales to individuals are up sharply.
   The municipal water works has a coin-operated machine that
dispenses 50 gallons of water for 25 cents. Sales, which totaled
about 25,000 gallons in all of January 1988, ran above 535,000
gallons this month, says Dean Davis, director of the municipal
utility. About three-fourths of those sales are for household use,
and farmers also have been buying water for mixing with chemicals
to control insects and weeds.
   When there is rain, it immediately is soaked up in the loose top
inches of the soil, never reaching deep enough to be stored for the
rest of the growing season or to flow into depleted farm ponds and
rivers.
   Davis, checking on the installation of new street lights, said
6-foot deep holes revealed bone-dry earth below a narrow band of
moist topsoil.
   That is a major worry.
   Subsoil moisture is deemed 100 percent inadequate throughout
south central Iowa.
   In last year's drought, it was ample subsoil moisture at the
start of the planting season that enabled many farmers to avoid
being wiped out.
   ``The lack of water is more scary than the lack of feed,'' Smith
says. ``Everyone's trying to hang on. But everybody I talk to says,
`When I run out of water I'm getting rid of them (cattle).'''
   So far, there's been no rush to liquidate breeding herds.
   But at the rural Corning farm of Ralph Neill, productivity
records on each cow are being reviewed to decide which ones to send
to the slaughterhouse if feed becomes scarce.
   The 51-year-old farmer, whose family has been working the remote
fields since 1875, says he knows such action is risky.
   ``If I don't save replacement heifers, every year the average
age of the cows gets one year older and you get in a perilous
situation,'' he says.
   He used to wait for a truckload of cattle before making the trip
to market to sell the weakest stock from his herd, but this day, he
was preparing to sell four cows that had lost calves.
   With feed scarce, there's no excuse for keeping marginal stock
on hand, he says.
   Cattlemen in the drought area say the May rains have been enough
to keep them going another 30-45 days even if no more rain falls.
   But many veterans say they've made their cutbacks early.
   Bill Henderson, a fifth-generation farmer near Clearfield who
says nine of his 14 ponds have run dry, reduced his herd by 25
percent a year ago.
   ``You make contingency plans way in advance,'' says Henderson.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, May 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
