<DOCNO> AP890525-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-China-ThreeFaces Adv28-2Takes   05-25 1209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Three Faces, Adv 28-2 Takes,1234</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>China's Struggles Seen in Three Faces</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Once you have seen the sky, you cannot go back into the well.''
   Spoken with the simple eloquence of an old sage, the words were
uttered by a 23-year-old Chinese woman yearning for freedom in her
homeland.
   Lee was our guide, one of three on a visit to China. My husband
and I went with the idea that we would find a lock-step society
cautious about change. We found, among the educated middle-class
Chinese we met, an intense desire for reform, a hunger to learn
everything about Western culture and society, a disillusionment
bordering on contempt for the old guard running the nation, and a
fierce determination to better their lives through individual
initiative.
   Now, like millions of others around the globe, we're glued to
the televised images of turmoil in Tiananmen Square and along the
Bund in Shanghai.
   Of all of the faces that we saw in February, of all the faces of
hunger strikers and peasants and workers and intellectuals
dominating the television screen and the front page today, three
remain distinct in our memories: Lee in Kunming, Charlie in Xian,
and Louie in Guilin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Lee is a lovely young woman, daughter of factory workers,
youngest of four children, a former college teacher who is
determined to have her own travel business one day. She lives in a
single room and eats cafeteria-style with other employees of the
travel office where she is the beginner.
   She dresses in Western-style clothes, simple and inexpensive,
and likes bright colors. Every day for five days she wore her red
shoes. When we asked her to forget the regular tour and take us to
the places she liked, she took us to the city park to watch old men
play card games in the sun, children chase ducks, lovers canoe on
the lake. We strolled the formal camellia gardens as we tried to
explain mortgages and credit.
   We sat at a restaurant table for hours as she demanded to know
everything about the U.S. Senate. She quoted Jefferson and was
curious about FDR and the New Deal. What was John F. Kennedy really
like? She asked us to recite the preamble to the Constitution and
made us feel ashamed when we stumbled through it.
   One starry night she guided us from tiny, cold-water apartments
to tinier, no-water apartments on the campus of the local art
institute and music conservatory.
   In one artist's garret we heard him extol, through Lee's
interpreting, the wonders of Tibet, the trouble it takes to put on
a modern art exhibit under the watchful eyes of the Chinese
authorities and the thrill of exchanging views with an artist, my
husband, from America.
   As we left after tea and heady conversation, he pressed on the
American painter a luminous watercolor of the Himalayas, saying:
``I was starving and hallucinating when I painted that picture. I
had no food and no money and I was stranded in Tibet. I want you to
have this to remember me by.'' As if anyone could forget him.
   In another concrete apartment, lit with a glaring overhead bulb,
we sat transfixed as a 14-year-old prodigy played Mozart on a
Chinese piano under the gaze of a plaster Beethoven bust. The boy
was recuperating at home because, while studying in Beijing, he'd
become malnurished and contracted pneumonia in his poorly heated
dormitory. His concentration, his technique, his passion at the
keyboard transcended language and hemispheres. We burst out in
applause and ``Bravo! Bravo!'' as he humbly bowed his head and
apologized for ``my inadequacy to play this master.''
   We left Lee on the tarmac as she prepared for her yearly exams
``which qualify me to escort our honored foreign visitors.'' She
haughtily refused a tip but was giddy as a schoolgirl with the few
humorous stickers and lapel pins we pressed on her.
   ``Please send me postcards, and pictures of your town,'' she
said shyly. ``And a book you think will get past the censors.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Charlie's 32 and hip. He wears Reeboks and has a VCR. But he
lives in a one-room unheated apartment in a city where it snows a
lot. He said he opted not to have a heater in his home because he'd
rather spend his precious income on ``other things _ books, tapes,
movies, traveling.'' Besides, grinned the newlywed, ``I've got my
love to keep me warm.'' His wife works in a factory office. They
say they will have to wait several years before they can afford a
baby. Currently they are saving for new bicycles.
   Charlie dreams of going to the United States, of seeing Madonna
in concert, of learning about the hotel business in California and
returning to China to make money as an innkeeper. ``Tourism is our
future. Everybody will want to come to see China as we open up.''
He says he's lucky, because he's traveled inside China and now
knows how beautiful other parts of his country are.
   The day he took us to see the 2,000-year-old terra cotta army
the three of us stood alone and stared together at one of the
wonders of the world. Charlie urged us to study an ancient clay
face, to imagine what the man who posed for the statue was like,
how he lived, what he thought. He forced us to contemplate our own
link with Emperor Qin Shi Huang, the first person ever to unite
China, in 221 B.C.
   Then we turned to stare into Charlie's face, and we saw the past
in the present.
   And we all decided it was too cold to stand around watching our
breath freeze. So we retired to the coffee shop at the new Holiday
Inn and talked politics, economics and art. Charlie asked us if
California was as wonderful as he'd heard, and we hedged our
answers about smog and gridlock as we waxed poetic about orange
blossoms and Hollywood.
   Revived by strong coffee and frank talk, we then moved downtown
to a main street, through an unmarked lobby, up three flights of
unlighted stairs and into a smoke-filled room ablaze in flashing
red spotlights. There, to the music of the Miami Sound Machine
blasting from an ancient stereo system, we watched a Western-style
fashion show as pencil-thin models paraded down a runway lined by
serious, unsmiling men and women in Mao jackets puffing on strong
cigarettes. The clothes were terrific, the setting straight out of
Fellini.
   When we left town we gave him a baseball cap and promised to
somehow send a few Michael Jackson tapes. Our last memory was of
him waving, somewhat forlornly, as we passed stern-eyed customs
agents.
   ``Try to help me go to America,'' he called, ``and don't forget
to write.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Louie is the dreamer who asks ``Why not?'' A former university
professor who gave up teaching eager minds because he couldn't feed
his family on the wages, he now guides tourists ``for my work and
also for fun.''
   Introverted, an intellectual, he comes from a family that
suffered greatly in the Cultural Revolution of the 1960s and '70s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
