<DOCNO> AP890525-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-China-ThreeFaces Adv28-1stAdd   05-25 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Three Faces, Adv 28-1st Add,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: and '70s.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Red Guards rampaged through his city, as they did nearly
everywhere in China, and his parents were sent from the university
to the countryside to be ``re-educated.'' Just as China's last
emperor, Pu Yi, was forced to wear a dunce cap and parade through
the streets in shame, so was Louie's father. It is a bitter memory.
   ``That is where the students jumped to their deaths,'' he said,
pointing down from a rocky promontory into a small, manmade lake on
a college campus. ``They refused to surrender to the madness, so
they killed themselves.''
   In much of Louie's speech there is a hint of melancholy. It is
there as he tells us _ strangers _ that his mother is terrified the
Red Guards will come again, and that he must never share his life
or his secrets with outsiders, he must never trust strangers, he
must never, ever, criticize the authorities.
   But Louie is a 30-year-old husband and father whose family is
victimized by rampant inflation. He knows that in his classless
society there is a privileged elite and a thriving black market. He
knows, from the BBC and the Voice of America, and the stories from
friends who've been to Hong Kong, and his own too brief, bungled
trip to study in Alaska, that a whole new world lies beyond China's
borders.
   ``We cannot go back to bound feet and Mao's caves,'' said Louie.
``I want to earn money, have my own house, be free to travel, raise
my child to go to college. I want better furniture, someday maybe
even a car, an impossible dream now. I want to read more books and
see American movies. I don't want my parents to be afraid of
speaking out. China is changing, we can never go back. Today we
wear a new face.''
   His wife is a teacher who works solely to pay for the food his
infant son needs.
   One of his greatest joys is a Sunday outing when he takes his
wife and child down to the river to see the rock that looks like an
elephant's trunk. There, on a sandy beach, fledgling entrepreneurs
sell ice creams and fruit ices, balloons and toys. Perhaps Louie
will draw a picture, or contemplate one. His wife might recite
poetry to him. His baby will giggle and coo, just as babies
everywhere do.
   ``Send me books by your best writers,'' he said. We asked, ``You
mean Faulkner, Steinbeck, Hemingway?''
   ``I don't know them,'' he replied. ``Just send anything you
like, and I will like it, too.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus, who has reported from Vietnam and
elsewhere in Asia, is now the AP Mountain States regional reporter,
based in Denver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 28</NOTE>
