<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0874</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge has approved
developer Donald Trump's agreement to buy Eastern Airlines' prized
Northeast shuttle for $365 million.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland approved the sale in
principle Wednesday and will hold a hearing on the matter Thursday
at 10 a.m. EDT, said a bankruptcy court clerk, who asked not to be
identified by name.
   Also Wednesday, America West Airlines withdrew a higher offer
for the shuttle, the clerk said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar resumed its climb against all key
currencies except the British pound and Swiss franc, breaking the
143-yen level overseas and hitting a 1{-year high vs. the Japanese
currency in domestic trading.
   Dealers said trading was volatile here and overseas Wednesday,
with the dollar starting out weak after a mixed performance Tuesday
but ending stronger in the absence of significant central-bank
intervention or signs of policy changes geared toward stabilizing
exchange rates.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government raised interest rates by a
full percentage point, hiking them to a four-year high in a
counterattack against newly resurgent inflation that has been
worsened by a drop in the British pound.
   The Bank of England signaled the change by raising its base
lending rate to 14 percent on Wednesday, and major commercial banks
responded by boosting their prime lending rates one point to that
level.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and truck sales rose a modest 2.7 percent in
mid-May from the same period last year, manufacturers reported, but
analysts noted the sales compared with a year-earlier period that
may have been slower than usual.
   During the May 11-20 period, sales of cars and light trucks made
by the eight major U.S.-based automakers rose to a rate of 39,360 a
day from a pace of 38,334 during the same period last year, the car
makers said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Import restraints have slowed the influx of
foreign steel, but the illegal trading practices that made trade
protection necessary 4{ years ago are as prevalent as ever,
American steelmakers said.
   ``We are prepared to file cases against virtually all our
trading partners'' unless steel import limits are extended under
the five-year Voluntary Restraint Agreements, Bethlehem Steel Corp.
chairman Walter F. Williams told reporters Wednesday at the annual
meeting of the American Iron and Steel Institute.
   President Bush is expected to fulfill a campaign promise to
extend quotas past their Sept. 30 expiration. But steel executives
are concerned he may weaken the restraints.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fuel-economy standard for 1989 passenger
cars will remain at 26.5 miles per gallon, the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration said in rejecting a petition for
reconsideration of the regulation.
   The petition filed by two Washington-based advocacy groups, the
Center for Auto Safety and Public Citizen, asked NHTSA to allow the
corporate average fuel economy standard to revert to 27.5 mpg, the
level set by a 1975 law intended to reduce dependence on foreign
oil.
   The advocacy groups failed to make a case that ``the standard
should have been set at a level other than 26.5 mpg,'' NHTSA's
order said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee approved a bill giving
the federal government authority to determine damages to be paid by
oil companies after spills.
   The measure approved by the House Merchant Marine and Fisheries
Coast Guard subcommittee Wednesday bars states from enacting
stricter damage laws than the federal standard. The issue of state
versus federal standard has been the chief hurdle over the past 13
years blocking legislation to simplify existing oil spill laws.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Judiciary Committee narrowly
defeated a Republican attempt to blunt the key capital reform in
President Bush's savings and loan bailout.
   The amendment, which failed on a 17-17 vote Wednesday, would
have allowed some institutions to use administrative appeals to
delay the imposition of tougher capital standards for up to a year
and half.
   That vote was the latest in a series by both the Judiciary panel
and House Banking Committee in which Bush has attracted more
Democratic than Republican support for preserving his proposed
reforms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 36 cents of every dollar of Americans'
income goes for taxes, with the nation's poorest and wealthiest
families paying considerably more than average, the Tax Foundation
reported.
   In 1986, households under $10,000 gave just about half their
incomes _ 49.5 percent _ to federal, state and local governments.
Those with incomes of $90,000 and more paid an average 51.6
percent, the foundation said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market shook off an early slump and closed higher
Wednesday in a generally quiet session. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials closed up 5.86 points at 2,483.87.
   The dollar advanced against all major currencies except the
British pound.
   Bond prices edged lower on technical factors.
   Energy futures prices climbed; grain and soybean prices drifted
lower, precious metals finished mixed, and livestock and pork
prices plunged.
</TEXT>
