<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RobinsWait     05-25 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robins Wait,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delay in Robins Plan Confirmation Frustrates Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dwindling number of women injured by A.H.
Robins Co.'s Dalkon Shield birth control device still hope to bear
children if they can get reconstructive surgery, the leader of a
victims' rights group says.
   But they are frustrated waiting for court approval of Robins'
bankruptcy reorganization that has delayed distribution of money
for surgery, said Linda Hightower, director of the Dalkon Shield
Victims Association.
   ``Every day we delay is another day that the women who have even
the smallest chance of having a child lose that chance,'' she said
Wednesday. ``A lot of women are losing heart.''
   Robins pulled the Dalkon Shield from the market 15 years ago but
resolution of claims has dragged on.
   A reorganization plan including a $2.5 billion trust fund for
Dalkon Shield claimants was approved in July 1988 by judges in U.S.
District Court and U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   The plan called for Richmond-based Robins to be acquired by
American Home Products Corp. of New York in a $700 million exchange
of stock with full payment of creditors.
   During the appelate process, $100 million of the $2.5 billion
trust fund has been available to compensate women with minor Dalkon
Shield injuries or poorly documented claims. The bulk of the fund
awaits final confirmation of the reorganization plan.
   An appeal of the plan was heard on an expedited basis by the 4th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last December but no decision has
been handed down.
   ``We're sitting on pins and needles expecting it at any
moment,'' said Guerry Thornton Jr., attorney for the Atlanta-based
victims' association.
   Thornton and other lawyers involved in the case said they had
expected a ruling earlier because of the delays and because
American Home can withdraw from the plan if it is not finalized by
July 26, one year after its initial confirmation.
   Robins spokesman Roscoe Puckett said American Home officials
have given no indication they plan to exercise their option to back
out of the deal.
   ``I have to believe in my judicial system and believe they're
trying to do the right thing,'' Ms. Hightower said. ``I hope the
justices realize how important it is.''
   Robins' filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in August
1985 came 11 years after it pulled the Dalkon Shield birth control
device off the market. About 4.5 million of the intrauterine
devices had been distributed in the United States and abroad.
   At the time of the Chapter 11 filing, Robins had paid about $520
million to settle more than 9,000 damage lawsuits, and faced
thousands more from women who said they suffered injuries including
infections, sterility, miscarriages and children with birth defects
because of their use of the Dalkon Shield.
   About 94 percent of the 200,000 women with injury claims against
Robins voted in favor of the reorganization plan, but lawyers for
the appealing claimants challenged the way the vote was taken and
the amount of the trust fund.
   The fact most of the claimants voted in favor of the plan
increases frustration over the appeal's delay, said Stanley K.
Joynes III, a Richmond lawyer appointed to represent future Dalkon
Shield claimants.
   ``There's a fair amount of resentment that the appeal was even
filed, that a handful of people are holding this up,'' he said.
   Lawyers representing claimants said millions of dollars in
potential interest are being lost because the trust fund money will
not be deposited until appeals to the plan are exhausted.
   ``If the trust had the money today and invested it at current
rates, it would be earning $800,000 a day,'' Joynes said. ``That's
the real loss. That's what the appeal is costing the Dalkon Shield
claimants, and the court's aware of that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BrandRomancing     05-25 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brand Romancing,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Book: Advertising Needs Sales As Well As Entertainment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It takes a memorable advertisement to grab
the attention of the average American, who sees about 80 television
commercials nightly.
   But even the funniest, most creative, entertaining ad isn't any
good if it doesn't sell the product, says the man who headed a
campaign that made people nationwide think that ``Virginia Is for
Lovers.'
   David N. Martin, chairman of a Richmond ad agency and author of
``Romancing the Brand,'' says the sales pitch is absent from
today's increasingly entertaining advertising.
   ``In the last four or five years there has been a return among
advertising agencies to really high creative _ very witty, very
charming and very entertaining ads,'' Martin, whose book has a
publication date today, said in an interview this week.
   But too many advertisers try to imitate commercials run by
market leaders, he said.
   The makers of Pepsi and Levis jeans can barely mention their
products in ads because their name recognition is so high. But
other companies mistakenly believe awareness is sufficient and they
don't tell consumers why to buy their products.
   ``They try to overwhelm the consumer strictly through
entertainment,'' Martin said. ``It doesn't work with a low share.
There are ways to be wonderfully witty, wonderfully entertaining
and not lose sight of the product.''
   Cable television, videocassette records and television remote
controls have increased viewing options and made competition for
consumers' attention increasingly fierce, he said.
   Escalating television and print advertising costs mean companies
can't run as many ads, putting a premium on getting viewer or
reader attention with a dramatic advertisement.
   Finally, advertising artists and writers are creative people who
like their ads to be talked about and to win awards, Martin said.
``Creative people don't put selling as first priority,'' he said.
   Good ads have ``a magical third dimension'' that gets them
talked about and makes them part of common culture, such as the
California Raisins or Wendy's ``Where's the Beef?'' slogan, Martin
said.
   ``Somewhere embedded in the customer's mind is a fact or belief
about every brand that can be converted into a memorable idea by
skilled advertising,'' he said.
   Before co-founding Hawley Martin Partners in Richmond last year
with his brother Steve, Martin was chairman of The Martin Agency,
named one of the nation's ``hottest'' agencies by Advertising Age
and Adweek magazines in 1987.
   Martin said he wrote ``Romancing the Brand'' after hearing
advertising professionals complain about the erosion of the
industry and companies' substitution of promotions and coupons for
advertising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
