<HEAD>Two-Year Notes Yield 8.84 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on two-year Treasury notes fell to the
lowest level since last October.
   The average yield in the government's auction Wednesday was 8.84
percent, down from 9.34 percent at the last auction on April 26.
   It was the lowest rate since two-year notes averaged 8.33
percent on Oct. 26, 1988. The notes will carry a coupon interest
rate of 8} percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for
$9,983.80.
   A total of $8.77 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling
$27.78 billion.
