<FIRST>r f PM-Steel-Construction     05-25 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel-Construction,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Unions Criticized</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Steel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steelmakers have lowered production costs by
routing out featherbedding work rules. Now they would like to see
the same done in the construction trades on which they depend.
   ``The construction industry must begin to eliminate such work
practices as a day for travel time, excessive coffee breaks,
overmanning, a lack of any right to subcontract and rules which
permit workers in one craft to sit idle with pay until those in
another finish their jobs,'' said Thomas C. Graham, chairman of the
American Iron and Steel Institute.
   Some companies that contract for construction services also are
at fault, Graham said Wednesday.
   ``A major offender ... appears to be the public utility
industry, where too often excessive construction costs can merely
be passed along to the consumer,'' Graham said during the
institute's annual meeting.
   Steelmakers have spent an estimated $9 billion on new plants and
equipment since 1982 and they worry about construction costs as
they plan for continued modernization, he said. Steel plants also
require frequent maintenance construction
   Construction costs were nearly uniform around the world 20 years
ago, but U.S. steelmakers today spend up to twice as much as
foreign competitors on the same project, Graham said.
   Steel companies last year negotiated with the AFL-CIO for a 10
percent discount off prevailing labor rates whenever they used the
labor group's members exclusively on construction jobs. But
pipefitters are not honoring the deal in the Chicago area, he
claimed.
   ``The kind of controls on wage rates which we've seen in steel
must begin to be applied in the building trades,'' Graham said.
``Chicago-area pipefitters have received total employment cost
increases since 1982 of 27 percent up to $25 an hour while those in
the steel industry came down over the same period.''
   Average steel industry labor costs, including wages and all
benefits, declined from a record high of $26.90 an hour in November
1982 to $24.50 an hour during the first quarter of 1989.
</TEXT>
