<HEAD>Airline Changing Colors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir is swapping its red and brown logo for a
red, white and blue one.
   USAir will scrape the old paint from all of its 429 jets within
the next two years and replace it with a new logo that includes the
airline's name in red, white and blue on the fuselage. The tail
will be painted blue with USAir in white letters between red
stripes.
   Chairman Edwin Colodny said it will cost $7,000 to paint each
plane.
   ``We all need to refresh ourselves periodically with a new suit
of clothes or a new dress,'' he told reporters and airline workers
Wednesday at Greater Pittsburgh International Airport.
   The present logo was designed in 1975.
