<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Dow-Recycling     05-25 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dow-Recycling,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Chemical Official Critical of National Bottle-Deposit Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Congressman from Michigan defends his
national bottle-deposit bill, described by an industry opponent as
too narrow, as a first step toward more extensive recycling efforts.
   Rep. Paul Henry, R-Mich., said Wednesday that nearly 80 members
of Congress have signed on as co-sponsors of his bill, which would
require all states to collect a deposit on beverage containers. The
bill is modeled after Michigan's bottle-deposit law.
   ``If you put a deposit on a bottle or a can, you'll get that
container back for recycling, but you won't get other materials
back,'' said Karl Kamena, director of governmental and public
affairs for the plastics department of Dow Chemical Co.
   ``I don't think the grocery stores should be in the garbage
business,'' Kamena said. ``I think we can do better by developing
an infrastructure that has curbside pickup, making it much easier
for the consumer.''
   Kamena, also chairman of the Council of Plastics and Packaging
in the Environment, a coalition of Dow and other large
corporations, said obtaining a supply of used containers for
recycling into other products was a top priority but didn't believe
bottle-deposit laws were the best way to meet that end.
   Henry said arguments such as those used by Kamena ``sometimes
are used quite frankly as an attempt to subvert taking that first
step.''
   He said he supported curbside-pickup efforts ``to the extent
that they're honestly motivated rather than attempting to derail
those forms of recycling that have proven effective.''
   Kamena said efforts to reduce solid waste, in part through
improvements in packaging, had resulted between 1970 and 1986 in an
8 percent decline in the number of pounds per capita of containers
and packaging discarded and not recycled.
   Members of the council, ``who make up the key players in the
packaging and plastics industry, feel that given this trend,
increased recycling and incineration of waste materials are far
more promising solutions to our disposal problems than simplistic
laws attacking packaging,'' Kamena said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890525-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PennCentral     05-25 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Penn Central,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Penn Central Scouting for Acquisitions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penn Central Corp., still hunting for a big
acquisition, has enough money to launch a multi-billion-dollar
takeover, says company chairman and Cincinnati financier Carl
Lindner.
   Lindner told shareholders Wednesday that Penn Central has plenty
of cash to finance a major acquisition.
   ``Penn Central continues to have great financial resources,'' he
said. ``We have over $1.8 billion in shareholders' equity.''
   The Cincinnati-based telecommunications and defense firm is 31
percent owned by Lindner's American Financial Corp.
   Lindner clearly spelled out the company's intentions at last
year's annual meeting, but also said at the time that he was in no
hurry to make a deal.
   ``Last year I said there was no sense of urgency to make any
move,'' he said. ``That is still true today.''
   Although shareholders' equity is approaching $2 billion, the
company's debt is only $220 million.
   At the end of 1988, Penn Central had cash, temporary investments
and marketable securities of $1.16 billion.
   The company has $1.3 billion in net operating loss
carryforwards, which are past losses that can offset future income
to reduce taxes. Acquisitions could produce higher earnings and
help maximize the benefits of the carryforwards.
   ``Penn Central is capable of doing a $5 billion or $6 billion
transaction, especially if Henry Kravis (of leveraged buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.) can do a $25 billion RJR Nabisco
deal with only $1 billion,'' said Lindner.
</TEXT>
