<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 0815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AmericaWest     05-25 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-America West,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Says it Gains Even Through Trump Is Getting Eastern's Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America West Airlines ended up withdrawing its
bid for Eastern Airlines' Northwest shuttle, but the Phoenix-based
carrier says it came out ahead nonetheless.
   ``The publicity is worth far more than we expended,'' said Mark
Coleman, an America West vice president. ``We literally could not
buy the positive awareness we've received.''
   A federal bankruptcy judge in New York on Wednesday approved in
principle developer Donald Trump's agreement to buy the shuttle for
$365 million after America West pulled out.
   America West said it withdrew its offer after failing to arrange
financing terms it considered acceptable before a Wednesday
afternoon deadline set by Eastern.
   ``We came very close, but ultimately, the lack of time was the
deciding factor,'' America West President Mike Conway said in a
statement.
   Conway, who has spent the past two weeks in New York working on
the proposed deal, also said the airline was impeded by financing
terms it considered unacceptable.
   America West, which formally announced its plans to bid for the
shuttle on May 3, actually had a pair of offers on the table.
   The company had offered $415 million for the shuttle and $336
million for 10 Boeing 757s. Or, America West would have bought the
shuttle's gates and landing slots at three airports for $375
million but no aircraft.
   Coleman, senior vice president of sales and product development
for America West, said the airline remains interested in buying 10
Boeing 757 jets from Eastern for $336 million.
   Paul Karos, airline analyst with First Boston Corp. in New York,
said America West generated some publicity in the East, where the
airline is not well-known but where it is strengthening service.
   Karos said that although America West is highly leveraged, it
appeared to be in a position to line up financing because of the
profitability of the shuttle operation.
   ``From an America West point of view, it's only a long-term
opportunity cost that is lost,'' he said. ``I thought initially the
shuttle would be dilutive to their earnings, but that in the
long-term it would be a nice return for the company.''
   Coleman said he doesn't believe that America West's failure to
secure financing impairs the airline's reputation.
   ``Quite the contrary, we don't think anybody in the financial
community was not taking us very seriously,'' he said. ``It's not a
question of, `Who are those guys?' We were a serious contender. The
people in the financial community know that.''
   The unsuccessful bid does not affect the airline's plans to
strengthen service to the East Coast with the start-up of flights
by July 1 to New York's LaGuardia and Washington National airports,
Coleman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
