<FIRST>r f PM-BrokerCase     05-25 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Broker Case,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Businessman Awarded $2 Million in Broker Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Atlanta businessman has received a $2 million
award in what officials called one of the largest awards in a
securities arbitration case.
   A three-member arbitration panel of the National Association of
Securities Dealers ruled Monday in favor of Dennis M. Crean, the
same man who was awarded $1.24 million by a federal court jury a
year ago in connection with the same investment program.
   Crean contended he lost more than 41.7 million in four days when
he invested in a complex stock options program in 1984.
   NASD said local stockbroker Thomas W. Alison and his New
York-based employer, PaineWebber Inc. are liable for Crean's losses.
   Crean's lawyer said his client lost all the money he invested
during a stock market rally in August 1984. He filed a lawsuit the
following December.
   Attorney George W. Fryhofer III said Alison advised Crean to
invest in a speculative strategy known as a ``variable hedger''
program.
   Fryhofer said Alison represented the program as ``low- to
moderate-risk'' investment and said Crean could not lose more than
15 percent of his investment.
   A spokeswoman for PaineWebber said Alison and PaineWebber both
declined comment on the case.
   As reported earlier this week, an Atlanta woman was awarded $3.1
million in another securities case.
</TEXT>
