<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Stocks     05-25 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Higher Following Unsurprising Trade Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher at midday Thursday in
quiet trading following the release of British trade figures for
April which were in line with expectations.
   The market climbed to its morning high in the minutes following
the late morning release of the April report, then sagged a bit for
lack of continuing buying interest.
   Traders said the initial buying appeared to have come from
market makers who had been short of stock ahead of the report.
   ``They bought on the chance that there might be some interest
after the figures. But there wasn't,'' said a dealer at a major
London brokerage firm.
   The current account deficit widened to 1.66 billion pounds ($2.6
billion) in April from 1.19 billion pounds ($1.9 billion) in March.
Expectations had been on average for a deficit of about 1.6 billion
pounds ($2.5 billion).
   At about noon in London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 6.1 points, or 0.3 percent, at 2,138.8,
though 3.2 points below its best level reached five minutes after
the trade report. The market had been as much as 6 points below its
Wednesday close near the opening.
   Volume was a modest 278.0 million shares at midday, compared
with 306.9 million shares at the same time Wednesday.
</TEXT>
