<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade     05-25 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain's Trade Deficit Widens to 2.16 Billion Pounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened to
2.16 billion pounds ($3.4 billion) in April, from 1.68 billion
pounds ($2.7 billion) in March, the government said Thursday.
   The Department of Trade and Industry said the current account
deficit widened to 1.66 billion pounds ($2.6 billion) from 1.18
billion pounds ($1.9 billion) a month earlier.
   The current account includes ``invisible trade'' such as
services, overseas investment earnings and official transfer
payments. The government estimates that Britain's invisible trade
was in surplus of 500 million pounds ($790 million) in April.
   The figures nearly matched expectations.
   Since the beginning of 1989, Britain's merchandise trade deficit
came to 8.0 billion pounds ($13 billion), compared with a deficit
of 5.4 million pounds ($8.5 billion) a year earlier.
</TEXT>
