<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales 2ndLd-Writethru f0045 05-25 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0045,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Figures Show Car Market May Be Softening</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to CORRECT spelling of McLean, Va.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A modest 2.7 percent rise in mid-May car and
light truck sales may indicate a softer-than-expected market and
force two of the Big Three automakers to extend incentive programs,
analysts say.
   The eight major automakers assembling vehicles in North America
reported Wednesday they sold cars and light trucks at an average
daily rate of 39,360 from May 11-20 compared with 38,334 in the
same 1988 period.
   Analysts expected an increase, mainly because many incentives
expired May 11 last year. Customers planning to buy cars in mid- or
late-May 1988 made their purchases early to take advantage of the
deals, which reduced sales in the period.
   ``I don't know what it's going to take to bring customers back
to the showrooms,'' said analyst Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors
Service Inc. in New York. ``I think demand is just tired at this
point.''
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co., Chrysler Corp. and some
overseas automakers had wide-ranging incentive plans in effect this
month to lure people into showrooms.
   But demand may not be there, said Tom Webb, a senior economist
with the National Automobile Dealers Association in McLean, Va.
   ``Basically, what sales have shown is that the underlying demand
is less than what most people expected,'' he said. ``Given those
sales, there's going to have to be some further (production) cuts.
They would be modest though.''
   Automakers often trim their inventories through incentives and
production cuts.
   Speculation that Ford and GM need to continue incentives past
their expiration dates during the next two weeks grew with
Wednesday's sales reports. Said Webb: ``There's no doubt about
that.''
   Ford spokesman Bill Carroll said he expected another, more
limited incentive package to be announced May 31, when the
company's current program expires.
   Most of GM's program ends June 5, but on Wednesday, the
corporation's Pontiac Division announced a wider selection of cars
qualifying for cash rebates or low-interest financing. GM also
boosted the cash offer on a few Pontiac cars.
   Chrysler's program continues indefinitely.
   The incentive programs were prompted by slower-than-anticipated
sales during the first three months of the year.
   Since New Year's Day, car and truck sales by the eight makers
were running 3.6 percent behind the pace for 1988, the second-best
year in automotive history. Car sales were running 5.4 percent
behind and truck sales were down 0.3 percent.
   Ford sold cars at an average daily rate of 7,616 during the May
period, compared with 7,410 last year, a 2.8 percent increase. Car
sales so far this year were 0.5 percent behind last year.
   Ford's mid-May truck sales were 6.1 percent higher than last
year and 2.9 percent slower for the full year.
   GM said its cars sold at a daily rate of 11,895 during mid-May
this year, up 2.6 percent from 11,592 last year. GM's year-to-date
car sales were down 9.6 percent. Truck sales in mid-May were up 4.6
percent and down 0.1 percent for the entire year.
   Chrysler said its cars sold in mid-May at a daily rate of 3,378,
0.2 percent ahead of the 3,372-car-per-day rate last year. So far
this year, the No. 3 automaker's car sales were running 15.6
percent behind last year's rate.
   Chrysler truck sales were off 6.4 percent in mid-May but were
0.4 percent ahead of the pace for the full year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
