<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market showed no clear trend today in
a mixed response to the newest data on the state of the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 2.75 to 2,486.62 in
the first half hour of trading.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 438 up, 496
down and 508 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.11 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Commerce Department said the nation's gross national product
grew at a 4.3 percent annual rate, after adjustment for inflation,
in the first quarter of the year, down from a previous estimate of
5.5 percent.
   That initially appeared to be a plus for stocks, by reinforcing
evidence that the economy was slowing in response to the Federal
Reserve's campaign against inflation.
   But analysts noted that the figures got a new interpretation on
close inspection when traders saw that much of the drop stemmed
from a reduction in inventories.
   Tight inventories are more often than not a forerunner of strong
economic activity, since they create a situation where new orders
translate quickly into a need for production.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Philip Morris rose 1 to 138];
Eastman Kodak gained | to 45]; General Electric dropped [ to 53{,
and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was down [ at 35].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.11 to 178.08. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .46 at 351.46.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 5.86 points
to 2,483.87.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a margin of 6 to 5 on
the NYSE, with 768 up, 640 down and 538 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 178.60 million shares, against 187.69
million in Tuesday's session.
