<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-EconomicOutlook 1stLd-Writethru f0021 05-25 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economic Outlook, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0898</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists' See Sharp Slowdown but No Imminent Recession</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 12th graf pvs, That prognosis, to UPDATE
with latest GNP report, reax. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top business economists today predicted that
economic growth will slow dramatically this year but the nation
should be able to forestall a recession until at least 1990.
   The consensus of 54 forecasting experts surveyed by the National
Association of Business Economists was that America will experience
a ``growth recession,'' in which the economy continues to expand
but at a very slow pace.
   The slowdown is expected to be accompanied by a moderate
increase in unemployment and higher inflation due to an emerging
upturn in food and energy prices, according to the association's
latest quarterly survey.
   1990 continues to be the year economists predict a recession
will arrive. Forty-three percent predict a downturn then, while 20
percent expect record peacetime expansion to end this year.
   That projection is slightly more optimistic than the group's
last quarterly forecast, issued in February, when 75 percent of
those surveyed expected a recession this year or next.
   In today's survey, 17 percent forecast a recession for 1991 and
20 percent said it would be 1992 or beyond before a downturn occurs.
   Recent government reports measuring the economy's performance so
far this year have suggested that growth is slowing in response to
a Federal Reserve campaign to engineer a so-called ``soft
landing,'' in which the economy slows enough to cool inflation
without slipping into a recession.
   But the forecasters warned that ``the real trick from an
economic policy perspective is preventing the forces that are
responsible for a major slowdown from degenerating into a fullblown
recession.''
   ``Soft landings have often appeared possible ... but inflation
has invariably worsened,'' the group said in a summary of its
findings. ``With the run-up in prices, government policy has been
forced to squeeze still harder and soft landings are lost in the
process.''
   The analysts' median forecast was that the gross national
product, the broadest measure of the economy's health, would grow
at an sluggish annual rate of 1.3 percent during the final three
quarters of 1989.
   For the year overall, the GNP was forecast to grow 2.8 percent,
down from 3.9 percent in 1988. Growth was expected to slow even
further in 1990, dropping to 1.8 percent.
   That prognosis is considerably more pessimistic than the Bush
administration, which is pinning its budget and deficit-reduction
plans on GNP growth of 3.2 percent this year and next.
   The government reported today that the GNP grew at a 4.3 percent
annual rate in the first three months of 1989, much slower than
previously thought. The pace was a lackluster 1.8 percent when a
statistical bounceback from last year's drought is excluded.
   Jay N. Woodworth, president of the business economists' group,
said the new GNP report reflects a downward revision in the amount
of inventories held by businesses, which bodes well for the economy.
   Woodworth said that were the group's economists polled today,
they ``might be just a trace more optimistic'' than they were when
the survey was conducted earlier this month.
   The overall slowing of the growth predicted in the forecasters'
survey was expected to reflect a sharp slackening in key sectors of
the economy:
   _Growth in industrial production was forecast at 3.2 percent in
1989 and 1.8 percent in 1990, down from 5.7 percent last year.
   _Construction of new homes and apartments was projected at 1.41
million units in 1989 and 1.44 million in 1990, compared with 1.49
in 1988.
   _Car and truck sales were forecast to slip to 14.9 million for
this year and next, down from 15.9 million in 1988.
   The economists also forecast that the slowdown in economic
growth would be accompanied by an increase in the unemployment rate
from a 15-year low of 5 percent in March, averaging 5.4 percent for
all of 1989 and 5.8 percent in 1990.
   Inflation, which advanced at a sharp 6.6 percent pace in the
first four months of 1989, was expected to peak midyear and then
become more moderate. Price increases were forecast to average 5.3
this year and 4.7 percent in 1990, up from 4.4 percent in 1988.
   Progress on the country's twin trade and budget deficits,
meanwhile, was expected to continue over the next two years, but at
a slower pace.
   The median trade deficit forecast was $112 billion for 1989 and
$100 billion in 1990, down from $119.8 billion in 1988. The slower
pace of improvement was linked to expectations of a drop in net
exports from $99.1 billion in 1988 to $90 billion this year and $76
billion in 1990.
   The budget deficit, which reached $155.1 billion in 1988, was
pegged at $160 billion for 1989 and $140 billion in 1990. That
would exceed the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction targets of $136
billion and $100 billion for this year and next, respectively.
   The economic slowdown also was evident in the economists'
forecast for personal consumption expenditures, which account for
two-thirds of overall economic activity. Consumer spending was
expected to grow by 2.5 percent this year and 1.9 percent in 1990,
down from 2.8 percent in 1988.
</TEXT>
