<SECOND>BC-Japan-Nintendo, Adv 29,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, May 29 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video Game Maker Surges to Head of the Toy Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK2 of May 24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KYOTO, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nintendo Co. Ltd. spent most of its 100-year
history producing playing cards with the cherry blossoms and cranes
of traditional Japan. Now its trump card is a modern computer game
that is the best-selling toy in the United States.
   The top Japanese maker of home computer video games reported
$1.7 billion in U.S. sales in 1988 alone and is believed to have at
least a 75 percent hold on the American market for the high-tech
toys.
   NEC Home Electronics, a U.S. subsidiary of Japanese computer and
telecommunications giant NEC, announced last Tuesday it has devised
a superior home video game system that will go on sale in the
United States this fall. But Nintendo executives say they're not
worried.
   For nearly a century, Nintendo was literally a house of cards _
until the 1970s, its main products were playing cards for a
traditonal Japanese game called hanafuda, as well as ones used in
Western card games.
   In the 1980s, the company of 690 employees nestled in a green
valley in Japan's ancient capital, Kyoto, began making toys with
audio visual features using micro-computers. Last year, only three
years after introducing its games in the United States, the
Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) was the No. 1-selling toy
there, according to Toy And Hobby World magazine.
   In late April, the company released its newest computer toy,
``Game Boy,'' a pocket version of the NES system, in Japan. It will
go on sale in the United States this summer. ``Game Boy'' has an
8-bit microprocesser that can be used with a variety of game
cartridges.
   Consumers _ and they are not only kids, Nintendo says _
apparently are ecstatic over games called ``Super Mario Brothers
2'' and ``Zelda II.'' They devoured ``The Legend Of Zelda'' last
year, and snapped up ``Mike Tyson's Punch-Out'' as soon as it hit
toy-store shelves.
   Nintendo spokesman Hiroshi Imanishi says the games originally
were developed from the premise that Japan's contemporary kids are
miniature versions of their workaholic parents.
   What with hectic schedules of school, after-school schools, and
other lessons, they required games they could play alone, indoors,
and within a short period of time.
   ``Considering all the pressures of children's schedules, we
searched for something they could play for 30 minutes to an hour
and walk away with a sense of excitement and satisfaction,''
Imanishi said.
   Those who follow the fortunes of video game makers say
Nintendo's success stems from its control over licensees who
develop many of the hundreds of games that can only be played on
Nintendo consoles.
   ``Nintendo was able to put out enough different titles (of
games) that it made people want to have the hardware,'' said Rodney
Harada, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in Tokyo. ``And Nintendo
controls so much of the hardware market that software developers
have to go through it.''
   In the United States, some of Nintendo's competitors are crying
foul over this arrangement. The company is the target of a $250
million lawsuit by Atari Corp., of Sunnyvale, Calif.
   The antitrust lawsuit, filed in February, alleges that Nintendo
forbids its developers to sell adaptations of their games to other
video game companies. Nintendo says the allegation is frivoulous.
   ``Atari has filed this lawsuit because of its lack of efforts to
expand its own market in computer games,'' said Imanishi.
   Meanwhile, Nintendo reported sales for the first half of its
fiscal year ending in February totaled 188 billion yen or $1.4
billion, up 47.1 percent over the same period the previous year.
   A recent survey of 1,000 publicly traded Japanese companies
showed that Nintendo stocks had risen more than 80 times in value
over the last 14 years _ by far the largest jump in value among any
of the companies surveyed.
   Its games also have been a phenonenon at home, where the video
system is called the ``Family Computer.'' As of March, however, the
United States surpassed Japan as the biggest consumer of its
consoles.
   More than 13 million consoles have sold in each country _ at
about $112 in Japan, where consumer prices are among the highest in
the world, and an average U.S. price of $80.
   Enough Nintendo game cartridges _ 160 million _ have been sold
in Japan to supply every Japanese man, woman and child _ with 40
million left over. About 75 million cartridges have been sold so
far in the United States.
   Last year, 97 percent of Nintendo's revenues came from sales of
computer games in both countries, and Imanishi says 95 percent of
the company's efforts are channeled into developing new games for
the console. But the company is not worried that its explosive
success could fizzle.
   ``We are creating entertainment, and that is a timeless concept
that doesn't change,'' Imanishi said.
   For the future, Nintendo is developing software that will allow
its computer console owners to trade stocks and do their banking at
home. They are also seeking ways to appeal to consumers beyond the
10- to 17-year-old males who are now their biggest customers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, May 29</NOTE>
