<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern Bjt   05-25 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, Bjt,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Plans To Turn Eastern Shuttle To Trump Shuttle In Two Weeks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be updated with details from Trump news conference; scheduled
to start at 3 p.m. EDT. LaserPhoto staffing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump plans to have Eastern
Airlines' Northeast shuttle flying as the renamed Trump Shuttle in
about two weeks, the head of the business said Thursday.
   Bruce Nobles, president of Trump Shuttle, said the new service
would be ``reliable, comfortable, efficient and clean.''
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland earlier Thursday
formally approved Eastern's $365 million shuttle sale to Trump.
Lifland had approved the sale in principle late Wednesday after
rival suitor America West Airlines withdrew its $415 million offer
after failing to arrange financing.
   ``I'm elated about it. I've been unemployed for three months;
it's a relief,'' said Bill Sanford, a striking Eastern pilot from
Marietta, Ga., who is one of 170 pilots tentatively hired by Trump
Shuttle.
   The deal for the New York-Washington-Boston shuttle should be
closed in about two weeks and the Trump Shuttle should be operating
soon after that, Nobles told reporters at the bankruptcy courthouse
in Manhattan.
   Nobles said Trump was aiming to capture 75 percent of the
shuttle market split with Pan Am Corp. by the first year of
operation, but he called that goal ``a little ambitious.''
   The shuttle is used mainly by business travelers and was
Eastern's only consistently profitable operation before the March 4
strike by its Machinists, which was joined by its pilots and flight
attendants unions. Because of the walkout, it lost many passengers
to Pan Am's rival shuttle.
   Trump has pledged to spend ``tremendous amounts of money'' to
upgrade the shuttle, whose fleet of 21 aging, blue-and-silver
Boeing 727s will be redecorated and emblazoned with red, black and
gold stripes and Trump's name on the tail.
   Trump, who owns several casino-hotels in Atlantic City, N.J.,
also operates a helicopter service between New York and that resort
city and has indicated an interest in routing the shuttle there.
   Miami-based Eastern initially agreed to sell the shuttle to
Trump last October. The deal was delayed by court challenges from
Eastern's unions and the need for bankruptcy court approval.
   Any Eastern asset sales must be approved by the court. Eastern
filed for bankruptcy protection from its creditors March 9.
   Eastern's unions wanted the airline sold as a single entity. But
Texas Air decided to sell the shuttle and about $1.4 billion in
other Eastern assets separately, as part of a plan to rebuild as a
smaller carrier.
   Richard Seltzer, an attorney for the pilots union, said Thursday
the unions were happy with Trump's ownership of the shuttle. He
also said they were continuing discussions with investor groups
that have submitted formal bids for all of Eastern, including
groups headed by former Piedmont Airlines chairman William Howard
and by Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie.
   America West, an aggressive Phoenix-based regional carrier, had
offered $415 million for the shuttle and $336 million for 10 Boeing
757s. Alternatively, America West offered to buy only the shuttle's
gates and landing slots at the three airports for $375 million.
   Lorenzo and Trump renegotiated their original contract in April,
after the strike caused many Eastern shuttle passengers to defect
to the Pan Am Corp. shuttle. The new agreement gave Trump four four
additional 727s for the same price.
   Trump has recognized Eastern's unions as representatives for
employees of his shuttle, while America West said it would not
employ Eastern workers if it bought the shuttle.
   Trump has signed labor contracts with pilots and flight
attendants, but not with members of the Machinists union. Nobles
said the Machinists would be able to work for the Trump Shuttle
initially without a contract.
</TEXT>
