<FIRST>u f AM-Salomon-SEC 1stLd-Writethru   05-25 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salomon-SEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Censures Salomon For Short-Selling During '87 Market Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 19th graf to CLARIFY that rule allows short sales when
stock price is unchanged as well as higher.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Brothers Inc. on Thursday became the
first investment firm sanctioned by the government for violating
laws governing short-selling during the 1987 stock market crash.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Salomon agreed to be
censured to settle Securities and Exchange Commission allegations
regarding its short sales, which are a type of speculation aimed at
profiting from market declines.
   Salomon also agreed to establish procedures to prevent future
short-selling violations, said the SEC, which further alleged
Salomon ``willfully'' failed to promptly turn over its books for
inspection. Salomon will not pay a fine.
   Salomon spokesman Robert Baker said the firm ``did not refuse to
produce documents.'' While Salomon ``had difficulty responding as
quickly as the SEC wanted ...the SEC was not denied a single
document.''
   Many Wall Streeters have said privately that short-selling
aggravated the spectacular drop in stock prices on Oct. 19, 1987,
when the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 508 points. But
observers noted the Salomon short sales cited by the SEC were a
drop in the bucket and did not effect events that day.
   Short-selling is the sale of borrowed stock by investors who
believe the price of a stock will decline and that they will be
able to profit by repaying their borrowings with cheaper shares.
Short sale rules prohibit the strategy when a stock price already
is falling.
   ``I view this as a signal to the securities industry that they
had better start to improve their compliance ... to our
examinations,'' said Lawrence Iason, the SEC's New York regional
administrator. ``If they don't, penalities in the future will be
more severe.''
   The SEC stated Salomon made 70 short sales for its own account
throughout the Black Monday crash. The sales involved 300,000
shares of stock in 19 New York Stock Exchange companies.
   Iason could not comment on how much Salomon profited from the
sales. The 19 companies whose stocks were involved weren't
identified.
   Salomon's Baker said there was ``no suggestion that any Salomon
Brothers trader intentionally engaged in a transaction contrary to
the short-sale rule or that any ... customer was disadvantaged in
any way.''
   The SEC said the shares Salomon sold short carried a market
value of $12.5 million. Baker said the firm traded $2.5 billion in
securities on Black Monday.
   On Wall Street, market players shrugged off the SEC action.
   ``When it's over, we'll probably find out that everybody did it.
It's not a big conspiracy, it's that everybody was having their
heads handed to them,'' said James Cramer, president of the money
management firm Cramer &amp; Co.
   Iason could not comment on whether other firms were being
investigated for similar violations.
   James Kirby, chairman of Los Angeles-based Capital Guardian
Trust and a member of the presidential Brady Commission that
studied the crash, said it was very difficult to identify short
sales on Black Monday.
   ``I wouldn't assign it a high priority in terms of its
contribution to an unbelievable event. It was one of several
things,'' he said.
   Short selling was widely abused after the Crash of 1929 by
speculators who would gang up on a target company, spreading lies
about it to drive down the stock price.
   Such abuses led the NYSE to implement the short-sale rule, which
theoretically prevents short sellers from intentionally depressing
a stock price.
   Under the rule, a short sale may be executed only in instances
when the previous sale raised the stock's price or left it
unchanged.
   Shortly after Black Monday, the SEC and the NYSE began probing
allegations that improper short selling may have contributed to the
crash, though ultimately they reached no determination.
   While the short-selling allegations are serious, it is
particularly unusual for the SEC to admonish a securities firm for
failing to respond quickly to its investigation. Some speculated
the SEC may have been more concerned about that than about
Salomon's trading violations.
   To prevent further abuses, Salomon agreed that semi-annual
reviews of its short-sale compliance procedures be conducted by a
senior internal auditor and an independent certified public
accounting form or outside legal counsel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
