<FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SEC-Ruderman     05-25 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Ruderman,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rudy Ruderman, SEC Settle Civil Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Business Week radio broadcaster Seymour
G. ``Rudy'' Ruderman has agreed to pay the Securities and Exchange
Commission more than $40,000 to settle a civil suit stemming from
his use of nonpublic information to make investments, the
commission said Thursday.
   The 62-year-old financial journalist currently is serving a
six-month jail term for illegal stock market trades.
   Ruderman pleaded guilty last year to two counts of mail fraud
after he was fired by Business Week for trading on information
learned from prepublication copies of the magazine's ``Inside Wall
Street'' column.
   Lawrence Iason, regional administrator of the New York office of
the SEC, said Ruderman agreed to pay $20,734.89 ``representing his
gross illegal trading profits,'' and a like amount in civil
penalities and fines.
   Under the agreement reached in April and approved Wednesday by
the SEC, the U.S. district court in Manhattan will set up a bank
account to repay investors who lost money because of Ruderman's
illegal trades.
   Ruderman, a resident of Scarsdale and a widely known veteran
financial news broadcaster, had produced a syndicated stock-market
report since 1981 as Business Week's broadcast editor.
   Manhattan U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward sentenced Ruderman
on April 5 to six months in jail, fined him $5,000 and placed him
on probation for three years after his release from jail.
</TEXT>
