<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Prices Pull Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices finished lower Thursday
at the end of a volatile session dominated by speculation about the
outcome of an OPEC meeting next month.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, ended at
$19.48 a 42-gallon barrel, off 18 cents, following a rise of 62
cents on Wednesday.
   Prices for crude oil contracts for delivery after July also fell.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale home
heating oil for delivery in June slid 0.56 cent to 49.05 cents a
gallon after rising 2.11 cents in the prior session. The June
contract for unleaded gasoline fell 0.22 cent to 66.61 cents a
gallon following Wednesday's gain of 2.59 cents.
   Analysts said gas and other petroleum futures prices rallied
early when report of a gasoline pipeline explosion in San
Bernardino, Calif. raised speculation about a possible supply
disruption.
   But Mary L. Haskins, assistant vice president at Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., said the buyers bailed out after awhile, possibly
because they were reluctant to accumulate significant holdings
ahead of the meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries that begins in Vienna on June 5.
   There has been speculation that the 13-nation cartel may decide
to boost their output limits.
