<FIRST>r f AM-ConstructionContracting     05-25 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Contracting,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Construction Contracting Spurts in April</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction contracts surged by 9 percent in
April, reflecting a large increase in new housing construction, an
industry survey reported Thursday.
   The value of newly started construction contracts increased to
an annual rate of $256.8 billion last month, up from $236.1 billion
in March, the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services
Co. reported.
   Residential building contracts rose 16 percent to an annual rate
of $126.1 billion, while nonresidential building contracts _ which
includes institutional, commercial and industrial building _
increased 5 percent to $82.2 billion.
   Contracts for nonbuilding construction, which comprises public
works and utilities, were little changed from March's performance,
with an annual rate of $48.5 billion.
   Overall construction contracting for the first four months of
the year has been off 2 percent, to an unadjusted total of $75.68
billion from $77.28 billion a year earlier.
   Much of the decrease was attributed to cutbacks in construction
of office and apartment buildings, partly because of higher
interest rates that slowed borrowing demand.
   ``It remains to be seen whether April's surprising improvement
will have staying power,'' said George A. Christie, F.W. Dodge's
chief economist, ``but it does show that the construction sector so
far is taking this year's higher interest rates in stride instead
of collapsing into a downward spiral.''
</TEXT>
