<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market stalled Thursday in a mixed
response to the newest data on the state of the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 1.28 to 2,482.59.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
839 up, 630 down and 515 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 154.47 million
shares, down from 178.60 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 187.29 million shares.
   The Commerce Department said the nation's gross national product
grew at a 4.3 percent annual rate, after adjustment for inflation,
in the first quarter of the year, down from a previous estimate of
5.5 percent.
   That initially appeared to be a plus for stocks, by reinforcing
evidence that the economy was slowing in response to the Federal
Reserve's campaign to restrain inflationary pressures.
   But accompanying figures showed no downward revision of the pace
of inflation over the January-March period.
   And analysts said the figures on growth got a new interpretation
on close inspection when traders saw that much of the drop stemmed
from a reduction in inventories.
   Tight inventories are more often than not a forerunner of strong
economic activity, since they create a situation where new orders
translate quickly into a need for production.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Philip Morris rose 2| to 140;
Eastman Kodak gained [ to 44~; General Electric dropped ~ to 52},
and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was down \ at 35\.
   Takeover rumors and speculation sparked active trading in such
issues as Maytag, up 2[ at 23{, and Syntex, up 1\ at 47}.
   Del Webb Corp. rose ~ to 13~ on word of the cancellation of a
planned offering of $50 million in convertible debentures. The
company cited market conditions.
   The debentures would have had the potential to increase the
number of claims on the company's earnings.
   Analysts noted some tentative buying in depressed
precious-metals stocks. ASA Ltd. rose { to 39| and Hecla Mining \
to 12[.
   LIN Broadcasting climbed 4} to 101 in the over-the-counter
market. The company announced plans to spin off a new subsidiary
that will own seven of its television stations.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $2.44 billion, or 0.08
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .08 to 178.05.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose .45 to 366.50, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up .03 at 319.17.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
1.40 to 442.89. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 352.65, up 1.65.
