<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-25 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in nervous trading Thursday,
reflecting rounds of central bank intervention and fears of
interest rate hikes abroad.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York said the
late bid for a troy ounce of gold was $365.90, compared with
$362.40 late Wednesday.
   Traders were not surprised by the currency's retreat after its
recent rise. ``Everyone was looking for a correction phase to
begin, and it's begun,'' said Jim McGroarty, a senior vice
president at Greenwich Capital Markets Inc. in Greenwich, Conn.
   ``The question is how far (down) do we go?'' he said.
   Market strategists expect the dollar-selling to continue as
speculators protect themselves against any hike in European
interest rates over the long Memorial Day weekend, which could
cause the dollar to fall.
   A day after British interest rates moved higher, the Swiss
National Bank on Thursday announced the introduction of a flexible
Lombard rate policy. Dealers said that this daily adjustment of the
Lombard rate, which acts as a ceiling for Swiss interest rates, was
seen as a prelude to a rate increase.
   The Lombard rate is what the central bank charges commercial
banks for supplemental borrowings in which securities are used as
collateral.
   ``The Swiss announcement had a psychological impact on the
market after the U.K. rate rise and the continued threat of rate
increases in Japan and West Germany,'' said Joe Leitch, a foreign
exchange director at Salomon Brothers International in London.
   The Federal Reserve, the Bank of Canada and several European
central banks intervened against the dollar shortly after the
government announced a downward revision in the nation's gross
national product for the first quarter to 4.3 percent from a 5.5
percent estimate.
   Overall, however, ``intervention hasn't been all that
effective,'' said Kevin Lawrie, a vice president at the Bank of
Boston. Many who are still bullish on dollar note that it is the
central bank and not investors who are doing the selling.
   ``We have some room to come off a little further still, but next
week the dollar should resume its upward momentum,'' Lawrie said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 142.35 Japanese yen, down 0.65
yen from the 19-month high posted Wednesday. Later in London, the
dollar fell further to 142.05 yen. In New York, the dollar finished
at 141.23 yen, down from 142.78 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5815 from $1.5695 late
Wednesday. In New York it cost $1.5910 to buy one pound, more
expensive than Wednesday's $1.5700.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday included: 1.9800 West German marks, down from 2.0137;
1.7425 Swiss francs, down from 1.7855; 6.7035 French francs, down
from 6.8225; 1,434.50 Italian lire, down from 1,459.00, and 1.2068
Canadian dollars, down from 1.2085.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Wednesday
included: 1.9965 West German marks, down from 2.0115; 1.7650 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7887; 6.7675 French francs, down from 6.8250;
2.2480 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2670; 1,444.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,455.75, and 1.2105 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1985.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $367.00 a troy ounce, from $364.50 on Wednesday.
   Gold was trading in London at a late bid price of $364.75 a troy
ounce, up from $362.75 late Wednesday. In Zurich it rose to $364.25
from $362.60. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.31 to $364.31.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery
finished at $5.267 a troy ounce, up from $5.178 on Wednesday. In
London, silver rose to a bid price of $5.26 a troy ounce, from
$5.18 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
