<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Honda     05-25 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Honda,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honda Motor's Profits Hurt By Drop in Foreign Exchange Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda Motor Co. Thursday reported its
fourth-quarter earnings fell 26.3 percent and its annual profit
slid 2.9 percent, attributing the declines to less favorable
currency-exchange values.
   The Tokyo-based automobile manufacturer said after-tax income
totaled 24.3 billion yen ($184 million) in the three months ended
March 31, down from 33 billion yen a year earlier.
   Net income per American share, which each represent 10 shares of
Honda common stock, came to $1.87 in the fourth quarter, down from
$2.54 in the prior year's final quarter.
   Quarterly sales were 886.8 billion yen ($6.7 billion) compared
to 825.3 billion yen a year earlier.
   Honda's annual profit totaled 97.2 billion yen ($737 million)
down from 100.2 billion yen the previous year.
   Earnings per American share were $7.46 last year vs. $7.54 a
year earlier.
   Sales for the full year were 3.49 trillion yen ($26.4 billion)
in the year ended March 31, up 7.9 percent from 3.23 trillion yen a
year before. Higher sales of cars in Japan and North America
boosted the figures.
   The latest results are Honda's first since the company switched
its fiscal year to end on March 31 rather than the last day of
February. Comparative figures given for the report, thus, represent
a hypothetical towelve-month period.
   Honda said a drop in the gains on foreign exchange conversions
led to deterioration in its profit.
