<FIRST>r f AM-HollyFarms     05-25 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Sets Date For Stockholder Eligibility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holders of stock in the Holly Farms Corp.
at the close of the business day June 6 will be eligible to vote on
a proposed merger with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb., Holly Farms
said Thursday.
   A shareholders meeting for the vote is expected before the end
of July, Holly Farms said in a statement.
   The propoed merger, announced by Holly and ConAgra on May 21, is
a second attempt to join the two companies. Tyson Foods Inc. of
Springdale, Ark., continues its efforts, meanwhile, to take over
Holly Farms.
   Tyson has asked a Chancery Court in Delaware, where Holly Farms
is incorporated, to block the merger attempt.
   To be accomplished through a stock swap worth $1.3 billion, the
ConAgra-Holly merger would require approval of stockholders of both
companies.
   Holly shareholders decided April 17 to reject an earlier merger
attempt, valued at $1 billion. ConAgra shareholders approved it.
   Tyson Foods, which began the bidding war for Holly Farms last
October, has offered the company's stockholders $63.50 a share cash
for their stock. That offer is worth about $1.1 billion.
   Tyson is the nation's largest poultry processor while Holly
Farms is a diversified company heavily involved in fresh fryer
sales. ConAgra is a diversified food and agricultural services
company.
</TEXT>
