<FIRST>u f AM-AlleghenyInternational     05-25 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drops Merger Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. called off a
merger agreement Thursday that was to be the cornerstone of efforts
to emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
   The $747 million deal with Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc., a
New York investment banking firm, began unraveling last week when
Allegheny International disclosed its 1989 earnings would be less
than anticipated, officials said.
   The deal was to be presented for approval Thursday in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court.
   Instead, Allegheny International proposed a plan that would lift
its key Sunbeam Corp. subsidiary out of bankruptcy separately
without an outside buyer. Creditors of the parent company would be
repaid with funds left over after Sunbeam is reorganized.
   Bruce McCullough, Allegheny International's lead bankruptcy
attorney, told U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Joseph L. Cosetti the
operating companies could emerge from Chapter 11 in three to four
months. He said the plan would be easy to finance and no vote by
Sunbeam creditors would be required because all would be fully
repaid.
   As part of the plan, Chief Executive Officer Oliver S. Travers
Jr. and other top managers at the parent company would be replaced,
as major creditors have demanded.
   But Robert Sable, attorney for Allegheny International's
unsecured creditors, said his group and the company's bank lenders
would oppose a reorganization involving only Sunbeam.
   The DLJ contract, which was struck in February, included a
clause allowing the banking firm to terminate the agreement if
Allegheny International failed to come within 95 percent of its
operating goals at any time from February to September, when its
fiscal year ends, officials said.
   The merger agreement required Allegheny International's domestic
operating companies to make an operating profit this fiscal year of
at least $66.5 million. But earnings projections now total only $61
million to $62 million, McCullough said.
   Allegheny International refused to accept the lower price of
$687 million DLJ offered because of the shortfall, officials said.
   Nicholas J. Sakallariadis, Allegheny International's investment
banking adviser, told reporters the poor projections were a
``complete shock.'' The most serious problems appeared to be at
Sunbeam-Oster's iron business, he said.
   Sakallariadis also said sales apparently were hurt when Black &amp;
Decker Corp., which had a brief agreement earlier this year to
acquire Sunbeam-Oster, indicated the Sunbeam and Oster lines would
be discontinued.
   The break between Allegheny International and DLJ was the
second. In January, Allegheny International called a halt to the
deal when it learned DLJ had secretly agreed to sell two divisions
to a Los Angeles financier and a New York merchant banking group.
   Allegheny Internationl then devised its own reorganization plan
backed by equity holders and agreed to sell Sunbeam-Oster to Black
&amp; Decker, its main competitor. But that plan was quickly shelved.
   Sunbeam Corp. is comprised of Allegheny International's major
operating units, including Almet-Lawnlite Inc., which manufactures
patio furniture; Oster-Sunbeam Appliance Co., which manufactures
small appliances; Northern Electric Co., which makes electric
blankets and heating pads; and Sunbeam Leisure Products Co., which
makes barbecue grills.
</TEXT>
