<FIRST>u f AM-PanAm-NorthwestStory     05-25 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am-Northwest Story,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Subpoenaed on Airline Bid Story</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury Thursday subpoenaed Dow
Jones &amp; Co. for stories pertaining to a statement issued Tuesday by
a man who claimed to be preparing an offer to acquire NWA Inc. and
Pan Am Corp. simultaneously.
   The New York Stock Exchange temporarily halted trading in shares
of Pan Am and NWA on Tuesday after another market news service
indicated it was planning a story about the statement, which both
companies have said they do not take seriously.
   Dow Jones News Service, which is owned by Dow Jones &amp; Co.,
reported it was subpoenaed in Newark for all documents referring or
relating to Michael Stern, who issued the statement about the
potential bid.
   An attorney for Dow Jones who spoke on condition of anonymity
said the subpoena later was amended to include only a copy of the
story the news service issued about the trading halt and reason for
it.
   In the statement issued Tuesday to several news agencies in New
York, including The Associated Press, Stern identified himself as
chairman of Trans Global Holdings Inc. and said the company was in
the final stages of forming an investor group to buy the airlines.
   NWA, the parent of Northwest Airlines, has solicited potential
buyers since receiving a $2.7 billion takeover offer from investor
Marvin Davis. Several companies and investor groups, including Pan
Am, have expressed interest in acquiring NWA.
   The New York exchange halted trading in Pan Am and NWA after
Reuters news service alerted the exchange it was about to run a
story about the bid.
   In interviews, Stern refused to provide information to
substantiate his claims and an exchange spokeswoman later termed
his news release as appearing ``somewhat less than credible.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Diane Weeks declined to comment on the
subpoena or why it was issued in Newark.
   A spokesman for Reuters, Michael Reilly, did not immediately
return a telephone message at his home.
   Rich Torrenzano, a New York Stock Exchange spokesman, said that
as of Thursday the exchange had not been subpoenaed or asked for
similar information by authorities.
   It was not known immediately whether any other subpoenaes were
issued.
</TEXT>
